n=&quot;false&quot;    UnhideWhenUsed=&quot;false&quot; Name=&quot;Colorful Grid Accent 6&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;19&quot; SemiHidden=&quot;false&quot;    UnhideWhenUsed=&quot;false&quot; QFormat=&quot;true&quot; Name=&quot;Subtle Emphasis&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;21&quot; SemiHidden=&quot;false&quot;    UnhideWhenUsed=&quot;false&quot; QFormat=&quot;true&quot; Name=&quot;Intense Emphasis&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;31&quot; SemiHidden=&quot;false&quot;    UnhideWhenUsed=&quot;false&quot; QFormat=&quot;true&quot; Name=&quot;Subtle Reference&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;32&quot; SemiHidden=&quot;false&quot;    UnhideWhenUsed=&quot;false&quot; QFormat=&quot;true&quot; Name=&quot;Intense Reference&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;33&quot; SemiHidden=&quot;false&quot;    UnhideWhenUsed=&quot;false&quot; QFormat=&quot;true&quot; Name=&quot;Book Title&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;37&quot; Name=&quot;Bibliography&quot; /&gt; &lt;w:LsdException Locked=&quot;false&quot; Priority=&quot;39&quot; QFormat=&quot;true&quot; Name=&quot;TOC Heading&quot; /&gt; &lt;/w:LatentStyles&gt; &lt;/xml&gt;&lt;![endif]--&gt;&lt;!--[if gte mso 10]&gt; &lt;mce:style&gt;&lt;!   /* Style Definitions */  table.MsoNormalTable 	{mso-style-name:&quot;Table Normal&quot;; 	mso-tstyle-rowband-size:0; 	mso-tstyle-colband-size:0; 	mso-style-noshow:yes; 	mso-style-priority:99; 	mso-style-qformat:yes; 	mso-style-parent:&quot;&quot;; 	mso-padding-alt:0cm 5.4pt 0cm 5.4pt; 	mso-para-margin:0cm; 	mso-para-margin-bottom:.0001pt; 	mso-pagination:widow-orphan; 	font-size:10.0pt; 	font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;} --&gt; &lt;!--[endif] --&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;float: left; border: 0; margin: 5px;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/1058605_60297588 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;223&quot; width=&quot;311&quot; /&gt;Joel (yo-el)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;The name Joel like many names is made from two elements. The first ‘Yoe’ is an abbreviation of the name of Yahweh and ‘el’ is the abbreviated form of Elohim which means God. So Joel means ‘Yahweh is God’ or ‘The Lord is God’.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;The name Joel in the Bible is very popular and there were many men with that name. The prophet Joel however is mentioned in the book bearing his name and also in Acts. To learn what Joel is about you should read the &lt;strong style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-style: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;book of Joel&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; which is only three chapters long, and he is mentioned once more in &lt;strong style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-style: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;Acts 2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;The Bible gives precious little information about the prophet Joel as an individual; we know his father’s name was Pethuel but that’s all the information there is about his family. In chapters &lt;strong style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-style: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;1 &amp;amp; 2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Joel demonstrates great passion for the Temple however he also demonstrates familiarity with an agricultural life so this would suggest he wasn’t a Levite or a Priest. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;There are some who think he may be of the Tribe of Reuben but there is a hint which suggests he may have lived close to Jerusalem and therefore may have been of the Tribe of Judah. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;The historical setting of Joel was that Tyre, Sidon and Philistia had made numerous military raids into Judah causing great disruption and fear; they had experienced an extended drought and massive invasions of locusts that had destroyed every last vestige of vegetation from the land and they were suffering under severe economic collapse leaving the Southern Kingdom seriously weak and vulnerable. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;The physical destruction and degradation of the land gave Joel a prophetic illustration to communicate to his people about God’s judgement against sin; and in particular God’s future judgement during the ‘Day of the Lord’. In fact Joel’s prophecy about the ‘Day of the Lord’ would make the historical destruction of Judah during his day pale by comparison. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;Joel doesn’t mention any specific sins committed by the people and he doesn’t point out their idolatry because the people were actually living under the judgement of God at that time because of their sin; what Joel does command the people however is that their repentance be from the heart and not merely be an outward show of regret at being caught in their sin. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;mso-bidi-font-style: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica; color: red;&quot;&gt;Joel 2:12-13, ‘”Yet even now,” declares the Lord, “Return to Me with all your heart, and with fasting, weeping and mourning; and rend your heart and not your garments.” Now return to the Lord your God, for He is gracious and compassionate, slow to anger, abounding in lovingkindness and relenting of evil.’&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; mso-ascii-font-family: Calibri; mso-ascii-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-hansi-font-family: Calibri; mso-hansi-theme-font: minor-latin; mso-bidi-font-family: Helvetica;&quot;&gt;Despite the fact that Joel was written in the late ninth century BC (approx) this message of a call to heartfel",2012-10-08 23:07:38,mworby
7863,Home Group - Elisha Pt 2,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/954634_94521374 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;213&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;Elisha Pt 2 (El-e-sha)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha’s story can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 19, 2 Kings, chapter 2 through to chapter 13.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;As a quick recap from last week, Elisha means ‘God is Salvation’ or ‘My God is Salvation’ and he was the &lt;em&gt;‘talmid’&lt;/em&gt; or student or disciple or apprentice of the prophet Elijah. Elisha was a faithful and committed student who learned well from his mentor and never shied away from what he was called to do. He was respectful and honouring to Elijah and refused to leave his side, right up to the very moment that God supernaturally transported Elijah to heaven by a whirlwind in a fiery horse and chariot.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha had one request of his mentor before he was taken away and that was to receive a double portion of his spirit. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:9)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Elisha wasn’t asking for Elijah’s actual ‘spirit’ but rather the spiritual inheritance and legacy of his prophetic gifting. He wanted to be just like his mentor, but because he loved Elijah like a father, he was asking for the blessing of a first born son; again not with a physical inheritance in mind, but a spiritual one. A spiritual inheritance for a spiritual son.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah promised that if Elisha actually saw him taken away by God, he would be granted his request, and yes, Elisha actually saw it all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha twice destroyed the physical attachments of his past – the oxen and plough he used to earn his living with and his outer clothing that designated his spiritual position – such was his determination to walk in the path God had chosen for him. He wanted no means of turning back to what was his past.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah his mentor was a powerful man of God and performed eight major miracles through the power of God. Elisha’s double portion sees him also become a very powerful man of God and the record of his life shows sixteen major miracles thus proving the double portion granted to him by God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;These miraculous events were:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;ol start=&quot;1&quot;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He parted the Jordan River &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings      2:13-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He cursed the teenagers who were mocking him &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:23-25)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He healed the poisoned waters of Jericho &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2      Kings 2:19-22)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He filled the widows vessels with oil &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(2      Kin&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;gs 4:1-27)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The miracle birth of a son by the Shunemite woman &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:8-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He raised from the dead the son of the Shunemite woman &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:18-37)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He healed the poisonous stew &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2      Kings 4:38-44)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He fed 100 men with a small amount of food as well as leftovers      &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:42-44)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He healed Naaman the Syrian &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2      Kings 5:1-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He punished Gehazi with leprosy &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2      Kings 5:15-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He caused the sunken iron axe head to float on the water &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:1-7)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He caused the trenches on the battlefield to flood &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 3:1-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He gave special insight to the king’s messenger &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:16-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He blinded the Aramean army &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2      Kings 6:8-18)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He restored the sight of the Aramean army &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2      Kings 6:19-20)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A dead man was raised to life after his body was thrown onto Elisha’s      grave &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 13:20-21)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What’s interesting is that there are some similarities in the miracles done by both Elijah and Elisha.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah parted the Jordan River      and Elisha parted the Jordan River. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:8,      13-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah miraculously caused the      flour and oil of a widow not to run out until the drought ended and Elisha      caused the oil of a widow not to run out until all the empty vessels she      could get her hands on were filled to the brim. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1      Kings 17:9-16, 2 Kings 4:1-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah raised a young boy from      the dead and Elisha raised a young boy from the dead. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1      Kings 17:17-24, 2 Kings 4:18-37)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah had power over the      elements of nature by causing drought and Elisha had power over the      elements of nature by causing a flood without rain. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1      Kings 17:1, 2 Kings 3:1-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There is another aspect to Elisha’s character that is worth looking at; he was no respecter of persons, he didn’t allow a person’s position, wealth or social standing to influence him. This is seen when king Jehoram (son of Ahab) approached king Jehoshaphat and the king of Edom to go with him to battle against Moab. Jehoshaphat was a godly man and wanted to receive a word of direction from God through one of His prophets. So Jehoram sent for Elisha.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 3:11-14, ‘But Jehoshaphat said, “Is there not a prophet of the Lord here, that we may inquire of the Lord by him?” And one of the king of Israel’s servants answered and said, “Elisha the son of Shaphat is here, who used to pour water on the hands of Elijah.” Jehoshaphat said, “The word of the Lord is with him.” So the king of Israel and Jehoshaphat and the king of Edom went down to him. Now Elisha said to the king of Israel, “What do I have to do with you? Go to the prophets of your father and to the prophets of your mother.” And the king of Israel said to him, “No, for the Lord has called these three kings together to give them into the hand of Moab.” Elisha said, “As the Lord of hosts lives, before whom I stand, were it not that I regard the presence of Jehoshaphat the king of Judah, I would not look at you nor see you.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha didn’t give a toss that he was standing before royalty or that he was humiliating his king in front of two other monarchs. He even went so far as to compare his own wicked king with the righteous king Jehoshaphat. He didn’t even care that his insult against his king could have eventuated with his own execution. Elisha was faithful to the call of God and to truth and he had no time for pandering to wicked men in order to gain influence or to protect his own life - no matter who they were.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is also seen in his ‘sort-of’ encounter with Naaman the Syrian, I say ‘sort-of’ because he never actually met Naaman.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Naaman was the captain of the army of the king of Aram, he was &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘highly respected because by him the Lord had given victory to Aram.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; That’s very interesting isn’t it? God – Jehovah – the God of the Jews – had given victory to Aram, a pagan nation and He used Naaman, a pagan army captain to do it...and what’s more, Naaman and his king recognised that Jehovah was giving them victory over their enemies. They worshipped false gods but they knew their victories came through Jehovah. It’s hard to understand why they weren’t devoted to the One True God or why this didn’t stop them from going to war against Israel at a later date. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 5:1) &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Naaman was a leper and he had a young Jewish servant girl that obviously cared for her masters because she knew that if Naaman could get to Elisha the prophet in Israel he would be healed. In ancient times leprosy was a death sentence. Naaman heard about this prophet and spoke to his king and got permission to travel to Israel to seek a miraculous healing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He makes his way to Elisha with great pomp and ceremony with elaborate and expensive gifts and he has great expectations of how he would be healed. Elisha wasn’t in the least bit impressed with him, his stature, his standing with royalty or his wealth, in fact Elisha didn’t even walk out and meet the man, he simply sent a messenger to tell the Syrian captain to go away and wash himself seven times in the Jordan River and Naaman was furious at being treated like a nobody.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 5:11-12, ‘But Naaman was furious and went away and said, “Behold, I thought he would surely come out to me and stand and call on the name of the Lord his God and wave his hand over the place and cure the leper. Are not Abanah and Pharpar, the rivers of Damascus better than all the waters of Israel? Could I not wash in them and be clean?” So he turned and went away in a rage.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Of course, the story goes on to show that one of Naaman’s servants said that what he had been instructed to do was an easy thing so just go and do it. He did and was completely healed and restored.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There’s one more thing that it would be good to look at that happened during the life of Elisha. The king of Aram decided to go to war against Israel and he would make a decision to go to such and such a place to attack the king of Israel. Each time he did, the king of Israel would go via a different place and every time the king of Aram’s plans would be thwarted. He got so frustrated he was sure that one of his own people was leaking his plans to his enemies. One of his servants however reminded him about Elisha the prophet (who had healed Naaman his captain of leprosy) who was receiving information from God about the king of Aram’s plans and he would promptly warn his own king about what was about to happen. The king of Israel would simply avoid the danger zones.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The king of Aram was so enraged he sent his entire army to Dothan to capture Elisha; (any gratitude he may have felt toward Elisha for healing Naaman was gone...and since we never hear of Naaman again perhaps he quit the army to serve the God who healed him...that's only speculation but it's interesting to consider), they travelled at night and surrounded the city that Elisha lived in. Elisha's servant woke in the morning and was absolutely terrified at what he saw and went into a panic to Elisha and said, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Alas my master! What shall we do?”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Elisha remained very calm because he knew that God was with them. He calmly responded by saying, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Do not fear, for those who are with us are more than those who are with them.” Then Elisha prayed and said, “O Lord, I pray, open his eyes that he may see.” And the Lord opened the servant’s eyes and he saw; and behold, the mountain was full of horses and chariots of fire all around Elisha.’ (2 Kings 6:15-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;How did Elisha know what was surrounding them? He’d already seen what the horses and chariots of Israel looked like when he saw his mentor Elijah taken into heaven in one. Elisha didn’t need physical security because his confidence was in his God who wasn’t in the least bit limited by physicality. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:11-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Since May 14, 1948 Israel has been attacked seven times by surrounding nations resulting in major wars - this is not including uprisings, smaller attacks and terrorist bombings. One of them was the Yom Kippur war which took place in October 1973. I once read a book written by Lance Lambert called ‘The Battle For Israel’ which was written in 1979, and in it he recorded incredible miracles that took place during this war, a war that should for all intents and purposes have ended with the destruction of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In this book, Lambert records the testimonies of invading foreign forces in the desert who fled from their tanks leaving their weapons and ammunition behind. When asked why they fled, they said they ran for their lives before the massive army in white on the horizon that was surrounding them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Psalm 121, ‘I will lift up my eyes to the mountains; from where shall my help come? My help comes from the Lord, who made heaven and earth. He will not allow your foot to slip; He who keeps you will not slumber. Behold, He who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep. The Lord is your keeper; the Lord is your shade on your right hand. The sun will not smite you by day, nor the moon by night. The Lord will protect you from all evil; He will keep your soul. The Lord will guard your going out and your coming in from this time forth and forever.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha knew his God and he knew God wouldn’t fail him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What we see is not as important as WHO we know!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;br /&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-wink.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Wink&quot; title=&quot;Wink&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-10-03 05:21:14,mworby
7786,Home Group - Elisha Pt 1,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/575231_55762839 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;191&quot; width=&quot;254&quot; /&gt;Elisha Part 1 (El-e-sha)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha is made up of two elements; ‘El’ which is the common abbreviation of Elohim which means God. The second element, ‘yasha’ means to be saved or delivered. So Elisha’s name means ‘God is Salvation’, ‘My God is Salvation’, ‘God the Saviour’ or ‘The Salvation of my God.’&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha is a great name and is similar to other names formed from the same verb ‘yasha’ which also mean salvation; names like Joshua, Yeshua, Hosea, Isaiah...these are also related to the word Hosanna which means ‘Save’ or ‘Bring about Salvation.’&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha’s story can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1Kings 19, 2 Kings chapter 2 right through to chapter 13. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God told Elijah to choose Elisha to be his successor and when Elijah came upon Elisha he was ploughing his family fields with twelve pair of oxen. Twenty four in total...that’s a lot of oxen!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The sheer number of oxen reveals that Elisha was from a very wealthy family, they had hired help to work with the sons of the family and Elisha was leading the twelfth pair and as Elijah approached the property and the teams working in the field he waited for Elisha to pass him and as he did he threw his mantle or cloak over him. Elijah’s cloak or mantle was what identified him as a prophet of God and when he placed it over Elisha he was signifying that Elisha had been chosen to not only be a prophet unto the Lord, but that he was to specifically be Elijah’s successor. He was handpicked to be Elijah’s ‘talmid’ – his student, pupil; and Elijah would disciple him, train him, apprentice him to become a man who knew and loved the Word of God and would be committed to speaking God’s very words to the people of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha knew immediately what the significance was behind this action. Being trained by a prophet often meant living a hard life, often a lonely life, often on the run (especially if you were a prophet like Elijah), prophets were mostly unwanted, unwelcome and feared and quite often even hated and this meant the vocation of a prophet was often dangerous. Being the apprentice of Elijah was particularly dangerous.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha made his decision immediately, he didn’t second guess his course of action and he had only one request of his new boss – to be allowed to say farewell to his father, family and friends and Elijah was happy to oblige him. This says a lot about the kind of man Elisha was; he was a man who loved God intensely and was willing to give up everything to serve Him. Elisha killed the two oxen he’d been leading and cooked them over the wood of the plough they’d been harnessed to and doing this was also significant because he destroyed his personal means of making a living according to his former way of life. He prepared a feast for his family and friends – a celebratory feast – and then promptly made his way to Elijah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha watched Elijah over the next four years observing his mentor and learned all he needed to from him. He saw Elijah deal with King Ahab over his murder of Naboth and his sons when he conspired to steal his vineyard; he saw the fulfilment of the prophecies concerning Ahab and Jezebel’s deaths as well as other things. He knew Elijah was a real man of God, he was awed and inspired by the powerful prophetic ministry of his mentor and he learned well from him that God was faithful and could be thoroughly trusted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;On the day Elijah knew God was going to take him to heaven he told Elisha three separate times to stay where he was because the Lord was directing him to yet another place. The prophet was testing him to see how strong his loyalty really was. First they went to Bethel, next to Jericho and finally to the Jordan River. Each time Elisha refused to leave his master and remained at his side. There were many other prophets in these particular places and they all spoke to Elisha to ask him if he realised that he was going to lose his master that very day. Elisha acknowledged their information but he refused to be sidetracked or influenced by them, he refused to leave to plot his own ministry course. They were all godly men, prophets in their own right and this is acknowledged by the fact that they all knew Elijah was about to leave them because God was going to take him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Once they had crossed the Jordan River (miraculously because Elijah parted the water by striking his mantle [cloak] on the water and it parted for them to walk through), Elijah finally turned to Elisha to ask if he had a final request of him and we all know of Elisha’s famous request for a double portion of the same spirit that rested upon Elijah to rest on him. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:1-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ancient Hebrew custom granted a double portion of the father’s possessions upon the firstborn son and with it gave the right of succession to that son to lead the family. Requesting a double portion of the spirit of Elijah didn’t mean that Elisha was greedy or considered himself to be superior to his mentor, rather, Elisha loved Elijah as a father, he honoured his mentor immensely and since Elisha had given up his claims to his physical inheritance when he left his home and family to serve Elijah, he was asking for the ‘double portion’ or inheritance of his mentor and spiritual father Elijah. He was in fact asking for a spiritual inheritance rather than a physical one.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha knew he was about to step into the shoes of his mentor, he would take over the position and authority of Elijah and he wanted to be thoroughly equipped for the task. He wanted to be a faithful student by becoming a mentor to others in the same way that Elijah had been to him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Elijah said that Elisha was asking a hard thing &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(v10)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; it was because the source of Elijah’s power wasn’t of his own doing, it was given to him by God. Elijah didn’t have the ability or authority to endow such power on another human being; that was entirely God’s prerogative. However, being a prophet meant that he could in fact issue instructions that would serve as a sign to his student to indicate whether or not God would grant the request. Elijah told Elisha that if he actually saw him taken into heaven by God that would be the sign to indicate that God would grant his request and that’s exactly what happened.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 2:11-14, ‘As they were going along and talking, behold, there appeared a chariot of fire and horses of fire which separated the two of them. And Elijah went up by a whirlwind in to heaven. Elisha saw it and cried out, “My father, my father, chariots of Israel and its horsemen!” And he saw Elijah no more. Then he took hold of his own clothes and tore them in two pieces. He also took up the mantle of Elijah that fell from him and returned and stood by the bank of the Jordan. He took the mantle of Elijah that fell from him and struck the waters and said, “Where is the Lord, the God of Elijah?” And when he also had struck the waters, they were divided here and there; and Elisha crossed over.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elisha’s request was granted, he saw his mentor taken into heaven and there are several important things to note about Elisha’s reactions at this incredible event.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He called Elijah “My father” which was a term of endearment and respect toward his mentor. It is a common title to call a leader/teacher ‘father’ in Hebrew culture, but Elisha’s high esteem and love for his mentor was greater than the relationships held by most teachers and their students as is evident by his refusal to leave him.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He immediately took off his own clothing (an outer garment) and tore it in two. It’s a similar action to him slaughtering his oxen and plough in that he was destroying his former way of life so he couldn’t return to it. Here he is destroying his clothing to show that he was leaving his former position behind never to return to it and he was now the authorised successor and newly appointed prophet of God taking the place of seniority which had previously been held by Elijah.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When he approached the Jordan River, he used ‘his’ mantle just as Elijah had done to part the waters in order to cross over. He didn’t call upon the power of Elijah or the power that had been bestowed upon him. He didn’t feel the need to exercise his new authority or even to come up with his own methods, he did what he saw his mentor do and he called upon the God of Elijah. Yahweh was his God too, but he honoured his mentor and acknowledged his relationship with his old mentor and his new relationship standing with God. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;As a person Elisha was quite different from Elijah in that while Elijah was very much a solitary kind of figure, Elisha was often found in the company of other prophets &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:8-10)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;; he spent time with the elders of Samaria &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:32)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; as well as the kings of Israel and on one occasion with the king of Judah. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 3:11)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He travelled a good deal like his mentor and we know that he had his own home in Samaria &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:32)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;; he also had the use of the upper room in the home of the Shunemite woman whenever he was in that area. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:8-10)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Elisha was quite prepared to involve himself in his society and the general everyday dealings of life. He was committed to assisting his students when they needed help &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:1-4)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and it’s from this that we know he was committed to training other godly young men to be responsible prophets and leaders to declare the word of the Lord to their people.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We know that there were eight major miracles performed by Elijah and we’ve just seen that God granted Elisha’s request for a double portion of Elijah’s spirit so what did that mean with regard to the things Elisha did? Well, Elisha performed sixteen major miracles and they were:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;01 - He parted the Jordan River &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:13-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;02 - He cursed the teenagers who mocked him &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:23-25)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;03 - He healed the poisoned waters of Jericho &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:19-22)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;04 - He filled the widows vessels with oil &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:1-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;05 - The miraculous birth of a son by the Shunemite woman &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:8-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;06 - He raised from the dead the son of the Shunemite woman &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:18-37)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;07 - He healed the poisoned stew &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:38-44)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;08 - He fed 100 men with a small amount of food and provided leftovers as well &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 4:42-44)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;09 - He healed Naaman the Syrian from leprosy &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 5:1-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;10 - He punished Gehazi with leprosy &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 5:15-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;11 - He caused the sunken iron axe head to float on the water &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:1-7)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;12 - He caused the trenches on the battlefield to flood &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 3:1-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;13 - He gave special sight to the kings messenger &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:16-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;14 - He blinded the Aramean army &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:8-18)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;15 - He restored the sight of the Aramean army &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 6:19-20)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;16 - A dead man was raised to life after his body was thrown onto the grave of Elisha &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 13:20-21)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;ol&gt; &lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Doing a quick Google search to get a comparative list of the miracles done by both the prophet’s Elijah and Elisha you quickly discover that different people have very diverse definitions of what constitutes a miracle. Some include all their prophecies but a prophecy doesn’t necessarily equal a miracle such as raising a dead body to life or multiplying food and oil. Regardless how one defines a miracle however, what is sure is that Elisha’s miracle count was twice that of Elijah thus validating and proving that God really did answer his request to receive a double portion of the spirit of his mentor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Next week we’ll take a closer look at a few of the specific miracles that Elijah did during his ministry years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy&lt;/p&gt;",2012-09-27 01:34:59,mworby
7686,Home Group Notes - Elijah Pt 2,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://vision.org.au/images/blog_images/1058605_60297588 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;201&quot; width=&quot;281&quot; /&gt;Elijah Part 2 (Ay-lay-yah or Ay-lay-yahu)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Last week we began looking at the life of the Prophet Elijah. Here’s a quick recap...(or see last week’s study notes on the Journey blog at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/the-journey&quot;&gt;www.vision.org.au/the-journey&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah’s story can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 17, 18, 19, 21 &amp;amp; 2 Kings 1, 2, &amp;amp; 2 Chronicles 21.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He was a simple yet rough kind of man who lived simply and according to the old ways, he ate simply, wore animal skins and had a leather belt around his waist.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;His ministry life only spanned about twenty years.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He was seriously zealous for the Lord.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He lived during the reign of King Ahab and Queen Jezebel and after then Ahaziah.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He did some amazing things and his ministry was defined by eight major miracles and we looked at just two of them last week, raising from the dead the son of the widow of Zarephath and the contest on Mt Carmel between Elijah and the prophets of Ba’al and Asherah.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is where we pick up the story.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah was a lone voice when he called the king, his people and their false religious system to the challenge on Mt Carmel and for the most part, Elijah probably felt like he was the only one of his nation who still loved God, he was seriously outnumbered but he obeyed the call of God. He stood alone on that mountain before his nation knowing he could pay with his life but he exposed the falsehood of their false religion and God showed Himself to be the One True God. The people responded and revival came to the land. It was a short lived revival to be sure, but it was a revival none the less and one man instigated it at God’s direction. Ba’al worship returned, but we have no way of knowing just how many Israelites were permanently saved from deception simply because of Elijah’s obedience.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If you are called of God, don’t look at your situation and determine that your success or failure is dependent upon those around you or how many people you have on your side; your success or failure is determined by God alone. He’s the One you have to worry about. If you’ve never heard the story of Mr Genor on George Street in Sydney, can I encourage you to hear this story and be encouraged that whatever God has called you to do, your only responsibility is to obey God and leave the results to Him. Here’s the link...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ew1srubCw_0&quot;&gt;http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ew1srubCw_0&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah may have experienced some fear when he issued his challenge to the king, but the Scripture shows him being confident and even somewhat cheeky in how he related to the false prophets themselves. For all intents and purposes Elijah didn’t experience any fear during this challenge, so it’s really a surprise to see how Elijah reacted after this incredible display of God’s unmatched and unquestionable power. Queen Jezebel was so enraged over the slaughter of her false prophets that she sent a message to Elijah saying that within a 24 hour period, he would be as dead as all her prophets were.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah more than anyone knew God was all-powerful and could deal with this wicked woman, but her reputation was so huge, that Elijah literally ran for his life all the way to Beersheva which is a distance of about 165km from Mount Carmel (I checked on Google Earth), he literally crossed the border into the Southern Kingdom of Judah where he couldn’t be followed and caught and he was in a terrible state.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He left his servant at Beersheva and went even further into the wilderness and finally sat under a juniper tree and begged God to kill him; he’d had enough and he wanted to die. He probably thought that after such a powerful display against the false prophets of Ba’al and Asherah, real change would come to the nation starting with the king and his household, but what Elijah got was a death threat from the deadliest woman who ever lived and Elijah simply gave up.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He slept for a while (sheer exhaustion and strain would have finally taken their toll on him) and then an angel came to look after him, gave him food and drink and he slept again; the angel came a second time with more food and drink and it strengthened him so much that it sustained him for 40 days and nights and he set out on another long distance trek, but he didn’t make his way back home to Israel, to the place God had called him to prophesy and speak His words to the people, instead he travelled to Mt Horeb. This mountain is in Arabia, and this was a further 283km distance. Elijah ended up nearly 550km from his home in Israel and he was hiding in a cave in the backside of the Arabian wilderness.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God spoke to him and said, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;“What are you doing here, Elijah?”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt; You see God didn’t tell Elijah to run to this spot, it was all Elijah’s idea and this is where we come to see the flaws in Elijah’s character and he answered God this way...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 19:10, ‘He said, “I have been very zealous for the Lord, the God of hosts; for the sons of Israel have forsaken Your covenant, torn down Your altars and killed Your prophets with the sword. I alone am left; and they seek my life to take it away.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God was very patient with Elijah and told Him to stand on the mountain and the Lord would pass by him. This is extraordinary. A whirlwind, something like a hurricane that was breaking rocks into pieces went by, then an earthquake went by and then a fire went by. Three ‘natural disasters’ sent by God Himself, back to back, passed by Elijah for him to see. Was Elijah afraid? Not that we’re told, he simply stood there and watched as these events took place. God wasn’t in these things, but God was controlling these things and sent these things for a reason; to show Elijah that God is the One who controls all things...even the natural elements of the world around us. When these things had passed by there was a very quiet, gentle blowing, like a really soft breath of wind and Elijah wrapped his cloak around himself and stood at the entrance of the cave to hear what this last phenomenon was. And God spoke to him again...do you know what He said to him? &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;“What are you doing here, Elijah?”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt; It was exactly the same message he’d received before.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What is the lesson here?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God had called Elijah to be His prophetic mouthpiece and Elijah was overcome with fear to the point of wanting to die. Elijah knew that God was the only True and Real God and Elijah had seen God’s power up close and personal, but Elijah had been completely sideswiped with the results that came against him after the contest on Mount Carmel. All Elijah could see was the terror and mayhem around him. When God sent the whirlwind, the earthquake and the fire, the noise and the chaos would have been phenominal and when that all stopped suddenly and there was barely a whisper of breeze, the quiet of the moment would have been ‘LOUD’...and he listened intently to hear God’s voice again very clearly ask, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;“What are you doing here, Elijah?”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God didn’t take Elijah out into the backside of a desert wilderness to teach him how to hear the voice of God; Elijah had been hearing the voice of God very clearly for years and years; God was teaching Elijah that he didn’t need to fear the chaos and disaster that was going on all around him or even the death threats of a wicked woman, God was entirely in control of all that was taking place. All Elijah had to do was trust Him. Running out into the wilderness was not where God wanted Elijah. Hiding in a cave listening to a still small voice is not where God wanted Elijah...that’s why God asked him, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;“What are you doing here?”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What was Elijah’s response? It was the same as the first response...woe is me...everyone’s against me and I’m the only one left who loves You. Woe is me.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;How did God respond to him this time? He gave Elijah what he wanted. He told Elijah to head up to Damascus, he was given a couple of final tasks one of which was to anoint Elisha to be his successor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It wasn’t long after that, that God took Elijah up to heaven without tasting physical death and Elijah’s prophetic ministry was transferred to Elisha but Elijah hadn’t complete his mission.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This brings us to the doubly prophetic side of Elijah the prophet and his particular ministry...he is a forerunner of the Messiah. The Jews today set a place at every Passover table for Elijah, they have a cup of wine for Elijah and before the meal has finished, the youngest person at the table will open the front door in anticipation that Elijah just might be there. They believe from the Scriptures that before Messiah can come, Elijah must come first to prepare the way for him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Now we know that John the Baptist was the forerunner for Messiah when He came the first time. John came in the spirit of Elijah and was the voice in the wilderness crying out for the people to get ready for the arrival of their Messiah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;John was a rough diamond like Elijah, he wore camel skins and a leather belt, he ate locusts and wild honey, he lived a simple life according to the ‘old ways’ just like Elijah did. He preached a message of repentance and for the people to turn from wickedness and return to the Lord just like Elijah did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Unlike Elijah however, John completed his mission by pointing out the Messiah, calling Yeshua &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘The Lamb of God who takes away the sins of the world’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;John 1:29&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Not too long after Yeshua began His ministry, John’s ministry finished and he was executed. Mission complete.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We know that Messiah will come back a second time and before He does, Elijah will again be His forerunner.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Revelation 11:3-6, ‘”And I will grant authority to My two witnesses, and they will prophesy for twelve hundred and sixty days, clothed in sackcloth.” These are the two olive trees and the two lampstands that stand before the Lord of the earth. And if anyone wants to harm them, fire flows out of their mouth and devours their enemies; so if anyone wants to harm them, he must be killed in this way. These have the power to shut up the sky, so that rain will not fall during the days of their prophesying; and they have power over the waters to turn them into blood, and to strike the earth with every plague, as often as they desire.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is talking about two individuals who will be prophetic witnesses during the last of the last days, they will be based in Jerusalem and they will boldly preach the Gospel and during their three and a half years of ministry, and tragically they will be despised. Some will attempt to kill them but these two prophets will have power to destroy their enemies by fire proceeding from their own mouths.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Many but not all Bible scholars believe that these two men will be Moses and Elijah returned. Now Moses died on Mount Nebo but no one knew of his burial site so no ‘body’ was ever found. Elijah was taken up in a chariot and he never died. Moses’ mission to enter the promised land was cut short by his disobedience and Elijah’s mission was cut short by his self-pity.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What’s interesting about these two men possibly being the two witnesses spoken of in Revelation 11 who will return during the final days of the Great Tribulation period is the characteristic behaviours they will display.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;They will destroy their enemies with fire.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah called down fire from heaven to demonstrate that Yahweh was God and then destroyed 850 false prophets, he also called down fire on 102 men sent to capture him.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;They will have power to shut the heavens so that no rain falls on the earth.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah performed this miracle bringing a three year drought that almost destroyed Israel.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;They will have power to turn the waters into blood&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Moses was given this power when he turned all the water in Egypt into blood.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;They will have power to unleash plagues on the earth.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Moses brought in plagues to crush the Egyptians to force Pharaoh to let the Hebrews go free.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In Rabbinical literature it’s believed that Elijah will play a vital role when the Messiah finally appears...&lt;em&gt;“His real Messianic activity – in some passages he is even called ‘go’el’ which means ‘kinsmen-redeemer’ – will commence three days before the coming of Messiah. On the first day he will lament over the devastation of Israel, but will close with the words: ‘Peace will now come over the earth’; on the second and third days he will speak words of comfort. When the archangel Michael blows the trumpet, Elijah will appear with the Messiah, whom he will present to the Jews. They will ask of Elijah, as an attestation of his mission, that he raise the dead before their eyes and revive such of the dead as they personally knew.’ &lt;/em&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com&quot;&gt;www.jewishencyclopedia.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Non-Biblical and extra-Biblical literature is not inspired so we don’t base our theology on them, but what we learn from these additional sources show that the Scripture itself is the source of these teachings; they’re not made up out of thin air. Unlike most Jewish people today who don’t accept the New Testament as legitimate Scripture, believer’s in Yeshua have the benefit and wisdom from both the Old and New Testaments from which to base and build their theology with the Old and New reaffirming and confirming the other.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What is fascinating about this view for the Christian, is that we see this unfolding through both John the Baptist and Yeshua two thousand plus years ago. The Jews are living under judicial blindness at the moment, though there are currently more Jewish believers today than there was even at the birth of the church, and for those still living under this blindness, they wait with longing for the arrival of their Messiah and eagerly waiting for Elijah to come first. We however know that Messiah has already come and John the Baptist in the spirit or anointing of Elijah was the forerunner announcing Messiah’s imminent arrival.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Messiah is getting ready to return again, and if the scholars are correct in their interpretation, this time Elijah will again be the forerunner and this next time will see all of national Israel saved at the arrival of the Messiah for the second time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Maranatha!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Zechariah 12:10, “I will pour out on the house of David and on the inhabitants of Jerusalem, the Spirit of grace and supplication, so that they will look on Me whom they have pierced; and they will mourn for Him, as one mourns for an only son, and they will weep bitterly over Him like the bitter weeping over a firstborn.”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy&lt;/p&gt;",2012-09-20 00:41:05,mworby
7608,Home Group Notes - Elijah Pt 1,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/954634_94521374 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;195&quot; width=&quot;293&quot; /&gt;Elijah Part 1 (Ay-lay-yah or Ay-lay-yahu)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah’s name is a magnificent name. There are two main elements in this name, the first being ‘El’ which is an abbreviation for Elohim, a word that means ‘God’ or gods and the second element is ‘Jah’ which is God’s personal name, Yhwh (Yahweh). It’s believed that the name ‘Elijah’ means Yahweh is God...or from the personal perspective of the name holder, ‘Yahweh is my God’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This name personifies this Old Testament prophet because he lived his life declaring always through his words and his actions that he served Yahweh alone as his God and was a defender of Yahweh against the worshippers of false gods. It was because of his unwavering faithfulness to Yahweh that some assume that the name ‘Elijah’ wasn’t actually his given name but that he took this name upon himself because he wanted other’s to know he was a devoted servant of Yahweh. Scripture doesn’t say this however, it’s speculation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah’s story can be read in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;1 Kings 17, 18, 19, 21 &amp;amp; 2 Kings 1, 2, &amp;amp; 2 Chronicles 21&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah lived during the last years of wicked king Ahab and queen Jezebel and during the very brief reign of king Ahaziah in the northern kingdom of Israel and he lived during the reign of king Jehoshaphat of Judah, the southern kingdom.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In many respects Elijah was the first prophet of Israel from the beginning of the monarchy even though Moses, Samuel and David are also very much confirmed as prophets, but as far as the history of Israel as a nation in the land during the reign of the Jewish monarchs, Elijah was the first prophet. To be sure there were always prophets who spoke the word of the Lord during Israel’s history, but not all became so notable as to have books written by or for them and what they spoke. So of the Biblical prophets, Elijah was the first ‘main’ prophet.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah the Tishbite gets this title either from the town he came from or from a family member with the name ‘Tishbe’; some think he hailed from a town within the boundaries of the tribe of Naphtali in the Galilee, while others believe he was from the east of the Jordan River because he’s described as being one of the settlers of Gilead and Gilead is situated in the tribal allotment of Dan which is east of the Jordan. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings17:1)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He lived very much according to the ‘old customs’ and presented himself in simple attire...a mantle of animal skins and a leather belt. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(2 Kings 1:8)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;As an individual he was quite rough and ready, he didn’t carry a lot of ‘airs and graces’ - he wasn’t of the refined social set. He was what Aussies would call ‘a rough diamond’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah had a dramatic start to his prophetic ministry and he was very enthusiastic about what God called him to do, though he was equally cautious. Being a prophet during the historical centuries of Biblical Israel was a dangerous vocation that saw the vast majority of God’s prophets killed in some very unpleasant ways. So Elijah always obeyed God but he didn’t hang around in public, he hid most of the time to avoid capture.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah’s ministry was marked by some remarkable miracles, in fact there were 8 distinct miracles. (Some like to say there were more but that list becomes a bit of a stretch with some events not really being classed as miracles).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He shut up the heavens to usher in a drought to show that God was very angry with the idolatry in the land of Israel. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 17:1)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;While hiding from a furious king Ahab, he hid at the brook Cherith and God used ravens to provide him with bread and meat every morning and evening. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 17:3-7)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;When the brook dried up, God directed him to a widow in Zarephath, Sidon who would provide him with food. She only had a handful of flour and a tiny amount of oil to make one last meal for herself and her son. She obeyed the word of the Lord and made food first for Elijah and this resulted in her oil and flour multiplying until the end of the drought; this kept them all alive. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 17:9-16)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The woman’s son died of a severe sickness, Elijah prayed for the dead boy and the Lord raised him back to life. This was a powerful witness and testimony to the widow who was a pagan...a non-Jew!!! &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 17:17-24)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah called down fire from heaven to destroy 450 prophets of Ba’al and 400 prophets of Asherah on Mt Carmel. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 18:7-40)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah prayed seven times for the drought to break, and eventually he saw a cloud the size of a man’s hand and the heavens opening bringing drought breaking rain. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 18:45)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah called down fire from heaven twice upon a total of 102 soldiers sent against him by Ahab. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 1:1-18)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Elijah parted the Jordan River. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 2:8)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;King Ahab hated him and called him a ‘troubler of Israel’ because of the drought...as though Israel’s problems were all Elijah’s fault. God was using the drought to get their attention because God hated their idolatry, something He’d told the people He would do to them before they’d even set one foot into their promised land. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Deuteronomy 28:1-14&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; lists all the blessings they would live under at God’s hand if they obeyed Him and &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;Deuteronomy 28:15-68&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;lists all the curses they would live under if they disobeyed Him. Then in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Deuteronomy 29&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; God through Moses, tells the people that the disobedience He’s referring to that will bring these dreadful curses upon them is in forsaking God and His ways and embracing the practices and worship of false gods and paganism.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah had the unenviable job of being the messenger reminding King Ahab of God’s promise of bringing curses upon His people for their wickedness and idolatry and like most human beings on the planet, Ahab refuses to take responsibility for his own sin and tries to place the blame on Elijah, thus calling him the ‘troubler of Israel’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s amazing how people will place blame onto righteous men and women of God when they bravely confront the sin they see in society; society in turn reacts with venom and promptly lays the blame at the feet of the righteous declaring them to be ‘haters’ and ‘judgemental bigots’ and ‘Pharisees’ and ‘hypocrites’. No one wants to take responsibility today, we would rather hide behind pop psychology and blame our mothers for not potty training us correctly, or our fathers for not boosting our self esteem enough or our cousins or uncles or aunties or neighbours or school teachers...anyone but ourselves...and this is a fallen human trait in both ancient and modern eras.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah’s ministry life was very short, from 870-850 BC and he’s renowned for his zeal for God. Elijah’s ministry and life is also very prophetic because he is believed to be the one who will be the forerunner of the Messiah which we will look at more closely next week.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We can take a brief look at a couple of really significant things that he did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-left: 8px; float: right;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/hg fun.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Home Group Fun with Steve's Biblical Timeline Chart&quot; title=&quot;Home Group Fun with Steve's Biblical Timeline Chart&quot; class=&quot;caption&quot; height=&quot;248&quot; width=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;Elijah is the only man of God to raise someone from the dead besides the Lord Jesus. The widow of Zarephath who fed Elijah during the drought when he was in hiding had a son and despite her acceptance of and care for the prophet and God’s supernatural provision for them, her son became very, very sick and died.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;All people grieve over the loss of a loved one and ask the ‘WHY?’ questions, but this widow’s response is very interesting, this is what she said to Elijah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 17:18, ‘So she said to Elijah, “What do I have to do with you, O man of God? You have come to me to bring my iniquity to remembrance and to put my son to death!”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We don’t like to call sin ‘sin’! We would rather call sin a ‘problem’ or an ‘issue’ or a ‘challenge’...but don’t call it ‘sin’. This widow was a Gentile...a pagan Gentile and she wasn’t a convert to Judaism. She had probably heard about the God of the Jews but she didn’t know the God of the Jews. One day, Elijah the prophet of Yahweh turns up on her doorstep...the very day she knows she’s going to cook her last meal for herself and her son and that after this, they’re both going to die of starvation because of the drought.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;She’s got nothing to lose when Elijah asks her to give him a small cake of food first and wonder of wonders, the God of the Jews miraculously multiplies her flour and oil and this keeps them all alive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;But it’s not possible to be in the presence of God and not recognise that He is pure and holy and we are sinful and wretched. When her son dies of a dreadful sickness, this woman is acutely aware of her sinful condition and the consequence of sin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sin exacts a great cost in every human life whether we acknowledge it or not, in fact sin is the most expensive thing in the whole universe as well as the most destructive.The shocking thing about our fallen human nature is that we crave and run after the very thing that will destroy us! Thank God for Yeshua and His willingness to pay our debt and reconcile us to the Father!!! &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;She’s a pagan and she acknowledges sin for what it is and the consequences of it. But her grief has made her wish that Elijah had never come to her at all. In that moment of despair, she would have preferred ignorance over guilt because she knows she’s responsible for her sin. But Elijah calls upon the Lord and he took her son to an upstairs bedroom and prayed to God. He stretched himself out on the boy three times and God revived him to life again.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What this did for the widow is incredible. She didn’t just believe in the man of God, she now knew that the God of the Jews was the One True God. If God can raise a dead person to life again, He can forgive sins and wash a person clean. Only a God with power over death has power over sin and can bring forgiveness and redemption.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Yeshua did something similar when He forgave the sins of the paralytic and the religious leaders questioned Him because of this; they said that only God had the authority to forgive sins...so Yeshua proceeded to heal the man’s physical body...something only God can do...proving Himself to be God and therefore absolutely able to forgive sins. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Mark 2:10; Luke 5:24; Matt 9:6)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Another really amazing thing that Elijah did was to utterly humiliate and destroy the false prophets of Baal and Asherah – 850 false priests/prophets in total.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He challenged them before the nation...calling the nation to return to God and turn away from their paganism. He called the false priests and all Israel to Mt Carmel for a contest between Ba’al and Yahweh. The challenge was this: Both Elijah and the false prophets would build and altar and place a bull for sacrifice upon it. They would then call upon their respective deities to send fire from heaven to consume the sacrifices. The deity that actually did respond with fire would be the true deity and therefore the people would know which deity they should worship. Everyone agreed to this challenge.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah let the false prophets go first and gave them hours to call upon their false god Ba’al to respond. They danced around, called out to him...&lt;em&gt;”Oh Ba’al hear us”&lt;/em&gt;...Elijah watched the spectacle with both disgust and amusement and even mocked them during their rituals and said things like, “maybe he’s busy...maybe he’s on a trip somewhere...maybe he’s sleeping...maybe he’s on the toilet”...and this only drove them into greater frenzy...so much so that they cut themselves with swords and lances until the blood was gushing from them. This is a gruesome scene and they did this for a whole day...from morning until the time of the evening sacrifice. Ba’al did not answer and the people had completely lost confidence in them. No one paid them anymore attention despite the spectacle they were giving.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Then Elijah said to the people, &lt;em&gt;“Come near to me”&lt;/em&gt; and they did. He then repaired the altar of the Lord that had been pulled down, it was made of twelve stones, one for each of the tribes of Israel, he dug an enormous trench around the perimeter of the altar, he put wood on the altar and then killed an ox and cut it in pieces and put it on the altar as well. Then he told some of the men there to get four large pitchers or jars of water and pour it all over the altar. He told them to do this three times...that’s a total of twelve large pitchers of water that left the alter, the wood and the ox saturated and the trench completely filled.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah didn’t perform any rituals, he didn’t dance around or cut himself, he didn’t act anything out as a sign or symbol, he simply prayed out loud.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 18:36-37, ‘”O Lord, the God of Abraham, Isaac and Israel, today let it be known that You are God in Israel and that I am Your servant and I have done all these things at Your word. Answer me, O Lord, answer me, that this people may know that You O Lord, are God, and that You have turned their heart back again.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Elijah gave God all the glory, all the honour, he asked for none for himself, he simply wanted God to confirm that he was only acting on God’s instructions and to prove it by answering with fire. And answer He did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Fire came down from heaven in an instant and it consumed the ox, the wood, the stones and the all the water that was in the trench. There was nothing left to look at but an enormous empty scorched hole in the ground. And the people fell on their faces in fear and readily acknowledged that Yahweh, the God of their fathers was the One True God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;At this point Elijah commanded the people to seize the false prophets, all 850 of them and to kill them all at the brook Kishon near the base of Mt Carmel. A gruesome event to be sure and it led to an interesting chapter in Elijah’s ministry life. Next week we’ll look at what happened and how Elijah is incredibly intertwined with the return of the Messiah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What we learn from Elijah is that obedience to God doesn’t mean we’ll be popular or even welcome. Standing for righteousness comes at a cost, and in Elijah’s case the cost was living under the threat of death on a daily basis. We have our challenges in the West, but we have family all around the world who live under the threat of death for their faith in Christ every day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Let's commit to keeping our family in Australia and around the world in prayer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-smile.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Smile&quot; title=&quot;Smile&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-09-12 23:51:26,mworby
7504,Home Group Notes - Ezekiel,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/575231_55762839 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;219&quot; width=&quot;292&quot; /&gt;Ezekiel (yekh-ez-kal)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This name is made up of two elements, the last element is ‘El’ which is a common abbreviation of the name of the Lord, ‘Elohim’ while the first element, ‘hazaq’ means to be or become strong or courageous. It’s mostly used to charge soldiers to be strong. So Ezekiel means ‘God Strengthens’, ‘Strengthened by God’ or ‘Strength of God’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This name is especially appropriate for Ezekiel because his message to his people made him extremely unwanted, unwelcome and unpopular and without God strengthening him for his mission it would have been particularly difficult to endure all he went through.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The story of Ezekiel can be found in all &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;48 chapters of the book of Ezekiel&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; written by the Ezekiel himself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel lived during the lifetimes of the prophet Daniel during the reign of King Zedekiah of Judah...who also happened to be the last king of Judah and also during the last half of the prophet Jeremiah’s life, and Ezekiel lived during the Babylonian exile. He began his prophetic ministry in the 5&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; year of King Jehoiachin’s captivity in Babylon, remembering that this king was so terribly wicked God pronounced a blood curse on his family line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel saw the destruction of both Jerusalem and the magnificent Temple built by King Solomon and was part of the first Jewish contingency to be deported to Babylon at the beginning of the 70 year exile that had been prophesied by the prophet Jeremiah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;The Role of a Prophet&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The primary task of a prophet was to arouse the people and the government to repentance and observance of God’s laws. This invariably meant that their messages were mostly in the form of a rebuke that not only listed the sins of the people in detail and God’s abhorrence to them, but their messages also included details of how judgement would come to them if they didn’t repent and return to the Lord and His ways.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Many see God in the Old Testament as brutal and harsh and vengeful, but when you consider how many years God took to warn His people and how long He gave them to repent, you actually come away with the understanding that despite the depravity and rebellion of the people, God waited many hundreds of years before He finally brought promised judgement. God in the Old Testament is in fact incredibly gracious and patient and merciful. The culmination of His mercy is ultimately seen at the cross of Calvary. This picture of God’s enormous mercy is very dramatically seen if you read from Genesis right through to the end of the Gospels.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Because prophets had a reputation for always bringing a message of rebuke and judgement they were very often feared by the people because nobody likes to get bad news especially if it means they have to stop living and behaving the way they want to. The message of repentance is still unpopular today.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;An example of how the people feared the arrival of a prophet is seen in the lead up to the calling and anointing of David when God instructed Samuel to go to the house of Jesse in Bethlehem and anoint one of his sons to be the next king of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Samuel 16:4-5, ‘So Samuel did what the Lord said, and came to Bethlehem. And the elders of the city came trembling to meet him and said, “Do you come in peace?” He said, “In peace; I have come to sacrifice to the Lord....”’.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The leaders of the people of Bethlehem went to meet with Samuel as he arrived in their village to find out if he was coming to them with a fearful message and intention or a peaceful message and intention.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel was 25 years old when he was taken captive and he was 30 when he was called into the ministry which is the traditional age for Jewish men to enter ministry service. His ministry began in either 593 or 592 BC and his ministry lasted approximately 22 years and just like Jeremiah and Zechariah, Ezekiel was both and prophet and a priest, in fact he was in the Zadok family line and this meant he was among the aristocracy whom king Nebuchnezzar selected as his first captives...these noble Israelites included the prophet Daniel and his friends.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel was a married man as was the case for the priests and he lived among other Jewish exiles near Tel-Abib on the River Chebar and he lived in his own house. He was considered to be wise by the Jewish elders and they often visited him wanting a divine word or oracle because Ezekiel was remember, of good family lineage and in the priestly line. His was a special position.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;As a prophet and priest he belonged to a privileged segment of the Jewish community and he lived in a strategic time in history because he was able to refer back to previous prophetic announcements by the prophet Jeremiah who warned the Jews of impending judgement and exile if they didn’t repent of their wickedness and he could also point to the fulfilment of those prophecies because they themselves were actually living in exile after they’d been taken captive just as Jeremiah had said they would.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The Jewish monarchy and government had been annihilated by the Babylonians, the Jewish political and national life was over as far as their independent national identity was concerned, their city and state was ransacked and their Temple was utterly destroyed. This was the situation Ezekiel himself was living in when God called him to be a prophetic voice to his people living in and under Babylonian rule.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel had the unenviable task of communicating to his countrymen that they didn’t need to despair, God wasn’t through with them...unfortunately, to his countrymen it appeared that God was indeed through with them. Ezekiel had to try to communicate that God and His sovereignty had lead them to Babylon because of their sin and disobedience but that through His sovereignty God would restore them once again but this would occur through the repentance of the people themselves. Once again, this was a call for personal and individual repentance before God and submission to His laws and ways.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What makes Ezekiel so very different to other prophets is that he strived to reach his countrymen in very personal and individual ways, he desperately wanted to win them back to the Lord and he felt personally responsible for each one of them. His focus was never on establishing the nation with political goals and aspirations, rather Ezekiel’s hope was for his people to become a congregation under the pure dominion of God one heart at a time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Another unique aspect of Ezekiel’s ministry was through various physical signs that he endured, experienced or acted out in order to communicate his message from God to the people. These signs included...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He was bound up, made housebound, mute &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(3:23-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He used a brick and an iron plate as preaching illustrations &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(4:1-3)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He laid on his left side for 390 days and on his right side for 40 days &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(4:4-8)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to eat food in an unclean manner &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(4:9-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to shave his head and beard &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(5:1-4)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to pack his bags and dig through the wall of Jerusalem &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(12:1-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to eat bread with trembling and drink water with quivering &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(12:17-20)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to brandish a sharp sword and strike his hands together &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(21:8-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He portrayed Israel in the smelting furnace &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(22:17-22)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to cook a pot of stew &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(24:1-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He was not allowed to mourn the death of his wife &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(24:15-24)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to be mute for a season &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(24:25-27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had to put two sticks together that became one &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(37:15-28)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Above all, the central theme in all that Ezekiel says and does is the ‘Glory of the Lord’; this is seen very graphically in chapters &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1:28, 3:12 &amp;amp; 23, 10:4 &amp;amp; 18, 11:23, 43:4 &amp;amp; 5, 44:4&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Ezekiel includes graphic descriptions of the disobedience of both Israel and Judah despite God’s kindness, patience and long-suffering warnings which He gave again and again and again.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel gives many illustrations of spiritual principles, a few of them are...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ezekiel was told to eat the scroll:- even though the writing on the scroll was full of lamentations, mourning and woe it was sweet in the prophet’s mouth because it was the Word of God Himself which is a light and always produces life. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Ezek 2&amp;amp;3) &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The four creatures representing the 12 Tribes of Israel which is again repeated in the book of Revelation. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;(Ezek 1:4-21; Rev 4:5-11)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The ‘barbershop’ scene where the prophet shaves his head and beard to demonstrate the humiliation his people will face because of their rebellion. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Ezek 5:1-4)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The graffiti on the Temple walls demonstrating that God wants holiness and purity in His house on filthiness and depravity. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Ezek 8:10-12)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Another primary theme throughout the book is God’s holiness and sovereignty, something the Israelites had completely forgotten in their efforts to live as they pleased. Ezekiel communicated this truth to the people by contrasting God’s holiness and purity as bright glory against the despicable depravity of Judah’s sins.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Like all the prophets of Israel, Ezekiel not only delivered God’s messages of anger, frustration and judgement on His people because of their rebellion, idolatry and stubbornness, but Ezekiel also delivered God’s promise of forgiveness, restoration and fulfilment of their calling and covenants especially with relation to the land and heritage He’d promised them unconditionally through Abraham, Isaac and Jacob and later on through David. God never left His people without hope of their promised future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;One of the final major themes found in Ezekiel is in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;chapters 40-48&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and these all pertain to the future Temple in Jerusalem. The dimensions and elements of this final temple are markedly different from the original Temple built by Solomon and the second Temple built by Zerubbabel but which was later expanded and finished by Herod the Great. This final Temple will be built and will be functional from which Messiah will reign when He returns to establish righteousness upon the earth.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Of course all the messages that Ezekiel was commissioned to speak to his countrymen came at great personal cost to the prophet because the people were unwilling to hear him and many times God forewarned Ezekiel that upon delivering his message the people would tie him up with ropes, imprison him, hate him, reject him...and this of course broke the heart of the prophet who desperately loved his own people, he loved God supremely and his greatest desire was to see his people reconciled to their God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Possibly one of the saddest and hardest things Ezekiel had to endure was the death of his beloved wife. Hard enough for any man (or woman) to lose their best friend and life partner, but in Ezekiel’s case, God instructed him that he wasn’t to grieve for her. He could grieve and groan inwardly, but he wasn’t to show any outward signs of grief or mourning. This is a very, very big ask by God of a man who loved Him supremely. What was the purpose of God asking such a thing? God was illustrating through Ezekiel’s personal tragedy that His people were not to grieve over the loss of their holy city and their holy Temple because they had become exceedingly corrupted and God was going to do away with them...for a time. God would eventually restore these things to them, but what had become filthy and polluted had to be destroyed and the people themselves were responsible.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s not possible to talk about the prophet Ezekiel without mentioning three incredibly important chapters.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The first of these being &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;chapter 37: The Valley of Dry Bones.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This chapter is a graphic description of the destruction of the Jewish people; the valley God showed to Ezekiel was full of dead bodies all reduced to very, very dry scattered bones. This was a people dead and without hope and yet God determined that they would live once more. He told Ezekiel to prophesy to the bones and when he did, he heard a noise, a rattling noise and all the bones came together and then sinews formed on the bones followed by new flesh and skin but they were still laying dead in the valley. They were reformed, but dead! Then Ezekiel continued to prophesy and the breath of God filled them, they stood upright and came to life and they became an exceedingly great army. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(37:1-10)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ezekiel 37:11-12, ‘Then He said to me, “Son of man, these bones are the &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;whole house of Israel&lt;/span&gt;; behold, they say, ‘Our bones are dried up and our hope has perished. We are completely cut off.’ Therefore prophesy and say to them, ‘Thus says the Lord God, “Behold, I will open your graves and cause you to come up our of your graves, &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;My people; and I will bring you into the land of Israel&lt;/span&gt;.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What’s interesting is that after the Babylonian exile, the Jews were not utterly destroyed and without hope and when they did return, they never ruled themselves as an independent sovereign nation, they were always under the rule of another nation or empire, and they were never an exceedingly great army. Not until after the catastrophe of the Nazi Holocaust when the Jewish people returned to their ancient homeland after being destroyed and left for dead and once the State of Israel was established in 1948, they developed an army that has been undefeatable despite the many invasions and attacks by their &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;COMBINED&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; enemies. This is a stunning fulfilled prophesy from Ezekiel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The other two chapters which are probably the most famous chapters in Ezekiel are&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;chapters 38 &amp;amp; 39&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;These chapters are yet future and they describe what has become known as the Battle of Gog and Magog. They describe a time yet future when Israel will be living in a relatively peaceful state, specifically when the will be without walls or unwalled villages. It also describes the land as being wealthy and bountiful and God Himself draws Israel’s ancient enemies out against her; these enemy nations think they’re going to invade and take Israel and her wealth as plunder for themselves but God has determined to personally fight against Israel’s enemies to destroy them once and for all as a judgement against them for all their hatred and mistreatment of Israel throughout their history.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;These chapters are graphic in how the battles unfold and it names the nation’s who come against Israel, and its during this battle that Israel realises that she can’t defend herself with her own army, she realises that she must call upon God for her deliverance or she won’t survive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are many who believe that this famed battle of Gog and Magog is very close at hand. Time will tell. &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-wink.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Wink&quot; title=&quot;Wink&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Being a prophet was a high calling but equally a lonely calling and always a dangerous calling.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There is little known about Ezekiel’s death, in fact there are no details of how he died but we do know that his grave is in Al Kifl in Iraq, south of Bagdad near the Euphrates River...Iraq of course is the modern name of Ancient Babylon. Ezekiel was buried in the land to which he was exiled during the siege and fall of Jerusalem when Judah was invaded and subjugated by King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Many of Ezekiel’s prophecies have come to pass, those that haven’t are yet future but what we know for certain is that all of God’s words of warning, judgement, promise and restoration will come to pass because God’s word cannot fail...ever!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ezekiel 39:25-29, ‘Therefore thus says the Lord God, “Now I will restore the fortunes of Jacob and have mercy on the whole house of Israel; and I will be jealous for My holy name. They will forget their disgrace and all their treachery which they perpetrated against Me, when they live securely on their own land with no one to make them afraid. When I bring them back from the peoples and gather them from the lands of their enemies, then I shall be sanctified through them in the sight of the many nations. Then they will know that I am the Lord their God because I made them go into exile among the nations and then gathered them again to their own land; and I will leave none of them there any longer. I will not hide My face from them any longer, for I will have poured out My Spirit on the house of Israel,” declares the Lord God.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-laughing.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Laughing&quot; title=&quot;Laughing&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-09-05 06:55:51,mworby
7316,Home Group Notes - Jehoiachin,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/724407_24295926 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;233&quot; width=&quot;311&quot; /&gt;King Jehoiachin (also known as Jeconiah or Coniah)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Two elements make us this name, ‘Yah’ meaning the name of the Lord, Yahweh. The second element can have several meanings, the first could mean ‘to bring something into being with a consequence that its existence is a certainty’ indicating steadfastness; it could mean a place, something that was established.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Other’s believe that Jehoiachin means either ‘He will be established by the Lord’ or ‘Yahweh is firm, enduring’. However knowing that God had already stated emphatically to Josiah that wrath was an absolute certainty because of the wickedness of the kings of Judah, it seems far more believable that God was going to bring wrath and judgement into being as a consequence for the sins of Judah and that this impending judgement was a certainty.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The story of Jehoiachin can be found in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 24 &amp;amp; 25, 2 Chronicles 36, Jeremiah 52&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;After Josiah died, Judah came under the subjugation of Egypt, his son Jehoahaz took the throne and ruled for a monumental 3 month period, he was a wicked man who displeased Pharaoh Neco who had him imprisoned and he never returned to Judah. Neco made Eliakim (Josiah’s other son) king instead and changed his name to Jehoiakim. He was 25 years old and he reigned for only 11 years and Judah was required to pay tribute to Pharaoh Neco. Jehoiakim was also very wicked and it was toward the end of his rule that Babylon began its rise to power. Nebuchadnezzar took the throne of Babylon and overthrew the dominion of the Egyptians and when Jehoiakim rebelled against Babylon’s domination over Judah, Nebuchadnezzar marched against Judah and that was the end of Jehoiakim.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Upon Jehoiakim’s death, his son Jehoiachin took the throne of Judah. He was 18 years old and he ruled for only 3 months. Not a lot is stated about what he actually did...although we know he followed the ways of his wicked forefathers...so that meant his exploits included the murder of innocents, idol worship, pagan sacrifice, immorality and depravity...but his depravity far exceed that of his forbears...and he was only in power for 3 months!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God was so fed up with the sins of this people and most especially with the sins of the leaders of His people; when Jehoiachin took the throne and sinned like he did, God drew a line in the sand so to speak and issued a damning judgement upon him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Jeremiah 22:24-30, ‘”As I live,” declares the Lord, “even though Coniah the son of Jehoiakim king of Judah were a signet ring on My right hand, yet I would pull you off; and I will give you over into the hand of those who are seeking your life, yes, into the hand of those whom you dread, even into the hand of Nebuchadnezzar king of Babylon and into the hand of the Chaldeans. I will hurl you and your mother who bore you into another country where you were not born, and there you will die. But as for the land to which they desire to return, they will not return to it. Is this man Coniah a despised, shattered jar? Or is he an undesirable vessel? Why have he and his descendants been hurled out and cast into a land that they have not known? O land, land, land, hear the word of the Lord!” Thus says the Lord, “Write this man down childless, a man who will not prosper in his days; for no man of his descendants will prosper sitting on the throne of David or ruling again in Judah.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ok, this is really bad news, because this is the kingly line of David from which the Messiah was supposed to come from and then to rule and reign from David’s throne. God just placed a blood curse on this man and all his descendants making them ineligible to rule as Sovereign.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jehoiachin went into Babylonian captivity and he and his descendants died there.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This has left a whopping great big problem now...how do we get a legitimate Messiah and heir to the throne of David from his direct bloodline if there is now a curse on that bloodline? The Messiah cannot be tainted by a blood curse.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Matthew 1 lists Jehoiachin (Jeconiah/Coniah) in Yeshua’s genealogy and this provides legal proof of the lineage Joseph, the adoptive father of Yeshua. Here we have an established direct legal bloodline connection to the throne of David through the kingly line. But...this bloodline is tainted now because of the curse God placed on Jehoiachin stating that no child of this man’s descendant’s would sit on the throne of David.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The genealogy of Yeshua listed in Luke 3 however, takes the bloodline through David’s son Nathan rather than Solomon and then down to Mary’s father Heli who apparently had no sons only daughters. So both Mary and Joseph were of the tribe of Judah and were direct descendants of David...Joseph on the cursed side through Jehoiachin and Mary on the non-cursed side through Nathan.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Luke 3:23, ‘When He began His ministry, Jesus Himself was about thirty years of age, being, as was supposed, &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;the son of Joseph, the son of Heli.&lt;/span&gt;’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;But there’s an added twist. Matthew’s genealogy lists Joseph’s biological father as Jacob...Mary’s father was Heli...so which is it? This brings us to a SERIOUSLY important law that was instituted during the days of Moses...enter the Daughters of Zelephohad.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Numbers 26&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; we read the laws regarding inheritance which insisted that land and property were always handed down to the sons in order to keep the land within families and more importantly within tribes. Women marry and join other families and change their names, so land inheritance had to be maintained through the males to ensure land wasn’t ultimately lost to others.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;However, there was a man named Zelephohad and he only had daughters; the girls approached Moses and basically said that because there were no male heirs in their family, their land would be completely lost altogether if they – the daughters – couldn’t inherit. So Moses sought God’s about what needed to be done about it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The law was extended allowing daughters to inherit so long as they married within their own tribe so that the land would be retained...and their husbands would be ‘adopted’ as sons into their family in order to maintain the family line and inheritance. The husband’s didn’t stop exit or leave their own family lines, they were simply legally adopted into their wife’s family as well to protect the family inheritance.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is what happened with Joseph...Heli adopted Joseph which is why he was listed as Heli’s son in Luke’s genealogy and this has stunning implications.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Joseph wasn’t Yeshua’s biological father which meant that Yeshua didn’t have tainted human blood flowing through His veins, but because his step father was in the direct lineage of the kings of Judah, Yeshua has legal legitimacy to be the king of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Both his biological mother and his step father who was adopted into His maternal bloodline...a non-cursed maternal bloodline, gave Yeshua a curse-free direct ancestry to King David doubling His legitimate claim of being the king of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Because He was conceived by the Holy Spirit, His Father had to be God making Him the absolute ruler and King of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;On all points, Yeshua is the One and Only legitimate King of Israel and this is why Jehoiachin is so important as is the blood curse placed upon him. There could be no physical connection between any wicked king and the Messiah or Messiah would be a corrupted human being like the rest of us...yet He had to have legitimate connection via bloodline. He got this through His mother.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;At every point since the day God called Abraham, up to the birth of Yeshua, the odds have been 100% against the line of Messiah being fulfilled...satan has tried time and time again to wipe out the line of Messiah, wicked men have brought curses, wrath and judgement upon themselves and the people, enemies have worked endlessly to wipe out the Jews as the people of God and God Himself has cursed wicked Jewish leaders for their sin and rebellion and yet despite all this, GOD has seen to it that His Word has never failed, His plans have come to pass and His Son came to earth to be the Messiah for His people Israel and for the Gentile world fulfilling every requirement and criteria exactly as God said He would.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The wicked kings of Israel and Judah destroyed their nation, sent them into exile and after their return to Judah they never had a king of their own to rule over them again. They were longing for their Messiah and this was God’s promise to them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Isaiah 9:1-7, ‘But there will be no more gloom for her who was in anguish; in earlier times He treated the land of Zebulun and the land of Naphtali with contempt, but later on He shall make it glorious, by the way of the sea on the other side of Jordan, Galilee of the Gentiles. The people who walk in darkness will see a great light; those who live in a dark land, the Light will shine on them. You shall multiply the nation, You shall increase their gladness of harvest, as men rejoice when they divide the spoil. For You shall break the yoke of their burden and the staff on their shoulders, the rod of their oppressor, as at the battle of Midian. For every boot of the booted warrior in the battle tumult, and cloak rolled in blood, will be for burning fuel for the fire. For a child will be born to us, a son will be given to us; and the government will rest on His shoulders; and &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;His name will be called Wonderful, Counsellor, Mighty God, Eternal Father, Prince of Peace. &lt;/span&gt;There will be no end to the increase of His government or of peace, on the throne of David and over his kingdom, to establish it and to uphold it with justice and righteousness from then on and forevermore. The zeal of the Lord of Hosts will accomplish this.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This prophetic passage tells very clearly where Messiah would come from, that the people were living in darkness and in desperate need of a Messiah who would redeem and restore them bringing great light and deliverance to them;&amp;nbsp; that He would be born a physical human being...so He would be a ‘man’, but the titles given Him in this prophecy also declare Messiah to be God Himself!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is why Messiah had to be born of a woman – making Him human – but without an earthly father so He would bypass the hereditary sinful blood handed down to us by Adam.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Messiah was fully human and fully God...just as the Scriptures foretold.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;br /&gt;Mandy :-)&lt;/p&gt;",2012-08-17 01:25:50,mworby
7302,Home Group Notes - Josiah,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/1058605_60297588 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;239&quot; width=&quot;336&quot; /&gt;King Josiah (yo’she’ya’hu)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The name Josiah is made up of two elements. ‘Jah’ is an abbreviated form of the Tetragrammaton:- the Name of the Lord: YHWH.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The origin of the first part of Josiah however isn’t clear. It looks exactly the same as the verb ‘ya’ash’ which means to despair which means Josiah could mean, ‘The despair of Yahweh’, however, it could also be from the word ‘‘oshya’ which means buttress or pillar which would mean Josiah may mean ‘Yahweh Supports’. &amp;nbsp;But...this words is almost the same and ‘ashah’ which means ‘give’ and this could mean that Josiah means ‘Given of the Lord’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;More recent sources which believe Josiah means ‘Yahweh heals’ because they believe the name Josiah is imported from another language that uses the verb ‘rapa’ which in the Hebrew is ‘Rapha’ which means heal or healer and this has become the commonly held meaning.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Names in the Bible are very important and were given with purpose so I lean toward ‘Yahweh Supports’ and or ‘Given of the Lord’ with regard to the meaning of Josiah because these meanings are borne out in his life, I also lean toward these meanings because God named Josiah before he was even born detailing what he would do in his life to honour God and oppose apostasy and this demonstrates that Josiah was indeed given of the Lord and supported by the Lord in fulfilling his specific calling.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The story of Josiah is found in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 21, 22 &amp;amp; 23; 2 Chronicles 33, 34 &amp;amp; 35.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s interesting that the reign of Josiah was actually prophesied in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 13:1-2&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; when a man of God spoke against Jeroboam because of his wickedness in setting up pagan altars. The man of God said;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘”...O altar, altar, thus says the Lord, ‘Behold, a son shall be born to the house of David, Josiah by name; and on you he shall sacrifice the priests of the high places who burn incense on you, and human bones shall be burned on you.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This ‘man of God’ said that a man by the name of Josiah who was of the kingly line of David would destroy the paganism that Jeroboam had established and that the false priests themselves would die on those very altars.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is the how Josiah came to fulfil that prophetic word.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;After Manasseh died his son Amon became king of Judah. Amon didn’t follow the ways of his father who repented and turned to God at the latter end of his life, rather, he followed the ways of his father at the first part of his life when he was a raging pagan and murderer. Amon was 22 when he came to the throne and he only ruled for 2 years but he was hated by his own servants...so much so that they conspired against him and killed him. The people were furious at such treason and in turn killed the conspirators and proceeded to make Amon’s son Josiah king over Judah. Josiah was the ripe old age of 8 when he became king. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 21:18-22:1)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Now Josiah did what was right in the eyes of the Lord and &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 22:2&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; says he walked in the ways of his father ‘David’ and wouldn’t deviate one way or the other. His father Amon walked in the ways of Manasseh but Josiah walked in the ways of David. Josiah may very well have been a student of history...his personal family history, a young man who studied the lives of his forebears and this is why he behaved the way he did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The prophecy given to Jeroboam specifically said would be born of the ‘...house of David...’ and true to that prophecy, Josiah is associated with David specifically rather than Amon or Manasseh.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He had been king of Judah for 10 years, following the example of his great grandfather David, he was just a boy in many respects, and would have relied heavily on his adult advisors...but still, it was 10 years before Josiah sent Shaphan, the son of a well known Scribe to the house of the Lord...the Temple. The Temple had been allowed to fall into disrepair and had pretty much been deserted and Josiah wanted it opened up, cleaned up, repaired and restored to back to working and functional order. Money had been collected from the people for this task and builders were put to work to get the Temple up and running once more.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In the process of the cleanup, the Priest Hilkiah told Shaphan the Scribe that he’d found the Book of the Law of God. Shaphan the Scribe immediately took it to Josiah and read the entire thing out loud to him. Josiah’s response is shocking...he tore his clothes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Rending of garments was a demonstration of intense grief...in fact the practice is still done today (with a great deal of criteria and regulations) and it’s primarily done when a loved one dies. It’s signifying ‘death’ and grief over that death. When Josiah tore his own clothing upon hearing the Word of God read aloud to him, he knew that he and his people were in serious trouble. Why? He loved God and he had modelled his life after his grandfather David, who was the greatest king the nation of Israel had ever had!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The issue in play here however is that we are to model our lives on the Word of God not other people. There’s nothing wrong with having godly mentors or aspiring to live righteously as we see godly examples in the lives of others but men always fail. King David was a man with a heart after God’s own heart...but he was also an adulterer, a murderer, an insipid father and very proud. David was a great sinner who genuinely loved God with all his heart but daily battled with his flesh.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Josiah came face to face with the reality that while he wanted to serve God, he and his people were living their lives in a manner that not only disobeyed God’s laws but their behaviour’s and lifestyles were inviting God’s wrath and judgement. God promised very clearly in His law that if His people obeyed Him, He would provide for and protect them but if they didn’t obey Him, He would judge them and hand them over to their enemies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Having never heard the law of God meant that Josiah was living in ignorance. Not knowing it’s a sin to tell a lie doesn’t change the fact that lying is still a sin and an offense before God. Not knowing that you’re offending God doesn’t change the fact that you’re offending God. In &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Romans 7:13 Paul explains that “...through the commandment sin would become utterly sinful.”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; In other words, the power of the Law is in its purpose to reveal and expose sin and how sinful we are and this in turn reveals to us that we are ‘rightly’ under the judgement of God until and unless we confess our guilt over sin and repent of it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;As soon as Josiah understood their true sinful state before God he was immediately grieved and determined to seek God for forgiveness and a solution...he didn’t run from God...he didn’t try justify himself by saying...”I didn’t know any better”, he simply admitted his guilt and that of his people and their forefathers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 22:13, ‘”Go, inquire of the Lord for me and the people and all Judah concerning the words of this book that has been found, for great is the wrath of the Lord that burns against us, because our fathers have not listened to the words of this book, to do according to all that is written concerning us.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Huldah, the prophetess had a word from God for Josiah and the people in response to Josiah’s earnest desire to seek God for help.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The sin of the people was grievous and had to be judged. Their wickedness was so bad that God had no alternative but to bring judgement upon them...however, because the heart of the king was tender toward God and he so willingly and immediately humbled himself before God, God would stay His judgement until after Josiah’s life had come to an end. God’s prophesied king – Josiah by name – would never see the judgement of God fall because he was a righteous man.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Josiah ushered in a temporary reformation in the nation of Judah, as the leader of his nation he stood before the Lord in the Temple and made a covenant with God to keep His commandments and ordinances; he did away with all the paganism that was rampant throughout the land along with the false priests and prophets. He abolished the religious cult prostitution and banned all forms of witchcraft and creation worship. No High Places were left, no Ba’al worship or Asherah worship was permitted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;During his reign, Josiah regained much of the land that had been part of Israel, the Northern Kingdom and this allowed him to destroy the two golden calves that Jeroboam put in place when Israel split from Judah; Josiah destroyed and ground them to dust. Josiah went through the land and cleaned the place out from top to bottom. No more spiritists, mediums or clairvoyants were allowed to remain and after all that he proclaimed a nationwide celebration of the Passover feast.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s important to note that while Josiah implemented a huge amount of change and made laws that banned paganism, idolatry, immorality and occult practices, the hearts of the people were not transformed...human laws cannot regulate the wickedness of human hearts, that can only occur through the power and conviction of the Holy Spirit.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 23:25, ‘Before him there was no king like him who turned to the Lord with all his heart and with all his soul and with all his might, according to all the law of Moses; nor did any like him arise after him.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;His death was quite interesting; Pharaoh Neco of Egypt went to war against the Assyrian’s at God’s command and Josiah went to war against Pharaoh Neco which was most unusual because Neco wasn’t at war with Judah...but Assyria was most definitely an enemy of Judah...it would have made sense for Josiah to stand back and let the Egyptians destroy their Assyrian enemies. What on earth made Josiah go to war against Pharaoh Neco?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Sometime after the apostasy of Solomon and the nation of Israel was split in 2, the Ark of the Covenant went missing. It’s believed that it was hidden away or ‘secreted’ away before the Babylonian invasion and captivity. All the gold elements in the Temple were taken to Babylon and these items were mentioned by name but the Ark wasn’t...this is why many believe the Ark was sent away for safe keeping by a number of priests who were faithful to Yahweh and could see ahead of time that the Ark would fall into pagan hands if they didn’t hide it somewhere.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are some who believe that the Ark was hidden in Egypt under the knowledge and protection of Pharaoh Neco and that’s why Josiah refused to turn away from battle with him. Pharoah Neco to some degree, believed in Yahweh because he admitted to Josiah that he was warring against the Assyrians at God’s direction and therefore, tried to talk Josiah out of his aggression toward him. Josiah, in his enthusiasm to have God honoured and the Temple function completely reinstituted wanted the return of the Ark. Scripture does not spell this scenario out, this is only a theory but it’s a very curious and interesting possibility.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;During Josiah’s insistent pursuit of Pharaoh Neco, he was hit by an arrow and mortally wounded. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 35:22-24)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Because God is sovereign, I believe that God was directing Josiah in his pursuit to make sure he died at exactly the right time. You see, one of the most grievous sins committed by Judah was their refusal to allow the land to have a Sabbath rest. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 36:20-21)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Every 7 years, the land was to be left alone – to rest - and while God said their rampant sin, rebellion, idolatry and immorality was the reason they would have to endure judgement, the reason the judgement of exile to Babylon was to last 70 years was because that’s how many Sabbath years of rest the land had been denied. Josiah had to die at the right time to ensure his heirs – who were wicked – would rule after him for the right amount of time to fit into God’s plans.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are no errors or mistakes in how days, months and years unfold in the lives of individuals, families, communities and nations. God times everything to perfection and when it was time for Josiah to exit the scene, God was in complete control.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Josiah was an incredibly righteous and godly king, indeed, one of the very best the nation ever had and Judah mourned greatly for him at his passing. In fact, the prophet Jeremiah chanted a lament for Josiah and all the male and female singers used to sing their lamentations about him and they actually became ordinances in the nation. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 35:25)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The greatest lesson that we can learn from Josiah is that having wholesome motivations toward God isn’t enough to please God...we absolutely must read, know, understand, love and obey the Word of God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Isaiah 40:8, ‘The grass withers, the flower fades, but the Word of our God stands forever.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Matthew 5:18, ‘”For truly I say to you, until heaven and earth pass away, not the smallest letter or stroke shall pass from the Law until all is accomplished.’”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Matthew 24:35, ‘”Heaven and earth will pass away, but My words will not pass away.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Psalm 138:2, ‘”I will worship toward Your holy Temple, and praise Your name for Your lovingkindness and Your truth; &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;for You have magnified Your Word above all Your name.”’&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-wink.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Wink&quot; title=&quot;Wink&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-08-16 01:35:58,mworby
7239,Home Group Notes - Manasseh,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/724407_24295926 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;234&quot; width=&quot;312&quot; /&gt;King Manasseh (men-ash-sheh’)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The name ‘Manasseh’ is generally derived from the verb ‘nasha’ which basically means ‘forget’. To the Hebrew mind, this isn’t simply forgetting because something fades from our consciousness, but rather it’s a deliberate action of taking something away. More specifically, something was forgotten because God took something away. Because we know that God cannot not know something because God doesn’t forget the way we do, this is inferring that God actively pushes someone or something away in the same way that when God remembers someone He pulls them close, just like He did when He remembered His people in slavery in Egypt. &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(Gen 30:2)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; From this perspective ‘Manasseh’ means ‘Making To Forget’ (Pushing away)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This becomes more complicated however because there is another verb identical to ‘nasha’ which means to lend or be a creditor and these verbs are seen as separate because they denote different ideas. These verbs are intertwined however because if we lend to someone we in effect push that person away because they’re indebted to us – this is the Biblical mindset. When the debt is paid however, the person is then drawn closer to us. (Which is precisely what Christ did for us – forgiving our debt and our separation from the Father and bringing us close to Him)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;From this perspective ‘Manasseh’ means ‘From a debt’. A commonly held understanding of this name is ‘God has made me forget’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Considering everything Manasseh did during his 55 year reign in Judah and then what God did for him toward the end of his life, the meaning ‘From a debt’ and or ‘God has made me forget’ are quite appropriate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh’s story can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 21:1-17 and 2 Chronicles 33:1-20.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh was 12 years old when he came to the throne of Judah the Southern Kingdom. Israel, the Northern Kingdom was obliterated by the Assyrians; his father Hezekiah being a godly man, would have taught him about the wickedness of Israel and their destruction because of their sin, he would also have taught him that God was holy, just and absolutely faithful to protect and defend His people when they trusted and submitted themselves and their security to Him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;However, every believing parent knows that a child cannot have a relationship with God vicariously through them; the child has to have their own personal relationship with God for themselves.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh was an incredibly rebellious young man, in fact, reading about Manasseh you would come to the conclusion that he made it his sole mission in life to undo all the good that his father did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;First, he rebuilt the ‘High Places’ that Hezekiah his father had broken down. High Places were typically chosen by pagan religions for the worship of demons because the highest points were places of power. God had specifically instructed His people to worship Him in the Temple in Jerusalem with specific rituals and sacrifices. God will not tolerate demon worship on high places which undermined His supreme authority and power.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Second, he rebuilt shrines to Ba’al and Asherah. Remember that Ba’al was the chief god of Tyre and was considered to be the most powerful and supreme god. Hand in hand with Ba’al is Asherah, his female counterpart which was usually represented by a wooden pole with revolting images carved into it. Very often sacrifices were made at the base of the poles and also included fertility rituals as well...so sexual immorality became the order of the day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Third, he desecrated the Temple of God by placing altars for idol worship in it. It’s an abomination before God Almighty to re-establish the High Places and places of worship to Ba’al and Asherah throughout the land, but to actually place altars within the Temple of God itself to facilitate sacrifices to demon gods is abominable on a whole other level!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Four, he built altars of worship to ‘the Host of Heaven’. In other words he worshipped the sun, moon, stars and heavenly bodies. He worshipped the creation rather than the Creator.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Five, he sacrificed his own sons to the despicable demon god Molech. Some believed Molech to be another representation of Ba’al...there are varying reports on who or what Molech was but what is absolutely sure is that this demon god required the murder of innocent babies. He was believed to be represented by a brass statue that was hollow with his arms extended in front; a fire would be made in the base section until the entire statue was red hot and a tiny infant would be laid on his extended arms to be burnt to death. Manasseh did this to his own babies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Six, he murdered so many innocent people that the Bible says &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘he had filled Jerusalem from one end to another’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. His commitment to paganism (demon worship) drove him to kill...such is the end result of such devotion. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(2 Kings 21:16)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;You become like the gods you worship. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(Psa 115 &amp;amp; 97)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Because satan comes to steal, kill and destroy, those who worship satan, in whatever form he takes, will become just like him and Manasseh is a prime example of a man who became like the god he worshipped. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(John 10:10)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God judged Manasseh by having Assyria attack Jerusalem, they captured him and placed him in shackles and chains of brass and ultimately dumped him in a prison cell 1000 miles away in Babylon. He was humiliated and absolutely powerless over his situation but sitting in his prison cell caused him to remember his father and his father’s God – Jehovah – whom his father loved and served. &lt;strong&gt;There’s nothing like utter devastation to cause a man to repent and call upon God. &lt;/strong&gt;This is why tragedy and devastation are not necessarily bad but are the means by which God draws us to Himself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;And that’s exactly what Manasseh did...he prayed and he repented, he confessed his sin before God and asked Him for help.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chronicles 33:12-13, ‘When he was in distress, he entreated the Lord his God and humbled himself greatly before the God of his fathers. When he prayed to Him, He (God) was moved by his entreaty and heard his supplication, and brought him again to Jerusalem to his kingdom. Then Manasseh knew that the Lord was God.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh’s repentance was genuine; upon his return he worked hard to rebuild what had been broken and destroyed by the Assyrians; he re-established Judah’s military security, he removed the foreign pagan gods and the idols from the Temple, he removed the altars of paganism that he’d established in Jerusalem and tossed them outside the city. He returned to righteous worship and Temple sacrifices according to God’s instructions and what’s more, he ordered the people to return to the Lord as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Unfortunately, no man can bring about a genuine change in the heart of another person and the legacy of wickedness – idolatry, immorality, brutality – that Manasseh established during the majority of his reign was thoroughly ingrained in the people and in his own family and in his son and heir.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;So what can we learn from the life of King Manasseh of Judah? Well, our society...our intelligent, educated, enlightened and technologically advanced society is no different in heart and mind than Manasseh was.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Demon worship is prevalent in the unbelievable number of false religions throughout not only our own country but the world over;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Sex is big business and is no longer hidden away in dirty little porn shops hidden in back alleys, but is celebrated on TV and in movies, magazines, clothing stores...it is used to sell everything from cars, boats and even fishing tackle! Sexual immorality is rampant in our society and getting worse by the day and all manner of perversions are not only normalised, they’re celebrated and promoted as healthy alternate lifestyles.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We have even gone so far as to normalise STD’s (sexually transmitted diseases) which have resulted from promiscuity and perverted behaviours and treat them as though they’re no different than the common cold. God has designed our human bodies in such a way that they contract shocking diseases when we engage in sexual immorality...it’s God’s way of dissuading us from participating in depravity, but we simply invent medicines that allow us to engage in depravity and get away with it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Worship of creation has not only infiltrated our society in pagan religions such as Wicca, but it has invaded the education system under the guise of science. God Himself has been denied as our Creator and evolution has become the object of veneration...the creation has usurped God’s place.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Astrology and the worship of the heavens has been around forever, but horoscopes and fortune telling is a massive business today...how many ‘Christians’ can’t go past reading their daily horoscopes?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When it comes to sacrificing babies, our modern society beats Manasseh’s efforts hands down...it is hard to comprehend the number of innocent babies who have been slaughtered through abortion. Well over 100 million babies worldwide (50 million in the USA alone) have been sacrificed on the altar of convenience to appease the god of self-interest.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shedding innocent blood is not only a reference to the murder of unborn babies, shedding innocent blood also means killing of political opponents, killing those who don’t believe your religion, killing those who speak out against corruption, killing those who take action to bring about social and political changes that protect the people against despots and dictators. The world is reeling from wars and civil wars not simply in the past, but so many are happening right at this very moment!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The wonderful thing about Manasseh’s story that I love the most is the incredible picture we get of God’s stunning and unparalleled willingness to forgive and restore anyone who will genuinely repent.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh was about as wicked as a man could be; he committed the most heinous sins bringing about not only his own demise but the destruction of his people as well. He slaughtered tens of thousands of innocents and offended God in every way imaginable and yet, when Manasseh had a genuinely repentant heart and a complete change of mind and attitude, God immediately forgave him and brought about his return and restoration.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;How amazing is the mercy and grace of God!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There was still a legacy of wickedness that resulted from Manasseh’s sins that continued on through his family and among his people, but God utterly forgave Manasseh for every act of wickedness that he committed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We should take great comfort and assurance from that, because if God could forgive a man as wretched and depraved as Manasseh, He can also forgive us.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh reigned over Judah for 55 years, most of those years were spent committing all manner of crimes against God and his own people; in the latter part of his reign he was imprisoned in Babylon and ultimately returned to Jerusalem by God because of his genuine repentance. His reign was the longest of any Jewish king either in the northern or southern kingdoms and this shows us very dramatically the long-suffering, patient and merciful character traits of Yahweh.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There is no-one too wicked or too evil or too far gone that God cannot forgive, heal, save and restore. God’s love and forgiveness is vastly greater than our worst efforts at wickedness...He looks only for genuine repentance.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In and of ourselves we cannot bridge the gap from our own wickedness and depravity to becoming holy and acceptable to God and God knows this; this is why God sent His Son, Yeshua, to come to earth as a man, remain sinless and die a criminal’s death on the cross in order to pay for our sin. He died, was buried and three days later He rose to new life. This is not a fictional account; Yeshua was seen by more than 500 people at one time! He spoke, ate and taught His disciples after His resurrection and the New Testament contains these eye witness accounts and what has been proven repeatedly over the past 2000 years is the accuracy and authenticity of the Bible...both Old and New Testaments. You can trust the Bible to exactly what it claims to be...the Word of God Himself. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Cor 15:1-8; John 20:16-19, 21:1-14; Luke 24:40-43; Acts 1:9-11)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Salvation and forgiveness is available to all in the same manner as it came to King Manasseh...confession of sin, genuine repentance and faith in God to honour His promise of forgiveness to those who will call upon Him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Isaiah 1:18, ‘“Come now and let us reason together”, says the Lord, “Though your sins are as scarlet, they will be as white as snow; though they are red like crimson, they will be like wool.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Psalm 86:5, ‘”For You, Lord, are good, and ready to forgive, and abundant in lovingkindness to all who call upon You.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Psalm 103:17, ‘But the lovingkindness of the Lord is from everlasting to everlasting on those who fear Him, and His righteousness to children’s children.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If your desire is to become a believer and disciple of Christ, I would encourage you to spend some time talking with the Father, be honest and admit your sin and then repent. This is not a scary, nasty, judgemental word, rather it’s a glorious word of freedom because repentance brings about redemption and liberation from slavery to sin and replaces that slavery with relationship with the God of the Universe. Repentance is a magnificent gift from God to you. Put your faith in Him and the promise in His Word to forgive all who call upon Him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If this has been a starting point for you in your relationship with God, we’d love to know about it. Please contact us as we’d love to assist and encourage you in this most important and pivotal decision that you will ever make.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy&lt;/p&gt;",2012-08-09 00:13:42,mworby
7165,HOME GROUP notes: S.O.A.P Journalling,"&lt;p&gt;Do you have a habit of keeping a daily devotional time? Definitely a discipilne!&lt;br /&gt; Maybe you love reading THE&amp;nbsp;WORD&amp;nbsp;FOR&amp;nbsp;TODAY as we do, or some other kind of devo book? Great :)&lt;br /&gt; But there's something really powerful about reading a bible passage followed by  some time to reflect, &lt;br /&gt; apply and pray that message into your life!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://i3.squidoocdn.com/resize/squidoo_images/-1/lens2661292_1234609577journaling1.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width: 141px; height: 107px;&quot; hspace=&quot;5&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 14px;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;Journalling&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is an excellent way to both record and process what God has  spoken to us. &lt;br /&gt; It's also a useful tool to use at a later time, to reflect  on and review some of the 'gems' that you have received. &lt;br /&gt; Without  writing them down, you may forget those blessings and some very  important lessons! &lt;br /&gt; And while journalling is a very personal time with the  Lord, &lt;br /&gt; you may want to share some of your daily journalling and encourage others. &lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;font-size: 18px;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;S.O.A.P&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;: (S)cripture, (O)bservation, (A)pplication and (P)rayer!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span data-ft=&quot;{&amp;quot;type&amp;quot;:3}&quot; class=&quot;messageBody&quot;&gt;All you need is:&lt;br /&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span data-ft=&quot;{&amp;quot;type&amp;quot;:3}&quot; class=&quot;messageBody&quot;&gt;- a bible (we prefer  the NLT) &lt;br /&gt; - a journal notebook &lt;br /&gt; - a bible reading plan (Google will find you  plenty of bible reading plans) &lt;br /&gt; - a pen or pencil. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span data-ft=&quot;{&amp;quot;type&amp;quot;:3}&quot; class=&quot;messageBody&quot;&gt;You can listen to our podcast, or hear Wayne Cordeiro, from New Hope Hawaii talking  all about it here :) &lt;br /&gt; &lt;a rel=&quot;nofollow nofollow&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;http://www.facebook.com/l.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Fvimeo.com%2F2043831&amp;amp;h=FAQFH4MIWAQE5x9DwVw5pSP_4JzI86AAowlwS-anUohZOew&quot;&gt;http://vimeo.com/2043831&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;",2012-08-02 01:40:38,krhunt
7083,Home Group Notes - Hezekiah,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/575231_55762839 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;179&quot; width=&quot;239&quot; /&gt;King Hezekiah (khiz-ke’ya / khiz-ke’yahu)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The name ‘Hezekiah’ is made up of two elements. The first part – ‘hazaq’ means to be or become courageous or strong, the second part – ‘jah’ (Yah) is God’s name, ‘Yahweh.’ So Hezekiah means “Yahweh strengthens’ or ‘Yahweh has strengthened” or “the Strength of the Lord”.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;You can learn about King Hezekiah in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings chapters 16 to 21; 1 Chronicles 4, 2 Chronicles chapters 28 to 33&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hezekiah became king of Judah, the Southern Kingdom and he was a very good king. He was only 25 years old when he ascended the throne and he ruled in Jerusalem for 29 years. He did right in the sight of the Lord...most of the time we read that many kings who ruled in Israel and Judah &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘did evil in the sight of the Lord’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; so it’s really refreshing when reading through Kings and Chronicles to come upon a verse that says, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“and he did right in the sight of the Lord.”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;By the time Hezekiah took the throne of Judah, Israel (the Northern Kingdom) had already been destroyed by the Assyrians and most had gone into captivity.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Upon becoming king, Hezekiah believed it was essential that he and his people get their spiritual lives together and in the first year of his rule he opened up and repaired the doors of the house of the Lord. Under the previous leadership, the Temple and the things of God had been ignored and had fallen into disrepair. The people had been guilty of sin and idolatry and Hezekiah meant to put things right.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Do you remember the bronze serpent that Moses made in the wilderness? Over the centuries this had become an object of idolatrous worship and Hezekiah destroyed it and he also removed the high places and cut down all the Asherah as well. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 18:1-5)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;King Hezekiah was responsible for a great spiritual revival in Judah and it began when he turned his focus on the religious leadership. Hezekiah reinstituted worship in the Temple, he brought in the priests and the Levites and when he gathered them together he said to them, “&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He said to the religious leaders...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chron 29:5-11, ‘...”Listen to me, O Levites. Consecrate yourselves now, and consecrate the house of the Lord, the God of your fathers, and carry the uncleanness out from the Holy Place. For our fathers have been unfaithful and have done evil in the sight of the Lord our God, and have forsaken Him and turned their faces away from the dwelling place of the Lord, and have turned their backs. They have also shut the doors of the porch and put out the lamps, and have not burned incense or offered burnt offerings in the holy place to the God of Israel. Therefore the wrath of the Lord was against Judah and Jerusalem, and He has made them an object of terror, of horror, and of hissing, as you see with your own eyes. For behold, our fathers have fallen by the sword, and our sons and our daughters and our wives are in captivity for this. Now it is in my heart to make a covenant with the Lord God of Israel that His burning anger may turn away from us. My sons, do not be negligent now, for the Lord has chosen you to stand before Him, to minister to Him, and to be His ministers and burn incense.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The encouraging thing in this situation is that the priests and Levites responded rightly. They immediately set about consecrating themselves and getting their sacred religious system cleaned up and back into function and service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;With their (religious leaders) hearts now resolute to worship God, Hezekiah turned his attention from them put it squarely on the national and civic leaders of Judah. In &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 20&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Hezekiah got up early, assembled all the ‘princes of the city’ and promptly led them all up to the Temple and then the process of purification began: there was sacrifice for the kingdom, for the sanctuary and for Judah, for the sins of the people and it says in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 24&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, that Hezekiah ordered burnt offerings for all of Israel. This probably meant that he was including Israel, the former Northern Kingdom in the offerings being made. Scripture doesn’t spell this out, but this is a real possibility because Israel the Northern Kingdom has been destroyed by the Assyrians and taken captive, so when &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 21&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; specifies offerings on behalf of Judah and &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 24&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; specifies ‘all Israel’; Hezekiah was wanting to seek God’s forgiveness on ALL of Israel...both north and south. Because Israel and Judah were both guilty of rebellion and idolatry before God they were both under God’s wrath and righteous judgement; Israel had already been destroyed but Judah was also in line for judgement and Hezekiah knew that Judah would end up like Israel if they didn’t repent.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What’s important to note however is that this event was positively huge. During this time of consecration and purification 70 bulls, 100 rams, 200 lambs were sacrificed as burnt offerings. On top of that a further 600 bulls and 3000 sheep were offered as sacrifices as well. This was a bloodbath...just under 4000 animals (3970) were slaughtered in a day in the same spot. There were so many animals that needed skinning that the priests simply couldn’t handle the numbers and had to call upon their Levite brothers to help them with the job. The purpose of these sacrifices was spiritual cleansing and consecration. The number of animals sacrificed shows the level of seriousness and commitment held by the priests and particularly the Levites.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s really important that we understand that sin is the most expensive thing in the universe (as well as the most destructive). The number of animals who forfeited their lives to cover the sins of the people in these events was phenomenal and they were only temporary!!! It took the very life of Yeshua, the Son of the Living God to sacrifice His own life to ensure our sin could be washed away permanently. Sin is incredibly expensive and our Saviour paid the most extreme and expensive price to pay for our forgiveness. I need to keep that in mind the next time I’m tempted to sin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This also demonstrated the enormity and severity needed for gaining right standing or ‘righteousness’ with God and with the return of Temple service, there was great rejoicing not only on behalf of Hezekiah, but also among the people in attendance because revival had broken out and it had happened suddenly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;So that took care of the religious leaders and the civic leaders; next Hezekiah sent letters throughout the nation calling on them to come to the House of the Lord to celebrate the Feast of Passover to the Lord. This was a call to reinstate the full celebration because it had only been minimally attended in previous years. This was God using Hezekiah to call the people to repentance and to return to Him fully.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chron 30:6, ‘The couriers went throughout all Israel and Judah with the letters from the hand of the king and his princes, even according to the command of the king, saying, “O sons of Israel, return to the Lord God of Abraham, Isaac and Israel, that He may return to those of you who escaped and are left from the hand of the kings of Assyria. Do not be like your fathers and your brothers, who were unfaithful to the Lord God of their fathers, so that He made them a horror as you see. Now do not stiffen your neck like your fathers, but yield to the Lord and enter His sanctuary which he has consecrated forever, and serve the Lord your God, that His burning anger may turn away from you. For if you return to the Lord, your brothers and your sons will find compassion before those who led them captive and will return to this land. For the Lord your God is gracious and compassionate, and will not turn His face away from you if you return to Him.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Here again we see Hezekiah wanting to reach out to the northern tribes as far as Zebulun, which is the Galilee region; his desire was to reach out to any of his people who remained there after the Assyrian invasion and destruction. Hezekiah was in fact calling for revival among his people to reunite them and draw them back to the Lord. Unfortunately, most of the remaining northern tribes laughed at them and mocked them...obviously near total annihilation didn’t soften their hearts, but there were some from the tribes of Asher, Manasseh and Zebulun who humbled themselves and came to Jerusalem for the Passover. This Passover event dwarfed the Temple consecration event in that 2,000 bulls and 17,000 sheep were sacrificed...a total of 19,000 animals. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(2 Chron 30:24)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hezekiah is noted for bringing revival to the people of Israel and for uniting the separated brethren from the north. This was a remarkable thing that he did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hezekiah was successful in his wars against the Philistines and he retook all the cities that his father had lost to them as well as others &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 18:7-8; 2 Chron 28:18)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and Hezekiah was alive during the life of the prophet Isaiah and relied heavily on the prophet of God for counsel and it was at Isaiah’s word that he revolted against the King of Assyria and refused to pay him tribute. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 18:7)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; This revolt led to the invasion by Sennacherib, initially Hezekiah tried to ‘pay off’ Sennacherib but this apparently wasn’t enough and he set a siege about Jerusalem. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 18:14-16)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; He sent a nasty man by the name of Rabshakeh to undermine the confidence of the Jews by telling them not to be so stupid in trusting Yahweh and Hezekiah because no god of any nation had been able to withstand the might and power of Assyria and if they didn’t surrender they would all be wiped out. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 18:17-35)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;During the siege Hezekiah became very sick and Isaiah visited him and told him to get his house in order because he was going to die. Now the kingdom was in danger because Hezekiah had no heir, his son Manasseh was born 3 years later – so his death would end his dynasty and he prayed desperately to God and he wept bitterly over this situation. God immediately spoke to Isaiah who went straight back to Hezekiah and told him that God heard his prayer and was going to give him another 15 years of life. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 20:1-11; 2 Chron 32:24-26)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hezekiah went to the Temple to pray to the Lord to act on their behalf, he was the first king of Judah to do such a thing since the time of Solomon! He actually spread open the letters sent to him by Sennacherib before the Lord in the Temple and prayed that God would deliver Jerusalem for this fierce enemy. Isaiah the prophet prophesied that Sennacherib would never again attack the Holy City and what’s more, the entire Assyrian army was destroyed in one night by ‘Angel of the Lord’. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 19; 2 Chron 32:9-22)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; God proved Himself to be absolutely trustworthy and what’s more, Isaiah his prophet was proven to be a real prophet unlike the plethora of false prophets who were repeatedly wrong.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hezekiah’s victory made him famous and elevated him very quickly among the surrounding nations who proceeded to bring him presents. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 32:23)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; One of the visiting nations was Babylon, in fact they had heard that Hezekiah had been miraculously healed and this visit was ostensibly to see if the reports of healing and wealth in the nation were in fact true.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Unfortunately, Hezekiah was probably feeling a bit puffed up and proud after coming through the siege and certain death unscathed. He unwisely showed all Israel’s wealth and power to the Babylonian ambassador and for this Isaiah promptly and severely rebuked him because Hezekiah’s actions demonstrated his trust in his wealth and military might which of course was misplaced, his faith was to be in God alone. To his credit, Hezekiah repented immediately. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 20:12-19)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; However, the one sad thing about this episode is Hezekiah’s attitude to the judgement that would come upon his children as a result of his pride...he didn’t seem at all perturbed about what his heirs would experience, he was just relieved that he wouldn’t live to experience it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-left: 8px; float: right;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/_dsc0168.jpg&quot; height=&quot;470&quot; width=&quot;312&quot; /&gt;Hezekiah did however build an incredible water tunnels hewn through solid rock to ensure there would always be a supply of fresh water to the city and the people. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 32:30)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; These tunnels are positively enormous and were constructed with several teams of workers who began the work at either end of the tunnels digging until the each met in the middle!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Manasseh his son became king after Hezekiah died, he was only 12 when he took the throne...unfortunately, Manasseh was a very wicked king and I can’t help but wonder if God’s initial plan to allow Hezekiah to die 15 years earlier might have spared Judah one of their worst ever kings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Sometimes when God allows or disallows things in our lives we think God is being unfair but in fact God knows what is best for us. If Hezekiah had died when he first fell sick, his wicked son would never have been born and thus he wouldn’t have been a wicked king who led the people back into sin and depravity. Perhaps a relative of Hezekiah would have come to the throne and been a really godly man. Not only that, Hezekiah wouldn’t have fallen into terrible pride by showed off all the wealth and power of his kingdom to the Babylonians who later on invaded them to get their hands on it. This would have spared his family line of future judgement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Who knows?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The disturbing thing about Hezekiah at the end of his life is not that he turned away from the Lord, because he didn’t, unfortunately his attitude toward his descendants was quite blasé; when Isaiah informed him that his pride and arrogance would result in judgement upon his son, he seemed completely non-plussed about it. Since he himself was going to be spared the judgement it didn’t worry him what would befall his son.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Hezekiah was one of the best kings Judah ever had and among the Rabbi’s he is revered because he brought revival to his nation and he honoured God and restored proper reverent worship and service to the Temple, but the lesson we can learn from Hezekiah is to take the legacy we leave to our own children and grandchildren seriously.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are broken families and broken family relationships all around us and as parents we must recognise that from the moment we become married, our attitude should no longer be ‘I’ but ‘WE’. When we become parents, our attitude is now supposed to be about ‘WE’ and ‘THEM’ and the choices we make must be first and foremost about considering what is good, right and profitable for the well-being and betterment of our children as well as each other.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God entrusts our children to us for a few short years, our decisions and choices can and should be of great benefit to them and their security, but wrong and selfish decisions they can be catastrophic to them. I want my legacy to my children and grandchildren be that of great blessing, security and stability, I’m sure you feel the same.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-wink.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Wink&quot; title=&quot;Wink&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-07-26 00:20:52,mworby
7007,Home Group Notes - Ancient Jewish Wedding,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 2px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/320472_10150963399582099_823209540_n.jpg&quot; title=&quot;Steve &amp;amp; Jehan Wedding Vows&quot; class=&quot;caption&quot; height=&quot;183&quot; width=&quot;326&quot; /&gt;Ancient Jewish Wedding&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The key players are; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The Father: &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; This is reflected in God the Father&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The Groom:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; This is reflected in the person of Yeshua&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The Bride&lt;strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/strong&gt;This is reflected in the church; the Bride of Christ&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The elements that make up the Ancient Jewish Wedding are:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Ketubah (Betrothal/Wedding Contract)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When a young man wanted to marry a young woman, he would prepare a covenant which he would present to the young woman and her father in the young woman’s home. The covenant itself would present the groom’s willingness to provide for and protect the young woman and it would present the price he was willing to pay for her. It was very much like a purchase of sorts. While socially, males were considered more valuable in ancient times because they were physically more capable of working hard to earn a living with hard labour and farming etc; however - while the bride price was a compensation for the woman’s family for the cost of raising her, it was so much more than that, it was very much an indication of just how valuable she was to the prospective groom. The young man would present his covenant to the young woman and her father for acceptance.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Yeshua&lt;/em&gt;, the heavenly Bridegroom, came to the home of His intended Bride and presented His marriage covenant. The ‘New Covenant’ as we know it, contained all the benefits that would provide for His Bride. He would provide her a mansion, He would provide her every need, He would see all her sins washed away, He would sanctify and purify her, He would glorify her with a new body and eternal security, He would honour her and bless her with every spiritual blessing, and the price He would be willing to pay to secure her as His own Bride was His very life, which He would willingly offer to be tortured and crucified in order to secure His Bride for Himself.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Jer 31:31; Luke 22:20; Heb 9:15; 12:24)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-left: 8px; float: right;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/532498_10150963399857099_1629701558_n.jpg&quot; height=&quot;184&quot; width=&quot;330&quot; /&gt;The Acceptance&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If the bride price was acceptable to the father of the bride – meaning the price was commensurate with her value - the young man would pour a glass of wine for the bride and if she willing drank it, it would indicate her acceptance of the proposal. It was at this point that the young couple were considered betrothed. This betrothal was a legally binding agreement. Today, if a couple become engaged, they can easily break up if they choose, but betrothal in ancient Jewish culture was considered to be as strong as the marriage relationship itself, the only difference being that physical union had not taken place.&amp;nbsp;If separation was desired at some point, a legal divorce was required.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Yeshua&lt;/em&gt;, poured a cup of wine for the Bride to drink to seal the marriage contract in the same way He poured wine for His disciples to drink. His words described the significance of the cup as the bride price; &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;‘Then He took the cup, gave thanks and offered it to them, say, “Drink from it, all of you. This is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many for the forgiveness of sins. I tell you, I will not drink of this fruit of the vine from now on until that day when I drink it anew with you in my Father’s kingdom.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; The disciples drank of the cup, thus accepting the contract. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(Matt 26:28-29)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;This cup will be drunk during the Marriage Supper of the Lamb! &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Rev 19:1-21; John 14:2-3; Matt 22:1-14, 25:1-46)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/575887_10150963400182099_1520226475_n.jpg&quot; height=&quot;191&quot; width=&quot;338&quot; /&gt;The Gifts&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The bridegroom would then present gifts to the bride and their purpose was to show his appreciation of the bride and they also were intended to help her remember him during the imminent betrothal period when they wouldn’t see each other &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;at all&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Yeshua&lt;/em&gt; has given gifts to His betrothed also. He promised the gift of the Holy Spirit which would remind us of our Groom and all that He taught. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 John 4:13)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Yeshua described this gift in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;John 14:26: ‘But the Counsellor, the Holy Spirit, whom the Father will send&amp;nbsp; in My name, will teach you all things and will remind you of everything I have said to you. Peace I leave with you; My peace I give you. I do not give to you as the world gives. Do not let your hearts be troubled, and do not be afraid.’ &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;He has given us His Word which is the instrument of transformation, purification and preparation, readying us for His imminent return for us. He has given us spiritual gifts to use during our preparation time to learn how to be His bride and the fruit of the Spirit that grows in us is demonstration of our preparedness. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Rom 12; 1 Cor 12; Eph 4; Gal 5)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;The Separation&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The typical betrothal period was between 1 and 2 years and during this time the bride and bridegroom wouldn’t see each other, they would in fact be in preparations for their marriage. The groom would be in his father’s home making and preparing a home for himself and his bride to dwell in once they were married, and fitting the home out with all that they would need for their life together. The bride would be making preparations for her big day and also for the things she would need to be a good wife upon her marriage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Yeshua&lt;/em&gt; also said He would go away and prepare a place for His Bride in His Father’s home. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“In My Father’s house are many dwelling places; if it were not so, I would have told you; for I go to prepare a place for you. If I go and prepare a place for you, I will come again and receive you to Myself, that where I am, there you may be also.” (John 14:2-3)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;During this betrothal separation period, the bride was also required to partake of a &lt;em&gt;Mikveh&lt;/em&gt;, or a ritual cleansing bath. The word ‘mikveh’ is the same word used for baptism and to this day in Conservative Judaism, a bride cannot marry unless she enters the water of the Mikveh.&amp;nbsp;The Mikveh is a ceremonial demonstration of a person transitioning from unclean to clean, defiled to purified, old to new, death to life.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-left: 8px; float: right;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/548178_10150962562372099_1477957677_n.jpg&quot; height=&quot;209&quot; width=&quot;372&quot; /&gt;Yeshua also provided for His Bride to participate in baptism of both water and the Holy Spirit. Water baptism takes place in many places in the New Testament; after His ascension He gave this command, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Do not leave Jerusalem, but wait for the gift My Father promised, which you have heard Me speak about. For John baptised with water, but in a few days you will be baptised with the Holy Spirit.” (Acts 1:4, 11:16) (Acts 2:38, 41, 8:12, 36-38, 9:18, 10:47-48, 16:15, 33, 18:8, 19:5, 22:16; Rom 6:3; Gal 3:27)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It was during the betrothal separation period that the groom was also preparing the bridal chamber, which had to be a beautiful place to bring his bride. The groom had to build it to the father’s specifications and the young groom could only go for his bride when his father had approved all that he had done. If the bridegroom was asked when the wedding was to take place, he would probably respond by saying, &lt;em&gt;“it’s not for me to know, only my father knows.”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;As mentioned, our own Bridegroom promised to go away and prepare a place for His Bride in His Father’s house and the preparations continue to this very day. We wonder when His return for us will be, and when His disciples asked Him when He would return, Yeshua responded by saying, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“No one knows about that day or hour, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son, but only the Father. Be on guard! Be alert! You do not know when that time will come.” (Mark 13:32-33) &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;While the bridegroom was making preparations, the bride was considered to be consecrated, set apart or &lt;em&gt;‘bought with a price’&lt;/em&gt;. If she went out, she would wear a veil so that others would know she was betrothed, and promised to another. She had probably saved money all her life in anticipation for this momentous time. She would obtain cosmetics and learn to apply them as a means of beautifying herself for her bridegroom. She would get her wedding gown, all her clothing and possessions prepared and ready at all times because the arrival of her bridegroom was a secret. Typically, the bridegroom would come in the middle of the night to &lt;em&gt;‘steal her away’&lt;/em&gt; or...to come like a &lt;em&gt;‘thief in the night’&lt;/em&gt;. The bride’s attendants would also be prepared, watching and waiting in anticipation, keeping their lamps filled and trimmed in order to be ready at all times for the imminent night festivities.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/403869_10150984719188183_703958637_n.jpg&quot; height=&quot;231&quot; width=&quot;345&quot; /&gt;Yeshua’s Bride has been consecrated and set apart, saved by faith and declared justified. We are waiting the return of our Bridegroom and our time here is to be spent in preparing ourselves for Him. It was the parable of the Ten Virgins that Yeshua used to inform us that we needed to be ready and watching at all times, keeping our lamps filled and trimmed, remaining alert and watchful in order to be ready when He returned at whatever time that might be. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Matt 25:1-13)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Rev 19:7, ‘Let us rejoice and be glad and give the glory to Him, for the marriage of the Lamb has come and His bride has made herself ready.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Eph 5:25-29, ‘Husbands, love your wives, just as Christ also loved the church and gave Himself up for her, so that He might sanctify her, having cleansed her by the washing of water with the Word, that He might present to Himself the church in all her glory, having no spot or wrinkle or any such thing; but that she would be holy and blameless. So husbands ought to love their own wives as their own bodies. He who loves his own wife loves himself; for no one ever hated his own flesh, but nourishes and cherishes it, just as Christ also does the church.’ &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It is no coincidence that Yeshua uses the marriage relationship between men and women to describe His relationship to the church!!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;The Surprise Arrival&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When the bridegroom’s father deemed that all was ready, he would tell his son to go and get his bride. The bridegroom would abduct his bride secretly, like a thief in the night and take her to the wedding chamber. As he approached the bride’s house, he would shout out loud and blow the shofar (rams horn) so that she would have at least some small warning to gather her prepared belongings to take with her. The bridegroom and his friends would come into the bride’s house and get the bride and her attendants.&amp;nbsp; In the same way, &lt;em&gt;Yeshua&lt;/em&gt; our Bridegroom, will come for us at a time not of our knowing, but He will come like a thief in the night, He will &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“...descend from heaven with a shout, with the voice of the archangel and with the trumpet of God, and the dead in Christ will rise first. Then we who are alive and remain will be caught up together with them in the clouds to meet the Lord in the air, and so we shall always be with the Lord.”&amp;nbsp; (1 Thess 4:16-17) &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;The Huppah and Seven Days of Celebration&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Once the groom receives his bride, the now much bigger bridal party make their way to the father’s house where the wedding guests have assembled and are awaiting the arrival of the happy couple. Shortly after arriving, the bride and groom are escorted by their attendants to the wedding chamber, also known as the Huppah and during all the proceedings up to this point, the bride is veiled so that no one can see her face. While the attendants remain outside, the bride and groom enter the Huppah alone and in the privacy of this place, they consummate their marriage with physical union, the ultimate sealing of the marriage covenant that was entered into 1 or 2 years earlier. Once consummation has taken place, this is announced by the groom to his attendants, upon which the happy news is relayed to the guests who then begin their celebrations which will last 7 days and during this week, the bride and groom remain hidden away together. When the 7 days are complete, the groom emerges from the Huppah to present his wife, introducing her to the community.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Yeshua&lt;/em&gt;, our Bridegroom, will also keep His Bride secreted away during a seven year time of testing on the earth, such as has never been seen before. During this time of great trouble and distress, the righteous will be protected because they will be in the wedding chamber with the Bridegroom. After this time of testing, Yeshua will emerge and will return with His Bride to earth at His second coming.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-left: 8px; float: right;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/3053_10150984720388183_1589630242_n.jpg&quot; height=&quot;311&quot; width=&quot;467&quot; /&gt;There are several things of great significance for me personally, after I learned about the ancient Jewish wedding. Firstly, my confidence in God’s Word increased exponentially and it’s made me realise just how important ancient Jewish culture is if I want to have a clearer understanding of Scripture and its relevance to me and my relationship with Christ.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Secondly, I have a greater awareness of the prophetic implications of ancient Jewish culture and how these have previously and continue to unfold in the plan of God for human history. It’s as though God is telling us in advance in a myriad of ways what He’s going to do and how He’s going to do it. If we don’t see it one way, we can see it in another and each way confirms the other...always remembering that the Word of God is supreme in all things. Jewish tradition never trumps Scripture, rather ancient Jewish traditions should mirror what is laid out in the Scripture not the other way around.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Thirdly, it’s a confirmation to me that God is not only the author of the Bible, He is also the orchestrator of all of human history and He is ensuring that all things unfold according to His design and prophetic plans.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Fourthly, I wish I had learned of the significance and importance of ancient Jewish culture and customs much earlier in my Christian walk so that I could have had a far greater understanding of the Word of God and God’s prophetic plan and timetable. I could have avoided a lot of error and misapplication of the Word had the foundations of Jewish culture and practices been explained. The lack of understanding and appreciation of the Jewishness of the Bible has robbed the church of so much richness and understanding which is a great shame.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;At least we have the opportunity to learn it now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-kiss.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Kiss&quot; title=&quot;Kiss&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.khouse.org/articles/2003/449/&quot;&gt;http://www.khouse.org/articles/2003/449/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bridalcovenant.com/wedding1.html&quot;&gt;http://www.bridalcovenant.com/wedding1.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-07-19 00:45:42,mworby
6765,Home Group Notes - Athaliah &amp; Joash,"&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/1058605_60297588 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;215&quot; width=&quot;300&quot; /&gt;Athaliah (Ath-al-ya)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are several complexities in coming to a correct understanding of this name, it’s made up of two parts, the first of which doesn’t occur in the Hebrew Bible and the Jones Dictionary of Old Testament Proper Names takes the meaning of this name from an Arabian root meaning ‘to handle violently’ and reads as ‘Taken Away of the Lord’. Other theological dictionaries don’t try to translate her name but propose its roots in an Assyrian verb that means to ‘Grow Great’ or ‘Great Exalted’. Others however believe this name means ‘Yahweh Is Exalted.’ This could possibly be true because Ahab gave his other children names that were honourable to Yahweh even though he himself was a pagan and dishonoured God in every aspect and action of his life.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Athaliah’s story can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 8, 9 &amp;amp; 11, and 2 Chronicles 21 &amp;amp; 22&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Athaliah (Ath-al-ya) was Ahab and Jezebel’s daughter, she was raised in an incredibly wicked environment where she saw rampant paganism, wanton murder of innocent men who were faithful to Yahweh, the One True God and the deliberate murder of an innocent man – Naboth the Jezreelite - so that her father could take possession of his property to grow a veg patch! Athaliah was heavily influenced by her parents, most especially by her mother Jezebel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;A few weeks ago we looked at the life of King Jehoshaphat who was king of Judah, the Southern Kingdom. He was a very godly king but unwise in his alliances with the wicked kings of Israel, the Northern Kingdom. One of the dreadful mistakes that Jehoshaphat made was to make a political alliance with Israel by marrying his son Jehoram (also called Joram) to Athaliah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;After Jehoshaphat died, Jehoram became king of Judah and he was a wicked king who walked in the ways of his father-in-law Ahab, mainly because of the wicked influence of his wife Athaliah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 8:18, ‘He walked in the way of the kings of Israel, just as the house of Ahab had done, for the daughter of Ahab became his wife; and he did evil in the sight of the Lord.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It was Athaliah’s influence that turned Jehoram away from the godly example of his father Jehoshaphat to follow the reprobate example of his in-laws. It is a lesson for all women...though we are considered the weaker sex (physically) we actually have incredible power to influence our men and those around us, and we need to make sure that any influence we do have is godly and righteous.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;After Jehoram died, his son Ahaziah (akh-az-ya) became king and he was also a wicked king. Ahaziah was Athaliah’s son, and a man named Jehu killed Ahaziah and this opened the door for Athaliah to declare herself Queen of Judah and using her dominating influence, she reigned exactly like her mother in that she fostered the worship of Ba’al throughout Judah temporarily pushing the worship of Yahweh into the background.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Athaliah seized the throne she immediately murdered every child who was an heir to the throne - she murdered her own grandchildren – all except for one; Joash (Yeh-ho-arsh) who was one year old. His sister and his nurse hid him to save his life, and he was secreted away to the Temple where he was protected and raised (along with his nurse) by Jehoiada the priest. For six years they lived inside the Temple proper, living in secret daily and under the threat of death. If his existence had been discovered by Athaliah or any of her co-horts, not only would Joash’s life been forfeit, so would all who had participated in his rescue as well as those who were maintaining the secret.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 11:1-3, ‘When Athaliah the mother of Ahaziah saw that her son was dead, she rose and destroyed all the royal offspring. But Jehosheba, the daughter of King Joram, sister of Ahaziah, took Joash the son of Ahaziah and stole him from among the king’s son’s who were being put to death, and placed him and his nurse in the bedroom. So they hid him from Athaliah, and he was not put to death&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;.&lt;strong&gt; So he was hidden with her in the house of the Lord six years while Athaliah was reigning over the land.’&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Athaliah reigned in Judah for six years after which Jehoiada the priest in conjunction with the army and the temple guards brought the young prince out into the public and proceeded with a coronation making Joash the rightful king of Judah. Athaliah tore her clothes and screamed &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Treason! Treason!”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jehoiada the priest then directed the captains of the army to seize her and remove her from the House of the Lord and took her to the entrance of the king’s house and executed her there. The people then went to the house of Ba’al and tore it down along with his images and altars and killed Mattan the priest of Ba’al.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The young king Joash who was then seven years old, was led to his throne and the people of Judah rejoiced because they were finally free of wicked false Queen Athaliah and their rightful, lawful king was now on the throne. Young king Joash was mentored through his life by the priest Jehoiada who was a very godly man.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Joash (Yeh’ho’arsh)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It was quite hard to find the meaning of this name, however a little extra digging revealed the meaning to be ‘Whom Jehovah gave’ or ‘Given by Jehovah’. I could find no history or background to this name.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We’ve just learned that Joash is the grandson of Athaliah and Jehoram. It’s unknown if or how many wives his father Ahaziah had, but it’s safe to say &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“all the royal offspring”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; meant that Joash had quite a few siblings who were each in line for the throne of Judah after their father. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Kings 11:1-3)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahaziah wasn’t a particularly good king because his parents – Jehoram and Athaliah – were both very wicked Ba’al worshippers. Jehoram died leaving the throne to Ahaziah who also died, opening the way for Athaliah to seize the throne for herself. Before Joash could be murdered with the rest of his siblings, his sister and nurse along with Jehoiada the priest raised him in secret in the Temple. At the ripe old age of seven, Joash underwent his coronation and his grandmother Athaliah was executed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Joash’s story can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Kings 11, 12&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt;and &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chronicles 22, 24&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jehoiada (Yeh-ho-ya’da) the priest became the personal tutor/guardian to you Joash and he guided the young king to re-establish the rightful worship of Yahweh, unfortunately, he didn’t remove the ‘high places’ that had been used for pagan worship.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;One of the first things Joash did was to repair the Temple which had been defiled by Athaliah and her other children who had used Temple articles in the worship of Ba’al, all the people contributed to the funding of this project, it took a long time because the priests couldn’t get their act together, but by the time Joash was 23, the Temple once again became a place of great veneration of Yahweh.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;You would think that being personally mentored by such a godly man as Jehoiada the priest, Joash would have learned a great deal about being a man of integrity, about the importance of obeying and trusting God, and that idolatry was pure wickedness that God would never turn a blind eye to. All his siblings were murdered because of the paganistic heart of his own grandmother, he himself would have fallen victim to her evil intentions had it not been for his righteous and godly sister, nurse and Jehoiada the priest. One would think that he of all people would understand the dangers of idolatry and paganism.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;But it turned out that Joash was actually very weak in character because he very quickly turned away from all he’d been taught by Jehoiada after the old priest died. Without the godly influence of this man, Joash was easily influence by evil.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;2 Chron 24:17, ‘But after the death of Jehoiada the officials of Judah came and bowed down to the king, and the king listened to them.’&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Jew’s interpret this to mean that Joash actually allowed the princes of Judah to worship him and this is because the word ‘bowed’ means to prostrate oneself, to give homage to as before a false god. This led the people right back into paganism. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Verse 18, ‘They abandoned the house of the Lord, the God of their fathers, and served the Asherim and the idols; so wrath came upon Judah and Jerusalem for this their guilt.’ &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God sent prophets to Joash to warn him to return to the Lord but he refused to listen, and then Jehoiada’s son Zechariah – also a prophet and priest, stood up and confronted the king and the people for their sin and Joash and his men conspired against Zechariah and stoned him to death in the court of the Temple. The son of the priest who saved his life as a baby, who mentored him throughout his life and taught him the ways of the Lord; Joash stoned his him to death. That was the level of Joash’s ingratitude toward Jehoiada and the extent of his own delusion in believing himself to be divine because he foolishly allowed his own princes to worship him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In Rabbinical literature, Joash is believed to be one of four men who pretended to be ‘gods’, his princes persuaded him to believe he was divine and apparently said to him, &lt;em&gt;“Wert thou not a god thou couldst not come out alive from the Holy of Holies”. &lt;/em&gt;It would appear that at some point in his reign after Jehoiada died, that Joash must have entered the Holy of Holies and wasn’t struck dead. (What was the king doing in the Holy of Holies? Only the High Priest once per year was allowed into the Holy of Holies...Joash was assuming authority that he didn’t have).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;During a battle with the Arameans, Joash discovered he wasn’t really a god at all, he was very sick from serious wounds he received from the fight and while he was recovering in his bed, two of his servants conspired against him and killed him because he had murdered Zechariah, Jehoiada’s son. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 24:25) &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The Rabbinical literature says that the two servants who killed Joash were an Ammonite and a Moabite, chosen by God to deliver judgement on him saying, “Let the descendants of the two ungrateful families chastise the ungrateful Joash.” (Rabbinical literature)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We as parents raise our children to know and love the Lord, we teach them right from wrong and how important it is to know the Saviour, and can be totally flabbergasted by the choices and lifestyles they choose to lead once they leave the nest and even sometimes even before they leave the nest.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The truth is that every human being is answerable to God for the choices and decisions they make. Children from Christian homes sometimes become reprobate denying what they know to be true and children from very ungodly homes can become the most righteous and godly people who come to faith in Christ and go on to represent the Lord well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;At the end of the day, God is the only One who can reach into a human heart no matter what their background or upbringing, and He alone has the power to save them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If you don’t know Christ as Saviour, this is what Peter said on the day the church was born...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Acts 2:38-39, ‘...Repent and each of you be baptised in the name of Jesus Christ for the forgiveness of your sins; and you will receive the gift of the Holy Spirit. For the promise is for you and your children and for all who are far off, as many as the Lord our God will call to Himself.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The purity of the Gospel is simply this, Christ died in our place for our sins, He was buried and three days later He rose from the dead. He was seen alive by more than 500 eye witnesses. Because of our sin, we live under a death sentence, and God is a righteous judge who must judge sin. If He doesn’t judge, He’s not just. But because Christ paid our debt and offers us salvation freely, we can be free from that death sentence and made righteous before God by accepting Christ’s payment for us. It’s really very simple.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Our response is to be &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;repentance&lt;/span&gt; – turning away from our sin in heart and mind and turning to Christ – and putting our &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;faith&lt;/span&gt; in Him alone for what He did on our behalf. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;REPENTANCE &amp;amp; FAITH&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;That’s the power and simplicity of the Gospel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If your heart is responding to the Gospel of Christ you don’t need any special prayer or ritual, just find a quiet place to do business with the Father. You simply need to come humbly and respectfully before God, confess your sins and repent (turn away from), ask Him to forgive you and put your faith in Christ alone. Talk with God from your own heart and be honest with Him; God knows the truth anyway, and you can’t keep secrets from Him. God seeks a genuine heart of repentance and faith in His Son.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Please contact us if you have responded to the Gospel as we would be honoured to assist you in your new relationship with Christ.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If you do know Christ, this is God’s Word to you;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Hebrews 12:28-29, ‘Therefore, since we receive a kingdom which cannot be shaken, let us show gratitude, by which we may offer to God an acceptable service with reverence and awe; for our God is a consuming fire.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We didn’t choose God – God chose us. It’s incumbent upon us to live lives of gratitude and not think more highly of ourselves than we should. In other words, stop believing our own press and believe God’s Word.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Don’t be like Joash who thought he was vastly more than he really was. Don’t ever forget the price that was paid to provide you (us) with salvation, but live a life that exemplifies gratitude and devotion to the ONE who sacrificed all on your (our) behalf.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy&lt;/p&gt;",2012-06-28 00:25:32,mworby
6702,Home Group Notes - Jezebel,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 10px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/724407_24295926 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;198&quot; width=&quot;264&quot; /&gt;Jezebel&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Pronounced ‘Ee-zev-el’; this name is synonymous with absolute malevolent evil. It’s not particularly easy to find an exact meaning for this name; the first part of her name in Hebrew is ‘ay’, it’s also in Ahab’s name, it means ‘jackal’ and possibly other things as well - it’s not definitive. The last part of her name, ‘zabal’ may mean a place designated to honour its occupant. This word is used in Scripture five times in this context:- for God’s Temple, for the heavens and for an earthly mansion. Both parts of her name put together however are believed to mean ‘un-exalted’ or ‘un-husbanded or unmarried’ or possibly ‘without cohabitation’. There are some who believe her name means ‘where is the exalted one or prince?’, and others believe that the root words from which this name is derived mean ‘there is no husband or prince’ suggesting lack of character and morals and implying immorality, someone who goes with many men, and not faithful to one husband.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jezebel was the daughter of the King of Phoenicia (Fon-eesha) – Ethbaal (Et’ba’al) – his capital being Tyre. Ethbaal was a priest of Ashtaroth (also known as Astarte’) who murdered Philetes (Fy-leet-as), king of Tyre and then assumed the throne. ‘Ba’al’ means lord or husband in Hebrew.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab (A’hav) married Jezebel not necessarily for love; he married her for the benefits that came to the Northern Kingdom through access to open trade routes via Phoenicia’s sea ports. It was a politically motivated marriage though he certainly wasn’t forced to marry her; he may very well have been attracted to her because she was so much like himself.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jezebel obviously learned the despicable art of wickedness, betrayal, murder, manipulation, slander and thievery from her father and she was maniacally devoted to her own religion of Ba’al worship. One of the first things she did when she became queen of Israel was to aggressively target anyone and everyone who remained faithful to Yahweh. She specifically made a point of slaughtering loyal Hebrew prophets of Jehovah, and the prophet Obadiah (who amazingly served in the kings court, but for safety reasons probably kept his loyalty to Yahweh a secret) frantically tried to save some of them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Serving in the royal court provided Obadiah with inside knowledge into the actions Jezebel was taking and he used this knowledge well to save as many godly prophets as he could.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 18:3-4, ‘Ahab called Obadiah who was over the household. (Now Obadiah feared the Lord greatly; for when Jezebel destroyed the prophets of the Lord, Obadiah took a hundred prophets and hid them by fifties in a cave, and provided them with bread and water.)’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jezebel also imported prophets of Ba’al and she and Ahab established what we would call a ‘state sanctioned religion’; they did everything they could to stamp out any residual worship of Yahweh, and imposed the worship of Ba’al instead. Jezebel was not satisfied to simply allow the religious coexistence of Yahweh and Ba’al worship; she insisted that the worship of Ba’al replace the worship of Yahweh in its absolute entirety. Unlike our own society that allows for freedom of religion, Jezebel had zero tolerance for any religion other than her own, people were not afforded the right to choose whom they would worship.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This rise in pagan worship and idolatry (which was already rampant in the Northern Kingdom because of the apostasy from all the previous wicked kings) brought about God’s judgement. He closed up the heavens and Israel was ravaged by drought. No matter how much wealth and prosperity came through the international trade agreements with their pagan neighbours, if the people couldn’t grow food, they couldn’t survive. God proved to them all, especially Ahab and Jezebel that He was the One True God with real power, not Ba’al...who couldn’t make a drop of water fall from the sky. God spoke through Elijah and said no rain would fall for three and a half years.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We learned last week that this eventually lead to the confrontation on Mt Carmel between Elijah and the prophets of Ba’al, resulting in God really showing off His unparalleled power and climaxing when Elijah slaughtered the false prophets of the false god Ba’al.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What is really surprising is Elijah’s reaction to Jezebel’s response. Elijah didn’t seem to be afraid so much of Ahab, but he was petrified of Jezebel. It appears in Scripture that as wicked as Ahab was he could at least be reasoned with somewhat, but Jezebel was a different entity altogether. She had no conscience at all. She was determined to get her way no matter the cost and no matter who stood in her way. She had zero qualms about taking another human life if it got her what she wanted. For all intents and purposes, Jezebel was totally and utterly devoid of any moral compass or ethical rationale.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Jezebel heard that her pagan prophets had been slaughtered (just like she had slaughtered the prophets of Yahweh) she was inconsolably livid with rage and she sent a message to Elijah to say that before the sun set he was going to be in exactly the same state as they were. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(1 Kings 19:1-4)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Elijah fled and was so scared he begged God to kill him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It can sometimes be hard to understand how Elijah could have been so overcome by fear at one threat from this woman, he had personally seen God’s mighty power demonstrated on Mt Carmel, but there was something so malevolent about Jezebel that everyone appeared to be in sheer terror of her. She really was a most evil woman.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Fortunately, Jezebel wasn’t able to find Elijah, but she set about replacing her false prophets and she got on with her wicked life...but she and Ahab did something a little later in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 21&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; that has chilling similarities to historical events that took place during a particular period of church history.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Last week we talked about King Ahab having a major dummy spit over the fact that his neighbour, Naboth (Na’voth) the Jezreelite, wouldn’t sell him his property to allow him to grow a vege patch.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Naboth’s neighbouring property was the ancient inheritance of his family line promised by God and it was the inheritance for his own continuing family line. Ahab ranted around his palace and eventually went to bed, wouldn’t talk to anyone and refused to eat; behaving like a toddler throwing a paddy in the supermarket because his mother wouldn’t buy him an ice cream. Ahab didn’t try to steal it, he offered to pay Naboth for it and even to replace it with a better vineyard, but Naboth understood the laws of inheritance and land allotment and Ahab – who had zero regard for the laws of God and the laws of the land – wasn’t used to not getting his own way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Enter Jezebel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;She asked Ahab what he was sulking about and why he would eat, and he told her his unhappy story about not being able to grow a vege patch because of Naboth, his unco-operative neighbour. So Jezebel reminds him that he is the king after all! In other words, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;because you’re the king, you can do whatever you like! Rules don’t apply to you. Get up, have some lunch and chill out...I’ll take care of it! &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Can you see any similarities in what Jezebel did next that remind you of events from church history?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Jezebel wrote letter’s in Ahab’s name and sealed them with his seal (that is, the authority of the king himself)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;They were addressed to the elders and nobles of Naboth’s community instructing them to proclaim a fast and to ensure that Naboth was the reason for this gathering. This was not a celebration to pretend to honour Naboth, rather it was very much like a public trial. It was a serious event that was tantamount to a legal proceeding.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This trial was to be held in public, with the community leaders presiding and Naboth was in the hot seat.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Jezebel further instructed the elders that two false witnesses (men without conscience) be brought forward to state before everyone present that they heard Naboth blaspheme both God and the king. In other words, charges were to be brought against Naboth.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Jezebel’s instructions were explicit, the charges had to be such that the result would require the death penalty.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jezebel knew exactly how to manipulate the laws of Israel; she knew that the charge of blasphemy held a death sentence and it could only be upheld with a minimum of two corroborating witnesses. The elders and nobles were obviously terrified of Jezebel, they themselves may have been Ba’al worshippers but what is clear, is that these instructions from Jezebel in Ahab’s name were very obviously false. The charges were clearly trumped up and they knew that Naboth was an innocent man. But just like Elijah, these community leaders were absolutely terrified of Jezebel and didn’t even consider once saying no to her orders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Once the trial had taken place and judgement had been handed down, Naboth and his sons were taken out and stoned to death and their bodies left unburied. They were ultimately eaten by wild dogs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Killing Naboth’s sons meant there could be no legal claims to the property. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;2 Kings 9:26&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;As soon as Naboth’s murder was reported to Jezebel, she went straight to Ahab to tell him the good news that Naboth was dead and he could go and claim the property for himself. Ahab was so pleased he went down straight away to gloat over his new acquisition.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;So in short.....&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Ahab wanted Naboth’s property but had no legal means of obtaining it.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In order to get Naboth’s property, Jezebel arranged for a mock trial, complete with false witnesses to &amp;nbsp;ensure Naboth’s condemnation and subsequent execution.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Naboth’s property was seized and became the property of the king.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Naboth’s rightful heirs were also executed, being implicated in their father’s so-called crimes to prevent their rightful, lawful claim on that property.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This sequence of events is shockingly mirrored in the inquisitions of medieval church history which spanned a period of approximately 1000 years during what is appropriately termed the ‘Dark Ages’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The state sanctioned church of that day – which was predominantly made up of unbelievers who simply sought personal church leadership positions to gain personal power and wealth – became reprehensibly rich through the implementation of what we know as the ‘Inquisitions’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Property and wealth from those who wouldn’t conform was easily obtained. All that was required was the mere hint of an accusation against someone for the crime of heresy. Such accusations could be levelled by anyone for any reason, and accusers would often be rewarded by the church leadership.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;One neighbour who had a fight or grudge against another neighbour could make an accusation of criticism against the church or church teaching and the accused would be dragged before their religious court.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Trials were conducted and false witnesses brought forward with their rehearsed testimonies. (Read that as ’bribery’, their false testimonies were ‘bought &amp;amp; paid’ for). Often the innocent victim was tortured mercilessly until a confession was finally given and then they were publicly executed where their so-called crimes were announced, their so-called admissions were proclaimed and their so-called ‘lawful’ executions were implemented. All property was then ceded to the church with no redress available to the rightful heirs of the executed party. Sometimes whole families were executed together.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There is nothing that the human heart can devise that hasn’t already been anticipated in God’s Word.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The question can then be asked...”Why is it that the wicked always seem to prosper in their wickedness, while the righteous seem to struggle and suffer wrongfully?” “How can this be God’s way?” It’s easy to look at those who live wickedly and wonder why they appear to not only get away with their wickedness, but they prosperous from it. David wrote about this in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Psalm 73&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;But the God tells us in His Word that He will absolutely deal with the wicked who remain unrepentant, but He will deal with them in His time and in His way and it’s entirely His business how and when He does that.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Psalm 37:7-10, ‘Rest in the Lord and wait patiently for Him; do not fret because of him who prospers in his way, because of the man who carries out wicked schemes. Cease from anger and forsake wrath; do not fret; it leads only to evildoing. For evildoers will be cut off, but those who wait for the Lord, they will inherit the land. Yet a little while and the wicked man will be no more; and you will look carefully for his place and he will not be there.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The day of recompense for the wicked will come.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What was Jezebel’s end? After the debacle with Naboth’s vineyard, good ol’ Elijah was sent to give Ahab a message of judgement at the exact time that Ahab was inspecting his newly acquired property - standing on the very ground he had just stolen from innocent Naboth. Elijah’s words would have been quite a shock to Ahab because the entire set up was secret...it was a complete contrivance to ‘look like’ a legitimate trial. Ahab came face to face with the fact that he has no secrets from God. Yahweh sees and knows everything, and doom was pronounced on Ahab and his family line, judgement that was virtually identical to the judgement declared on Jeroboam. Indeed, Ahab and Jezebel would reap what they had sown.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Because Naboth and his sons were left to be eaten by dogs, so would Jezebel be eaten by dogs. She was greatly feared by everyone, but she was also greatly hated by everyone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;After Ahab died in battle, a man by the name of Jehu approached the place where Jezebel was staying, he called out to others who were in the building with her, calling for them to throw her from the high window she was standing in. They did. She died on impact and Jehu proceeded to trample her body under the hooves of his horse and then left it there to go inside and have something to eat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Once he’d finished his lunch he decided to bury her because despite her unbelievable wickedness, she was after all, still royalty!!! However, when he went outside dogs had eaten or dragged her remains away leaving nothing but her skull, feet and the palms of her hands behind. A very gruesome end to a particularly evil woman. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;(2 Kings 9:29-37)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;This was fulfilled prophecy because there was to be no memorial or place where she would be buried, remembered or honoured.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;No matter how successful the wicked may appear to be, we should never envy their seeming success and prosperity; their lives and their wealth are short lived and eternity lasts a long, long, long time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;James 4:14&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;describes the duration of a human lifespan as a vapour;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;‘Yet you do not know what your life will be like tomorrow. You are just a vapour that appears for a little while and then vanishes away.’&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The following proverb describes Ahab and Jezebel to a ‘T’....&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Proverbs 21:6-7, ‘The acquisition of treasures by a lying tongue is a fleeting vapour, the pursuit of death. The violence of the wicked will drag them away, because they refuse to act with justice.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s better to enter eternity with a righteous and uncompromising heart, knowing that your eternal salvation is in God’s hands, rather than to enter eternity under the judgement and wrath of God all for the sake of gaining material wealth and comfort.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab and Jezebel knew who the One True God was, they had seen with their own eyes His power and glory, but they were too foolish, too selfish and too arrogant to reverently fear Him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Don’t be like them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ecclesiastes 12:13-14, ‘The conclusion, when all has been heard is: fear God and keep His commandments, because this applies to every person. For God will bring every act to judgement, everything which is hidden, whether it is good or evil.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-cool.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Cool&quot; title=&quot;Cool&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-06-21 00:53:09,mworby
6630,Home Group Notes - Ahab,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 8px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/575231_55762839 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;263&quot; width=&quot;346&quot; /&gt;King Ahab (Akh-av)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab’s name is made up of two elements, ‘ah’ &amp;amp; ‘ab’. ‘Ah’ holds a surface meaning of ‘brother’ and ‘Ab’ holds the meaning of ‘father’ from which we know the Hebrew word ‘Aba’. Therefore, the commonly held meaning of Ahab is ‘the Father is my brother’ which in turn is believed to mean ‘God is my close relative’. Knowing the life history of Ahab, we know that this is entirely untrue for him personally; he was a wicked king who hated God. There is however, another possible meaning; the ancient Hebrew word for brother has an identical spelling to the word used for an exclamation of grief as well as for the word used for jackal; though it has a slightly different pronunciation. So while the name Ahab is commonly believed to mean ‘the Father is my brother’, what is more akin to his personality is that he was a jackal, he brought immense grief to his people because of his wickedness and corruption.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The history of Ahab can be read in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 16&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;right through to 1 Kings 22; 2 Chron 18.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab was the son of Omri and he ruled Israel (Northern Kingdom), who was the first king of Israel to successfully establish a stable political government, none of his predecessors had been able to achieve this. Ahab reigned from 841-814 BC and he was fortunate in that he was able to simply continue to rule the nation upon stability inherited from his father.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He was a very wicked king. In fact, Ahab was considered to be the most wicked of all Israel’s kings up to that time. He was married to a woman named Jezebel who was a princess from Phoenicia which was situated along the Mediterranean coast north of Israel, in Lebanon. Tyre was the capital of Phoenicia. Ahab’s marriage was a political alliance that had to do with peace agreements and trade, it was not a marriage borne of love by any means, but Ahab and Jezebel got along very, very well because they were of the same heart and mind; they were both incredibly wicked and corrupt. Theirs was a match made in heaven...or more appropriately ‘hell’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Israel’s first king, Jeroboam, established places of pagan worship to prevent the people feeling the need to travel to the Temple in Jerusalem, he basically convinced the people that they were worshipping Yahweh, just in idol form, but Ahab went even further than that by setting up ‘Ba’al’ as being equal to Yahweh. Just as Solomon allowed his foreign wives to practice their own particular brands of pagan worship, Ahab allowed Jezebel to introduce the worship of ‘Ba’al-Melqart’ who was the chief god of Tyre.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab knew who the One True God was and he even gave names to his children that were expressions of Yahweh’s attributes. He held a superficial adherence to or connection to Yahweh because of his Hebrew roots, but he indulged and encouraged rabid paganism and its associated rites and practices.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;One of the most notable things that came to Israel during Ahab’s reign was monetary success for the people because of the foreign trade agreements he forged with the Phoenicians and others. In fact, Ahab had a palace that was build out of ivory – this man lacked for nothing, he denied himself nothing and indulged himself with everything. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Never mistake monetary or material wealth for the blessing and/or approval of God – one does not necessarily equate to the other. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are three main things that Ahab is most known for;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;His evil wife Jezebel whom we will look at next week&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;His excessive encouragement of paganism and idolatry&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;His shocking treatment of Naboth his close neighbour&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab had an intense hatred for true God-fearing prophets. He surrounded himself with false prophets who supposedly spoke the words of Yahweh, but in fact spoke only what they knew Ahab wanted them to say. This is clear in the story of King Jehoshaphat who aligned himself with Ahab to fight against the Syrians.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chron 18:6-22, ‘But Jehoshaphat said, “Is there not yet a prophet of the Lord here that we may inquire of him?” The king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, “There is yet one man by whom we may inquire of the Lord, but I hate him, for he never prophesies good concerning me but always evil. He is Micaiah, son of Imla.” But Jehoshaphat said, “Let not the king say so.” Then the king of Israel called an officer and said, “Bring quickly Micaiah, Imla’s son.” Now the king of Israel and Jehoshaphat the king of Judah were sitting each on his throne, arrayed in their robes, and they were sitting at the threshing floor at the entrance of the gate of Samaria; and all the prophets were prophesying before them. Zedekiah the son of Chenaanah made horns of iron for himself and said, “Thus says the Lord, ‘With these you shall gore the Arameans until they are consumed.’ All the prophets were prophesying thus, saying, “Go up to Ramoth-Gilead and succeed, for the Lord will give it into the hand of the king.” Then the messenger who went to summon Micaiah spoke to him saying, “Behold, the words of the prophets are uniformly favourable to the king. So please let your word be like one of them and speak favourably.” But Micaiah said, “As the Lord lives, what my God says, that will I speak.” When he came to the king, the king said to him, “Micaiah, shall we go to Ramoth-Gilead to battle or shall I refrain?” He said, “Go up and succeed, for they will be given into your hand.” Then the king said to him, “How many times must I adjure you to speak to me nothing but the truth in the name of the Lord?” So he said, “I saw all Israel scattered on the mountains, like sheep which have no shepherd; and the Lord said, ‘These have no master. Let each of them return to his house in peace.’” Then the king of Israel said to Jehoshaphat, “Did I not tell you that he would not prophesy good concerning me but evil?” Micaiah said, “Therefore, hear the word of the Lord. I saw the Lord sitting on His throne, and all the host of heaven standing on His right and on His left. The Lord said, ‘Who will entice Ahab king of Israel to go up and fall at Ramoth-Gilead?’ And one said this while another said that. Then a spirit came forward and stood before the Lord and said, ‘I will entice him.’ And the Lord said to him, ‘How?’ He said, ‘I will go and be a deceiving spirit in the mouth of all his prophets.’ Then He said, ‘You are to entice him and prevail also. Go and do so.’ Now therefore, behold, the Lord has put a deceiving spirit in the mouth of these your prophets, for the Lord has proclaimed disaster against you.’”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;It’s an important word of caution to every believer in every generation to listen to the &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Word of God&lt;/span&gt; which is the sanctioned, canonised, proven, trustworthy and dependable Word of God; everything within the Bible, from Genesis to Revelation is &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;sufficient&lt;/span&gt; for every believer. We are not to live by the words of those who claim to be speaking special the words from God. Men fail...in fact men always fail, but God’s Word remains true and faithful. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The bizarre thing about this is that Ahab knew that Micaiah wasn’t prophesying according to the word of God when he gave the same initial speech as all his false prophets. He was angry with Micaiah for not being truthful to start with, and then got angry with him when he in fact did prophesy the truth to him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sinful human beings know within their own heart what is true and what is false...and to justify themselves and their behaviour, they surround themselves with people who will indulge them and tell them what they want to hear. But if a real man or woman from God happens to be there, they expect and demand nothing but the truth, otherwise, they consider them frauds and hypocrites. They recognise immediately when a godly person doesn’t tell them the truth, even if it’s the same information they’ve received from their ‘yes men’, but when a godly person does speak truth, they hate them for it. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There was a particular prophet who was especially frustrating to Ahab and his name was Elijah. We’ll look at Elijah another time, but Elijah had the unenviable job of issuing Ahab many prophetic words of rebuke and judgement because of the wickedness he promoted and indulged in. Elijah spent a great deal of time hiding from Ahab because this prophet was such a thorn in his side. Every time Ahab would do something, Elijah would turn up without notice and pour cold water all over it by declaring God’s anger at him and of the impending judgement that was going to unfold as a result of his wickedness. Before he could be captured, Elijah would disappear again – it was Ahab’s greatest frustration that he could never capture or silence this most persistent prophet of God – his nemesis.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab called Elijah a ‘troubler of Israel’ because at Elijah’s word, the heavens closed and Israel had no rain for three years. However Elijah stunned Ahab by declaring his face he was the cause of all Israel’s troubles because of his wickedness, paganism and idolatry, and it was this exchange the lead to the challenge by Elijah to all the prophets of Ba’al on Mt Carmel. Ahab was silent during that contest but he saw dramatically and powerfully that Ba’al was a fake, impotent god and Yahweh was the One and only True God. In fact, after this contest, Elijah gave immediate instructions to Ahab about what he was to do and where he was to go, promising that the drought was about to break, demonstrating the power of God yet again, and he – Ahab – obeyed them exactly, and sure enough God sent rain upon the land at Elijah’s word. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 18)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab was without excuse; he had every reason to believe in Yahweh and to repent, he had no reason whatsoever to continue with the paganism that he had allowed to rampantly overrun his nation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;One of the most unattractive attributes of Ahab is that he was a prize sook. He was incredibly childish. After an incident with Ben-hadad in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 20&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, one of the prophets delivered a message of rebuke to him for letting that wicked Aramean king escape when God had deemed he be destroyed. (remember King Saul and the Amalekites) Because Ahab got a message that didn’t appeal to him, he went home all sullen and moody. This is exactly how he behaved when he tried to get the property of his next door neighbour – Naboth. (Na-voth)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God gave very clear instructions about land ownership to Moses; family land and tribal land allotments were to be maintained. Even if a family or community fell on hard times, they would at least always have land on which they could live and grow food. If times were especially hard, they could lease their land to others, but every Jubilee year, the land was to revert to its original owner. All debts were cancelled and all ‘slaves’ or bond-servants were to be released.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab wanted the land next door to make a herb or vegetable garden...because being the king he needed to grow his own veges! (sarcasm!!!) Naboth informed the king respectfully that he couldn’t sell him his land because it was the inheritance he had received from his father’s (generations of fathers going back to the original land allotments when Israel took Canaan). Naboth owned a vineyard, it was his livelihood and it was the inheritance he would in turn hand on to his own sons.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What was Ahab’s response? He had a royal ‘sook attack’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 21:4, ‘So Ahab came into his house sullen&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;color: #333333;&quot;&gt;(sook)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;and vexed&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;color: #333333;&quot;&gt;(ranted and raved)&lt;/span&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;because of the word which Naboth the Jezreelite had spoken to him; for he said, “I will not give you the inheritance of my fathers.” And he lay down on his bed and turned his face and ate no food.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He threw a tantrum like a small child who doesn’t get his own way. It’s as though he laid down and held his breath until he turned blue just so others would give in to him. What he needed was a good swift kick on his royal behind!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What happened next we’ll take a look at next week when we learn more about Jezebel, but what we can look at now, is that after this horrendous situation with Naboth, Elijah tracked Ahab down and gave him a stinging judgement over what he had just done. A judgemental word from God – whom Ahab KNEW was real because he had seen His power numerous times, not least during the challenge on Mt Carmel – was enough to instil Ahab with great fear.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Ahab tore his clothes (a sign of grief) and put on sackcloth and ashes (a sign of repentance) and he fasted as well. He became very despondent.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Having sin exposed and experiencing the conviction of God is not a bad thing even though it’s unpleasant to experience. In fact, it’s a very good thing if it leads us to be regretful for our sin and to repentance. The very fact that God immediately spoke to Elijah after seeing Ahab in this contrite manner, said He wouldn’t bring evil upon Ahab in his lifetime, but rather in his son’s lifetime who turned out to be as wicked as his father.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We don’t see any long-term change of heart or deep repentance from Ahab, we see him as a rebel right to the very end. It appears that his short-lived repentance was motivated by little more than his sorrow at being caught out, rather than sorrow over his sin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;What we do see from this however, is the extreme and even exorbitant grace that God shows to those who will repent of their sin. Often people read the Old Testament (Tenach) and deduce that God is bloodthirsty and tyrannical, demanding the deaths of millions of innocents. What people fail to realise is that God isn’t willing that any should perish...Jew or Gentile...and that He sent warning after warning after warning over hundreds and hundreds of years and demonstrated His deity and power through stunning miracles to prove to everyone that He would indeed bring judgement if they didn’t repent of their sin. Since every human being is sinful, there is no such thing as an innocent human being.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God gave them multiplied centuries to turn to Him and they refused...both Jew and Gentile. So when God eventually sent judgement it wasn’t because He was bloodthirsty and cruel, it was because He is a just judge who must deal with unrighteousness, in exactly the same way earthly judges bring down the full weight of the law on human beings who break the laws of the land. If God doesn’t judge, He’s not just or righteous.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Romans 2:2-6, ‘And we know that the judgement of God rightly falls upon those who practice such things. But do you suppose this, O man, when you pass judgement on those who practice such things and do the same yourself, that you will escape the judgement of God? &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Or do you think lightly of the riches of His kindness and tolerance and patience, not knowing that the kindness of God leads you to repentance?&lt;/span&gt; But because of your stubbornness and unrepentant heart you are storing up wrath for yourself in the day of wrath and revelation of the righteous judgement of God, who will render to each person according to his deeds.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The lesson of Ahab, king of Israel is not simply to know that God is the One True God, it is to humble ourselves and repent so that we can be made right with God. Repentance over sorrow for sin, not sorrow over being caught out in sin.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s the difference between genuine repentance for sin as opposed to opportunistic repentance to avoid judgement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-smile.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Smile&quot; title=&quot;Smile&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-06-14 00:04:59,mworby
6578,Home Group Notes - Jehoshaphat,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 10px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/567311_74756230 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;212&quot; width=&quot;282&quot; /&gt;Jehoshaphat&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The elements that make up his name are ‘Jah’ or ‘Jehu’ which are abbreviated forms of Yahweh, the name of the Lord, and ‘shapat’ which means judgement in a penal sense being understood as justice, ordinance, custom, manner. Ultimately being a reference to God ushering in His judgement day. So Jehoshaphat means ‘Yahweh has Judged’ or ‘The Lord Judges.’&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The prophet Joel lived after the rule of Jehoshaphat and he prophesied in Joel 3:2 that God would gather the nations into the Valley of Jehoshaphat to judge them for what they have done to His people Israel and for dividing up His land. It's no coincidence that the 'valley' is named Jehoshaphat becuse it's a valley of the Lord's judgement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are three men and one valley named Jehoshaphat in the Bible, we are looking at King Jehoshaphat who was the fourth king of Judah. He ruled at the same time that Ahab, Ahaziah and Jehoram were kings in Israel, the Northern Kingdom. It was during his reign that the prophets Elijah and Elisha also lived.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Generally, Jehoshaphat is considered to be a good king, one of only 8 good kings from the Southern Kingdom of Judah. The northern kingdom of Israel had no good kings at all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;His father Asa was a good king and Jehoshaphat followed after his father and his great, great, great grandfather David, in that he didn’t worship the baal’s, but rather sought to follow the Word of God and the commands laid out in it. He was a strong leader and kept his kingdom under solid control with his people bringing him tribute and this brought him both great wealth and honour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There were many good things that he did, in the first years of his rule he earnestly sought to honour God but didn’t begin removing the places of pagan worship until later in his reign where he became more aggressive about it, and while he did remove a lot he didn’t remove them all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;His father Asa was very wise in ensuring Judah was militarily capable of defending itself against any possible sign of aggression from Israel to the north and Jehoshaphat followed in the same vein by placing his army in all the fenced cities of Judah, he set garrisons throughout the land and in the cities of Ephraim which his father had fought Israel for and won back. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 17:1-2)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The greatest thing Jehoshaphat did to strengthen Judah was in his obedience to the Law of God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chron 17:7-10 ‘Then in the third year of his reign he sent his officials, Ben-hail, Obadiah, Zechariah, Nethanel and Micaiah, to teach in the cities of Judah; and with them the Levites, Shemaiah, Nethaniah, Zebadiah, Asahel, Shemiramoth, Jehonathan, Adonijah, Tobijah and Tobadonijah, the Levites; and with them Elishama and Jehoram, the priests. They taught in Judah, having the book of the law of the Lord with them; and they went throughout all the cities of Judah and taught among the people. Now the dread of the Lord was on all the kingdoms of the lands which were around Judah, so that they did not make war against Jehoshaphat.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;By restoring reverence and a priority to the Word of God, Jehoshaphat placed his nation under the incredible protection of God. The dread of the Lord settled on all the surrounding nations who were historically their sworn enemies. In fact, their most vitriolic enemies – the Philistines – brought gifts of silver to Jehoshaphat, the Arabians brought him flocks of rams and male goats – 7,700 of each! 15,400 animals meant extraordinary wealth in those days.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;With this increase of wealth Jehoshaphat went on to build more fortresses and storage cities where he kept large supplies along with his army and non-military men who were valiant and patriotic. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt;It's also interesting to note that he used that wealth for the benefit and security of his people rather than lining his own pockets.&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In most cases, the kings of Judah and Israel were not friendly with one another, rather they were enemies, however Jehoshaphat wanted to make peace with Israel knowing that they were in fact brothers. He knew he could make peace with Israel because of the security measures he had taken to ensure the safety of Judah’s borders.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This was Jehoshaphat’s biggest flaw; he should never have tried to align himself and his nation with wicked, godless kings. One of the worst being Ahab and his wife Jezebel who happened to be at war with Syria, he was also incredibly foolish in allowing his son to marry Ahab and Jezebel’s daughter Athaliah and we’ll find out her in coming weeks.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;With his alliance in play, Jehoshaphat travelled north and king Ahab asked him if he would join him in battle against the Syrians, being a godly man, Jehoshaphat said he would but on condition they heard from God through a prophet. The short story is that the false prophets told Ahab exactly what he wanted to hear....that God wanted him to fight against the Syrians and God would guarantee him a glorious victory.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It must have been very obvious that these were false prophets because Jehoshaphat asked if there was any other prophet around whom they could ask for direction from God. Ahab said there was, his name is Micaiah but he hated him because he never gave him the answers he wanted. Jehoshaphat was horrified that king Ahab would be so disrespectful toward a man of God, but Ahab called for him to satisfy Jehoshaphat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;A tense conversation took place between the prophet and Ahab but the end result was that Ahab went to battle and convinced Jehoshaphat to go with him. Jehoshaphat should have been suspicious when Ahab told him to dress like the king while he, the king of Israel, would dress like a normal member of the army.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Of course, an enemy commander is going to target the leader of the enemy forces because if you kill the leader you conquer the followers quickly and easily. Jehoshaphat should have realised he was being set up to be the target while Ahab was protecting his own wicked hide.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The battle went badly for Israel but Jehoshaphat called on the Lord who saved him from being killed and when he got home, he was rebuked by the prophet Jehu who told him that God was angry with him for trying to help and assist those who hated God. He repented and refocused his efforts to steer the nation in righteousness and kept well away from the Northern Kingdom of Israel. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 22:29-33)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;His lesson was short lived however, and twice more he foolishly tried to align himself with Israel in an attempt to make ships that would go all the way to Tarshish. God sent word to him to say that because he had joined with the wicked king Ahaziah of Israel, God would break the ships and that’s exactly what happened. Jehoshaphat had to give that project away. The next foolish operation he joined with Israel for was a war against Moab; it was a military success but the prophet Elisha rebuked him and told him to mind his own business and look after his own nation. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 20:35-37 &amp;amp;&amp;nbsp; 2 Kings 3:11-14)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;One of the things he did very well however was seen during the time that the Moabites, Ammonites and some of the Meunites and Edomites from Mt Seir, collectively came together to make war against Jehoshaphat. When he was told of this vast multitude coming together against him he knew that his own army wasn’t big enough to counter them. Together they were just too much. The Ammonites and Moabites were the descendants of Lot (Abraham’s nephew), the result of his incestuous relationships with his daughters. The Meunites were an Arab tribe that lived on the border of Judah; probably a small tribe or clan from among the Arabians, believed to be the descendants of Abraham and his second wife Keturah whom he married after Sarah had died and the Edomites were the descendants of Esau. All these people were the immediate relatives of the Israelites.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jehoshaphat gave his full attention to the Lord, he called a nationwide fast and stood among the people in Jerusalem, in the Temple and prayed with all his heart to God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Chron 20:6-12, ‘and he said, “O Lord, the God of our fathers, are You not God in the heavens? And are You not ruler over all the kingdoms of the nations? Power and might are in Your hand so that no one can stand against You. Did You not, O our God, drive out the inhabitants of this land before Your people Israel and give it to the descendants of Abraham Your friend forever? They have lived in it, and have built You a sanctuary there for Your name, saying, &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;‘Should evil come upon us, the sword, or judgement, or pestilence, or famine, we will stand before this house and before You (for Your name is in this house) and cry to You in our distress, and You will hear and deliver us.’&lt;/span&gt; Now behold, the sons of Ammon and Moab and Mount Seir, whom You did not let Israel invade when they came out of the land of Egypt (they turned aside from them and did not destroy them), see how they are rewarding us by coming to drive us out from Your possession which You have given us as an inheritance. O our God, will You not judge them?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;For we are powerless before this great multitude who are coming against us; nor do we know what to do, but our eyes are on You.”’&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The text goes on to say that all Judah was standing before the Lord including all the wives, infants and children; they were all desperate to hear from God that He would deliver them. Then Jahaziel, a Levite who ministered in the Temple prophesied to the king and all the people gathered there; God spoke and reassured them all that they didn’t need to be fearful or dismayed because God was going to fight this battle for them. God told them which way their enemies were going to approach them and He said they were to go down to meet them, but He emphasised again that they wouldn’t be required to fight, all they were required to do was position themselves in the right place, then stand and see the salvation of the Lord on their behalf.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jehoshaphat’s response to this word was immediate. He didn’t even once flinch or question or doubt. He bowed his head and prostrated himself on the ground and the people immediately followed suit and they worshipped the Lord.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;I think it’s very important to note here that Jehoshaphat proved to be a godly leader in the darkest time of his reign. He demonstrated exceptional leadership and humility by acknowledging that even though he was the king, he didn’t have the answers or the resources to deal with their dilemma, he needed God to see them through this emergency. He quickly believed God and appropriately led his nation in humble acceptance of God’s Word and appropriately led the people to reverently worship God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When times were less dangerous, he showed some serious lack of wisdom but not from a malicious or greedy heart, it may very well have been that Jehoshaphat was grieved over the division within the entire nation of Israel proper and had a genuine desire to see both the northern and southern kingdoms at least reunited as friends even if they couldn’t be one single nation again. He wanted to ensure peace for Judah, and possibly his altruistic motives were misplaced because God didn’t want him to align with the rampant wickedness that was embraced so willingly in the north.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;But Jehoshaphat’s real deep love for God came to the fore when these combined armies marched against him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;With Jehoshaphat in the lead, the people rose early in the morning and went to the place God instructed them, then he said to the people, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Listen to me, O Judah and inhabitants of Jerusalem, put your trust in the Lord your God and you will be established. Put your trust in His prophets and succeed.” (2 Chron 20:20)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The next thing he did was very important, he consulted with the people – he got their input, the agreement and their heart; he appointed the Levites, those whose role it was to maintain worship around the clock in the Temple (this was established by King David); these worshipping priests from the tribe of Levi went ahead of the army singing, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Give thanks to the Lord, for His lovingkindness is everlasting”. (2 Chron 20:21)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;They were not at the battle field yet, they hadn’t even laid eyes on their enemies at this point, they were at the place where God said to congregate and they began their march &lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;TO&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; the battle front with the Levites out front leading the people with praise. As soon as the singing began, the text says that &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;the Lord set ambushes against the sons of Ammon, Moab and Mt Seir and they were utterly routed&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; – Ammon and Moab attacked the Edomites and when they’d destroyed them, they proceeded to attack each other. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 20:22-23)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Judah finally came to the lookout of the wilderness, they looked toward the multitude...and there were bodies all over the ground....NOT ONE escaped the carnage and Judah didn’t raise a sword to make it happen. They didn’t even see the battle. It was over before they got there. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Chron 20:24)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; It took Judah 3 days to collect the spoils of a battle they had no part in.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;These high’s and low’s in the life of Jehoshaphat are not chronological, but what is really interesting to learn from his life, is that when he tried to align himself with Israel in the north, he always failed; yet when he trusted in the Lord whole-heartedly, he saw great success.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The thing I marvel at most of all however, is that the people themselves, having seen God miraculously deliver them from these sworn enemies, continued to worship false gods after Jehoshaphat had died. What’s even more shocking is that his own son, Jehoram who acceded the throne after his father was a very wicked king, and he had seen firsthand, up close and personal so to speak, how his father failed when he sinned and succeeded when he trusted God, as well as seeing the power of God in a most remarkable way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s is human nature to call on God when you’re scared and when things improve, we quickly forget Him. This was seen very clearly after September 11.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The lesson of Jehoshaphat is to trust in God alone, never in men and alliances that we think will bring security. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-smile.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Smile&quot; title=&quot;Smile&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-06-08 06:38:30,mworby
6406,Home Group Notes - Jeroboam,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;margin-right: 12px; margin-bottom: 10px; float: left;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/images/blog_images/1058605_60297588 small.jpg&quot; height=&quot;252&quot; width=&quot;352&quot; /&gt;Jeroboam&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The name consists of two elements very similar to Rehoboam: The last part, ‘am’ means a people ranging from mankind to a specific nation, even to a population of a town or community, it can also mean kinsmen as in a family, clan or tribe. The first part is ‘rahab’ but with a slightly different meaning due to the verb roots; this time meaning ‘much to contain, increase in multitude’. So Jeroboam could mean ‘May the people increase’, ‘Whose people are countless’ OR, ‘The people contendeth’.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is very interesting because Jeroboam became the leader of the Northern Kingdom, the Northern Kingdom is also called 'Israel' and 'Ephraim' interchangeably in the OT - gaining rulership over the ten northern tribes after the people contended with Rehoboam, son of Solomon. Because Jeroboam was from the tribe of Ephraim, it's as though his own tribe really did increase to include ten whole tribes of Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jeroboam’s story can be found in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings chapters 11–14; 2 Chronicles chapters 10 – 13; the book of Amos&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and he is mentioned numerous times throughout &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2&lt;sup&gt;nd&lt;/sup&gt; Kings&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in conjunction with other kings after him because they did evil in the sight of the Lord following the sins of Jeroboam the son of Nebat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jeroboam was of the tribe of Ephraim (Ephraim and Manasseh were the sons of Joseph) and Jeroboam was originally faithful to Solomon who established him as the overseer of the forced labour of the house of Joseph. So his job was to oppress his own tribe. However one day when Jeroboam was heading to Jerusalem, the prophet Ahijah met him on the road; the prophet was wearing a new cloak and like many Biblical prophets, he did something physical to represent some event or circumstance that would take place. He took off his cloak and tore it into twelve pieces. Then he told Jeroboam to select ten pieces for himself and then Ahijah said in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;1 Kings 11:31-40, ‘“Take for yourself ten pieces; for thus says the Lord, the God of Israel, ‘Behold, I will tear the kingdom out of the hand of Solomon and give you ten tribes, but He will have one tribe for the sake of My servant David and for the sake of Jerusalem, the city which I have chosen from all the tribes of Israel, because they have forsaken Me, and have worshipped Ashtoreth the goddess of the Sidonians, Chemosh the god of Moab, and Milcom the god of the sons of Ammon; and they have not walked in My ways, doing what is right in My sight and observing My statutes and My ordinances as his father David did. Nevertheless I will not take the whole kingdom out of his hand but I will make him ruler all the days of his life, for the sake of My servant David whom I chose, who observed My commandments and My statutes; but I will take the kingdom from his son’s hand and give it to you, even ten tribes. But to his son I will give one tribe, that My servant David may have a lamp always before Me in Jerusalem, the city where I have chosen to Myself to My name. I will take you, and you shall reign over whatever you desire, and you shall be king over Israel. Then it will be, that if you listen to all that I command you and walk in My ways, and do what is right in My sight by observing My statutes and My commandments, as My servant David did, then I will be with you and build you an enduring house as I built for David, and I will give Israel to you. Thus I will afflict the descendants of David for this, but not always.” (somehow Solomon found out about this encounter)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;Solomon sought therefore to put Jeroboam to death; but Jerobaom arose and fled to Egypt to Shishak king of Egypt, and he was in Egypt until the death of Solomon.’&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Rehoboam, Solomon's son, was about to ascend the throne, Jeroboam comes back to Israel to champion the rights of the people (the ones he used to oppress) but his motivation for doing so was not for the betterment of the people, but rather to see the nation split with him inheriting the ten northern tribes and himself sitting on a throne.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God made an enormous promise to Jeroboam if Jeroboam would be faithful to God’s Word and ways (remember that Jeroboam had zero claim to royalty, he was merely a privileged commoner);&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He would be king&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;His family line would become an enduring house&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;He would rule over whatever he desired&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This promise wasn’t a rejection of David’s line or the covenant God made with David to bring forth Messiah, but this was a promise to Jeroboam and his family line if he would lead the ten northern tribes righteously and lead them out of the idolatry that Solomon had allowed and endorsed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;So when the northern tribes broke from the southern, the Jewish people became two separate nations geographically (not ethnically) with Israel to the north and Judah to the south.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jeroboam knew that even though the people were entrenched in idol worship, they still held to the traditions of travelling to Jerusalem for feasts, festivals and sacrificial offerings at the Temple. To Jeroboam this was unacceptable because it might cause many of the people to want to rejoin to the house of David and see the nation reunited once again and, they might kill him for being a usurper to the throne, then he would have no throne at all. So to prevent this from happening, he first selected Shechem to be his capital and then he established two separate places for the people to visit to perform their religious sacrifices and rituals. Beth-el in the south and Dan in the north; in each place he erected a golden calf. He said to the people, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“It is too much for you to go up to Jerusalem; behold your gods, O Israel, that brought you up from the land of Egypt”.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;1 Kings 12:28-33.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;These are the same words spoken in the wilderness when Aaron made the original golden calf. Do you know what they called that calf? Elohim. The same name for God in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Gen 1:1&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The One True Living God. By erecting idols and naming them by the name of God Himself, the people could delude themselves into believing that they were worshipping God (Elohim) after all.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This also speaks to universalism today...all the world’s different religions do not worship the same God who simply goes by a different look or name, there is only one God and He will not share His glory with another.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jeroboam also established high places of pagan worship, he established a priesthood from all the tribes not just from the Levites, he established feasts for the people to follow on the same dates as the feasts being followed by their brethren in the south, but they were to pagan gods, and he simply made up the feasts from his own imagination. He essentially devised a religious program of worship that was focused on pagan deities but mimicked the ordinances that God had specified. He even took it upon himself to perform ceremonial acts that were restricted to the priests alone. &amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 12:28-33.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In fact, a man of God (prophet) from Judah travelled to Beth-el and called out against the pagan sacrifices being done there and Jeroboam stretched out his hand demanding that the prophet be seized and God made his hand shrivel up and he couldn’t withdraw it. The altar also split apart as the prophet had said would happen and Jeroboam asked him to pray to God for his healing...and God healed him! &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 13:1-6)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jeroboam’s wickedness was extreme, but it’s even more so because he had been privileged to have real encounters with God. The prophet Ahijah gave him a direct promise from God Himself; he knew God was real and when he knew his life was in danger from Solomon, he fled to Egypt to wait. What God said would happen, actually did happen in exquisite detail. All he had to do was obey God’s instructions – which he was well aware of – and God would have blessed him and his family line for generations to come. Jeroboam knew God was real when God crippled his hand publicly and then healed it just as publicly. He could have immediately repented, removed the golden calf idols and the high places of pagan worship. The nation would have prospered and the people would have come out of their idolatry and the house of David would have endured the judgement of God and been disciplined for Solomon’s rebellion and for leading the people to sin and at the right time, the nation would have been either reunited or at least been allies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Instead of trusting God whose Word and promise came true before his very eyes, he set in place an apostate, state sanctioned pagan religious system of his own devising and led the people that God had entrusted to him into deeper and even worse idolatry than Solomon had.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Instead of having his family line established for generations to come, God promised to cut off every male descendant and make a clean sweep of his entire house as one sweeps away dung until it’s all gone. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 14:10)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; God also promised that everyone of his descendants would never be buried; anyone from his line that died in the city was to be eaten by dogs and anyone of his descendants who died in a field would be eaten by birds. Only one child named Abijah, Jeroboam’s son would be buried because God said there was some good in him, and God took him at an early age. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 14:1-12)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jeroboam established the worst kind of paganism in Israel and it set the tone for all the kings who followed after him. In fact, every king who ascended the throne of the northern kingdom was evil, there was not one godly, righteous king who ever sat on that throne. The Northern Kingdom lasted approximately 212 years, from 934 to 722 BC.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This was not the case for the southern kingdom, they had mostly evil kings but a number of them were godly and righteous. The Southern Kingdom lasted approximately 348 years, from 934 to 586 BC, 136 years longer than her northern brethren. It’s amazing what a difference even a handful of righteous leaders will do for a nation’s future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;All men are without excuse when it comes to being accountable to God. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Romans 1:20 says, ‘For since the creation of the world His invisible attributes, His eternal power and divine nature, have been clearly seen, being understood through what has been made, so that they are without excuse.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;If God holds all men accountable simply by the creation alone, then Jeroboam who had heard the Word of God, had been directly spoken to by God through the prophet Ahijah, had seen God’s Word come to pass, been crippled by God and subsequently healed by God is most definitely without excuse for rejecting God.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We, who have multiple copies of God’s Word, who have heard God’s Word directly declared and proclaimed, who can look back through history and see that every Word of God has come to pass in incredible detail are even more accountable before God to obey Him. Remember that everyone and everything in the Bible is for our learning, so by looking at the life of Jeroboam, we can clearly see his sins and wickedness and how seriously God takes such things.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We have godly examples too and we can compare the Jeroboam’s of the Bible with the Daniel’s and Joseph’s and Paul’s of the Bible and see very clearly what and who God honours and what and who God condemns and judges.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy :-)&lt;/p&gt;",2012-05-21 05:37:12,mworby
6360,Home Group Notes - Rehoboam,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Rehoboam&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The name Rehoboam is a compilation of two elements; ‘rahab’ which means to be wide to indicate the dimensions of land or an object; ‘am’ meaning ‘a people’. So Rehoboam means ‘Enlarges The People’ or ‘The people are enlarged’. Ironically, his aggressive and self-indulgent behaviour had the opposite effect on the nation he ascended the throne to rule over.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Rehoboam was the son of Solomon and his wife Naamah who was an Ammonitess. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 14:21)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; It’s a curious thing that out of all his wives Solomon’s successor was the son of an Ammonite, who were the ancestors of Lot, (Abraham’s nephew) so they were distant relatives. Solomon’s favourite wife was an Egyptian, daughter of Pharaoh but, it’s unlikely his royal court or the people would have approved having an Egyptian sit upon their throne considering their past history of slavery and oppression at the hand of the Egyptians.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;To understand what situation Rehoboam inherited, we need to take a quick look back at Solomon; Solomon began well but became very impressed with himself and despite the gift of wisdom granted to him by God, he ignored God’s instructions to the future kings of Israel and he acquired wealth, political power and wives for himself. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(Deuteronomy 17:14-17)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; The latter (1000 of them) did not love and believe in Yahweh, instead they continued to worship their own false gods and Solomon permitted it and eventually joined them in their pagan worship and practices. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 11)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;God told Solomon in 1 King’s 11:9-13, ‘Now the Lord was angry with Solomon because his heart was turned away from the Lord, the God of Israel, who had appeared to him twice, and had commanded him concerned this thing, that he should not go after other gods; but he did not observe what the Lord had commanded. So the Lord said to Solomon, “Because you have done this, and you have not kept My covenant and My statutes, which I have commanded you, I will surely tear the kingdom from you and will give it to your servant. Nevertheless, I will not do it in your days for the sake of your father David, but I will tear it out of the hand of your son. However, I will not tear away all the kingdom but I will give one tribe to your son for the sake of my servant David and for the sake of Jerusalem which I have chosen.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Even when God is committed to disciplining His people when they rebelled, God STILL remains committed to His promises to His Word.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon had not only polluted the land with foreign pagan gods and idolatrous practices, but his ambition for building a magnificent capital and grand building projects led him to implement exorbitant taxes and levies which were a heavy burden on the people as well as enforcing forced labour.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s amazing that when men reject God, they quickly embrace the attitude that human beings are little more than a commodity to be used for selfish aggrandisement and are expendable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Solomon dies, Rehoboam is called to his coronation in the city of Shechem which was situated within the territory of the ten tribes outside the district of Judah and Benjamin where Jerusalem was situated. In this the majority of the tribes in the government of the nation believed they would have a good opportunity to be heard by the new king and have their concerns taken seriously.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Most think that Rehoboam was just a teenager or in his early 20’s when he came to the throne because he favoured the counsel of the young men he had grown up with. He was in fact 41 years of age and he should have had some inkling that there was unrest among the people because of the incredibly high taxation and servitude they lived under.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jereboam who had fled to Egypt during the reign of Solomon, came back when he heard Rehoboam was about to receive the throne and he became the mouthpiece for the majority of the people. The people’s request was a simple one....&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 12:4-5, ‘“Your father made our yoke hard; now therefore lighten the hard service of your father and his heavy yoke which he put on us and we will serve you.” Then he said to them, “Depart for three days, then return to me.” So the people departed.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Like all good monarch’s Rehoboam sought the counsel of the court elders who had served Solomon and they said to him in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 7, “If you will be a servant to this people today, and will serve them and grant them their petition, and speak good words to them, then they will be your servants forever.”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In all history, no king of any nation or people group has ever ruled as a servant for the betterment of the people except for Yeshua, the true King of Israel. This is the kind of servant leadership we who love Him are supposed to emulate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;But Rehoboam was raised, along with his cosseted friends, in a pampered and luxurious manner for which Solomon was world famous. If Rehoboam reduced the tax burden on the people, he would have to temper his lavish lifestyle – and so would his friends because his royal revenues would be much smaller.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The advice given to Rehoboam by his friends went like this in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 10, ‘The young men who grew up with him spoke to him saying, “Thus you shall say to this people who spoke to you saying, “Your father made our yoke heavy, now you make it lighter for us!” But you shall speak to them, “My little finger is thicker than my father’s loins! Whereas my father loaded you with a heavy yoke, I will add to your yoke; my father disciplined you with whips, but I will discipline you with scorpions.”’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;A good leader needs to be strong and firm, but abuse, threats and intimidation are not qualities that endear the faithfulness of those who are expected to follow.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The result was that Jeroboam led a revolt, the people followed him when he said in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;verse 16, “What portion do we have in David? We have no inheritance in the son of Jesse; to your tents O Israel! Now look after your own house David!” &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This was a knee-jerk reaction against the royal line because of what Solomon had established during his rule, it wasn’t an indication of hatred toward King David because the nation had experienced the golden era under David’s leadership, flawed as he was personally.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Only the men of Judah who were of the same tribe as the house of David remained under Rehoboam and this actually incorporated the tribe of Benjamin as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This sparked the separation of the nation of Israel. The Northern Kingdom retained the name Israel, which was made up of the other ten tribes and was ruled by Jeroboam who we’ll look at next week. The Southern Kingdom took the name of Judah because that was the primary tribe that remained true to the house of David.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Rehoboam did try to keep the nation from breaking apart, but when he sent Adoram, who was in charge of all those under forced labour, they stoned him to death and Rehoboam fled to Jerusalem and lost the unified nation from that time on.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Rehoboam then amassed an army of 180,000 men in a bid to crush the revolt, but God sent the prophet Shemaiah who told him not to go to war against his brethren, because it was God Himself who had ordained the separation of the nation – God had already told Solomon this punishment would come upon his son – and as a result, the proud, haughty and arrogant young man was humbled and subdued. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(1 Kings 12)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It’s from this time that the nation of Israel remained separated until the north was destroyed by the Assyrians, and later the south was destroyed and taken into captivity by the Babylonians...but the nation of Israel never again ruled as one sovereign nation until May 14, 1948 when the modern State of Israel was born, fulfilling many, many prophecies and proving God’s Word to be absolutely true and proving that God is committed to keeping His promises to national Israel. Not because they deserve it, but because &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;God is faithful to His own Word.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; Israel is a mere 64 years old and is stark evidence that God is real and His Word is perfectly true.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God’s promised judgement to tear the nation from Solomon because of his wilful disobedience and implementing pagan worship within the nation itself was assured and again, God’s Word proved true.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 12:15 says, ‘So the king did not listen to the people; for it was &lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;a turn of events from the Lord, that He might establish His word,&lt;/span&gt; which the Lord spoke through Ahijah the Shilonite to Jeroboam the son of Nebat.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Every man is accountable for his deeds and actions as was Rehoboam; he knew that the taxes and work load of forced labour on his own people was wrong, and God was completely right to ensure that Rehoboam would refuse to listen to them so that He could initiate punishment on Solomon’s line for his rebellion against God’s laws. God is sovereign and He is always right and just.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God knows the hearts of all individuals and what their behaviour’s and responses will be, therefore God determines where and when each individual will be born and this ensures that every Word He says comes to pass.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The assuring and comforting thing for us to recognise again is that what God has said He will do, &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;He will absolutely do. He will never compromise His Word and He will never break His promises, no matter who He made them to. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Shalom&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-wink.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Wink&quot; title=&quot;Wink&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-05-16 23:56:58,mworby
6078,Home Group Notes - Solomon,"&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Solomon&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: The name Solomon comes from the root word ‘shalem’ and is a derivative of the word ‘shalom’. Shalem means ‘complete and sound’ and the word shalom means peace in its broadest sense. So the combination of shalem and shalom means ‘Recompense, or fair penalty’.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;When Solomon was born, his father David named him Jedidiah after the prophet Nathan had came to him and told him that this child (Solomon) was loved by God, and the name Jedidiah means ‘Beloved of Yahweh’ or ‘Beloved of the Lord’. &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;(2 Samuel 12:25)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; No reason is given for why the name Jedidiah wasn’t used or why the name Solomon was used instead.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Looking at Solomon’s life from his attaining the throne with regard to his ability to dispense justice, he was unbelievably wise and dispensed justice in such a way that it stunned the masses and his fame spread throughout the then known world.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon was the 2&lt;sup&gt;nd&lt;/sup&gt; son to David and Bathsheba, almost everything we know about Solomon comes from the Biblical record. What’s really stunning is that archaeology confirms the Biblical record confirming its accuracy and trustworthiness.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are 5 things about Solomon that he is famous or infamous for.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;His wives and concubines&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;His wisdom beyond human capacity&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;His wealth and power beyond measure&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;The building of the Holy Temple&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;His apostasy in his elder years &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;You can read about the life of Solomon in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings and 2 Chronicles&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;His ascent to the throne was pretty shaky, David had promised Bathsheba that Solomon would succeed him, but before David died of old age, his son Adonijah declared himself king. Adonijah was David’s 4&lt;sup&gt;th&lt;/sup&gt; son and he claimed to be the rightful heir to the throne. When news was brought to David that Adonijah was usurping him and making a public declaration of taking the throne and declaring himself king, David ordered the priests to anoint Solomon as king at the Gihon Spring thus making Solomon the ruling monarch of Israel. Not the usual practice...usually, a king had to be dead before the successor was crowned. By making this move, David himself was declaring publicly and before God with the blessing of the priests that Solomon – not Adonijah – was the heir to the throne.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Once king, Solomon still had some opposition from within the military and the priesthood and from Adonijah himself, there was some subterfuge which Solomon very quickly put down. He also dealt with 2 long time enemies of king David.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The first – Joab – who had been very loyal to David, but wrongfully killed two men (Abner &amp;amp; Amasa) out of his own vengeful heart, he also killed David’s son Absalom after David repeatedly said he was to be kept alive, and he also sided with Adonijah’s bid for the throne...you see if Adonijah had became king and then died, Joab would have apparently been his successor. Joab didn’t know that David had already decided that Solomon would succeed to the throne after him.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The second – Shimei – the forefather of Mordecai whom we learned about last week. David’s mercy upon Shimei meant that Mordecai was born and was therefore in the right place with Esther to ensure that the Jews were saved when their annihilation order was set in motion under Haman during the rule of the Persian Empire. Shimei’s treason was eventually dealt with.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Abiather the priest also sided with Adonijah and Solomon had him banished. This meant that with these potential enemies gone, Solomon was able to ensure that his reign would be smooth and without internal attempts to either dethrone or murder him.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon was very young at the beginning of his rule, and in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Kings 3&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, he had a dream in which God Himself spoke to Solomon and said, &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Ask what you wish Me to give you.”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Can you imagine God asking any man that question? What would most men ask for? Solomon’s response was firstly to acknowledge that God had shown great kindness to his father David, and that God had been gracious to David by giving him a son to rule after him. This wasn’t an ego trip, because Solomon went on to say, I’m the son You gave to David but I’m like a little child in comparison. I don’t know anything about ruling a nation. All I really want is for You to give me an understanding heart to rule the people well and to be able to discern between good and evil.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God was so pleased with Solomon for seeking wisdom and righteous judgement from God instead of wealth, health, long life, possessions....that God said He would give all these to Solomon anyway...along with great wisdom and discernment.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Let’s look at the main things Solomon was known for....&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wives and concubines&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;For all Solomon’s wisdom, he showed a major flaw in his character and in his trust of God. Solomon was undoubtedly a womaniser, but most of his wives were for political expediency. He made a habit of marrying foreign wives in order to bring about political alliances with nations that might otherwise become enemies and Solomon didn’t want war with anyone.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;So instead of trusting God for the security of his nation, Solomon sought peace through marriage. But these marriages were in direct opposition to God’s instructions. We learned last week that in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;Deuteronomy 17&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, God said that future kings were not to accumulate wives. God was also very explicit that His people were not to marry foreign wives...why? Because foreign wives would entice them into idolatry, worshipping foreign gods.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon accumulated 700 wives and 300 concubines. If he had dinner with a different wife every night, he would have only seen each of them once every 2 years and 7 months!!!&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wisdom beyond human capacity&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There are many examples in the Scripture to demonstrate Solomon’s wisdom; one of the most extreme is the story of the 2 prostitutes who came to Solomon regarding the legal status of a baby boy. They had both had a baby each and in the night one mother rolled on top of her baby and killed it. She got up and swapped the babies over. When the other woman woke up, she realised that the baby in her bed was dead but also that it wasn’t hers.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;With no DNA testing in the time of Solomon, how could the king give a righteous judgement. He shocked them and the entire court by asking for a sword...he was going to cut the baby in two and give each of the woman half. The false mother was ok with this, while the real mother, who couldn’t bear for her child to die, wept and said she would willingly surrender her baby just so long as he wasn’t killed. The heart of a real mother would sacrifice herself and her rights to protect her child and Solomon knew exactly which woman was the rightful mother of the baby boy. The news of this spread throughout the nation.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon composed over 3000 proverbs and 1005 songs. He wrote the books of Song of Solomon, Proverbs and Ecclesiastes.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;His wisdom was so famous that the Queen of Sheba travelled from the southern region of Arabia. Arabia was rich in gold, frankincense and myrrh, among many other things that Solomon wanted to obtain, and the Queen of Sheba needed Solomon’s co-operation in marketing her country’s goods. She brought him many gifts and quizzed him with many questions and riddles and was astounded by his answers and responses.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Wealth and power beyond measure&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon’s national borders extended from the Euphrates River in the north to Egypt in the south. This means that in the days of Solomon, Israel’s borders reached into what is today southern Turkey, most of Syria &amp;nbsp;and about a 3&lt;sup&gt;rd&lt;/sup&gt; of Iraq and probably most of what we know as modern Jordan and down into the northern part of Saudi Arabia.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He owned 12,000 horses plus the horsemen who rode them and 1400 chariots. The ruins of Solomon’s famed stables are in Tel Megiddo and the stalls could house 450 horses. I’ve walked through them. (Again, accumulating horses is something &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Deuteronomy 17&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt; also prohibited) He established Israelite colonies around his provinces to look after military, administrative and commercial interests and he divided the nation into 12 districts with Judah constituting its own political unit with certain additional privileges.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The building of the Holy Temple&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;To build the Holy Temple Solomon began with a humungous amount of gold, silver and other materials that he’d inherited from his father. He got wood (cedar) from Lebanon, and had stone cut from quarries and once the cutting and carving was complete it was covered with pure gold.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;History tells us that the temple was so magnificent that when people first saw it, it would take their breath away. When the sun rose and set, the sun would reflect off the structure and it would look like it was on fire because of the shine upon the gold.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;He was also renown for other buildings as well. He spent 13 years building his own palace, the city wall, the citadel which was called the Millo, a palace for the daughter of Pharaoh who was one of his wives, obviously a favourite wife and many facilities for foreign traders. He built cities for chariots and horsemen and he build enormous storage cities. He extended Jerusalem to the north and fortified cities near the mountains of Judea and Jerusalem as well.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;He became apostate and didn’t live according to his own wisdom and the truth of God&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The saddest part of Solomon’s story is that he became apostate at the end. It hardly seems possible considering the gift of wisdom and discernment given to him by God in such great measure. In his latter years, after he had built magnificent structures, indulged his physical senses with every pleasure known to man, ate only the choicest foods and denied himself absolutely nothing, he was utterly dissatisfied. In Ecclesiastes he goes into great detail to list everything he ever did, every indulgence he granted himself and at the end of it all, he claimed it was nothing but vanity.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The real undoing of Solomon however was because of his many wives. It becomes seriously apparent why God says one wife and not a foreign wife. Without a constant loving family relationship with just one wife, each of his wives - hundreds of wives were left neglected, lonely, unloved, feeling they were nothing more than a convenience for political purposes – which is exactly what they were – feelings of jealousy between the favourites and the convenient ones, - they hardly ever saw him and it’s little wonder they wanted to continue in their pagan religions. With so many whinging wives, it’s no wonder Solomon capitulated and allowed them to establish pagan altars and shrines and places to practice their idolatry in public and when they invited him to participate with them, he willingly did so and the Bible says that it was his many foreign wives who turned the heart of Solomon to apostasy.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;This is a critically important lesson in why we are not to be unequally yolked or joined together...one will always pull the other away. If you’re already married to an unbeliever, pray and seek God for your spouse and be vigilant to keep your heart close to God through the power of God the Holy Spirit and the wisdom and guidance and power of the Word.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon - such a wise man – it is easily seen how a sinful human heart can be so easily corrupted. In order to gain more wealth, he imposed heavy taxes on his own people, he had the civilian population work as soldiers, officers and commanders of his chariots and cavalry. He granted special privileges to the tribe of Judah which alienated the remaining tribes and he never appears to repent in Scripture.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;For all intents and purposes, Solomon knew who the True and Living God was, he wanted God’s assistance and He acknowledged God’s faithfulness to his father David, he wanted to be a good ruler who was just but absolute power corrupts absolutely. He sought the benefits and the help and assistance from God, but never sought to love and know God as his father David had. That’s the difference. Solomon knew God was good to have around...David highest goal was to know and love and worship God.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Solomon was a sensual man who lived to indulge his every whim. He denied himself nothing and in order to gain even more than he had. He eventually gave his heart to idolatry and the punishment came when his son came to the throne after him and followed in his father’s footsteps and lost the nation completely. It split in two and all his son was left with was Judah and Benjamin ruling from Jerusalem.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;It just goes to show that the human heart can never be trusted no matter what gifts or blessings God gives.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jeremiah 17:9 says, ‘The heart is more deceitful than all else and is desperately sick; who can understand it?’&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Genesis 6:5 says, ‘Then the Lord saw that the wickedness of man was great on the earth and that every intent of the thoughts of his heart was only evil continually.’&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mark 7:21-23, Jesus said,&amp;nbsp; ‘For from within, out of the heart of men, proceed evil thoughts, fornications, thefts, murders, adulteries, deeds of coveting and wickedness, as well as deceit, sensuality, envy, slander, pride and foolishness. All these evil things proceed from within and defile the man.’ &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;So the lesson we learn from Solomon’s life is that blessing from God doesn’t mean relationship with God. Gifts from God don’t equal a relationship with God.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Here in our culture, we equate blessing, wealth, health, material possessions as being in good standing with God but it doesn’t mean that at all. In fact, having all these things can actually be a curse because they become the focus of our love and attention and desires and actually turn our heart away from God...they distract us and God becomes obsolete.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The problem is with the heart of man&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, we are utterly corrupt and it takes nothing less than the Spirit of God to transform us from being evil and unregenerate to being righteous and a brand new creature. When that supernatural event takes place when a person comes to a true and saving faith in Christ through repentance and faith, then the regeneration of the heart takes place and the transforming process commences.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Those who turn away – even if they appeared gifted and blessed and said and did all the right things – were never truly saved to begin with. It’s possible for people to be actively committed to a Christian ethos and church community and never really know Christ.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Corinthians 13:5, Paul said, ‘Test yourselves to see if you are in the faith; examine yourselves! Or do you not recognise this about yourselves; that Jesus Christ is in you, unless indeed you fail the test.’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;A sobering end to Home Group today but so very important that we do as Paul instructed and examine ourselves to see what the condition of our heart is really like. What are our desires? What do we love? Who do we live to please? What are our goals?&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Don’t measure your relationship with God by how blessed or gifted or how popular or clever you are or how busy and active you are in your local church family; Solomon was all those things and more and he failed the test. I would suggest that we measure our own lives by the life of Paul who was the greatest Christian, the greatest preacher/teacher and the greatest evangelist who ever lived...remember he even told Timothy to imitate him in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Timothy 3:10-12&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;There is too much at stake to simply assume that our relationship with God is hunky-dory because after all...we’re under grace...it’s all under the blood. Remember, the heart is ‘deceitful’ and it will lie to you. Measure your life against the Word of God and what it says a true believer looks, thinks, talks and behaves like, not what other people tell us a believer looks, thinks, talks and behaves like.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Shalom&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Mandy &lt;img src=&quot;http://www.vision.org.au/plugins/editors/jce/tiny_mce/plugins/emotions/img/smiley-wink.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Wink&quot; title=&quot;Wink&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;",2012-04-17 06:11:21,mworby
6021,Home Group Notes - David Pt 2,"&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;David Pt 2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;: Over the last couple of weeks we’ve been looking at the first half of King David’s life...that is, his life before he came to the throne. This week we’ll look at David’s life after he claimed the throne.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David’s story can be found in &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;1 Samuel 16 to the end of 1 Samuel, all of 2 Samuel, the first 2 chapters of 1 Kings and 1 Chronicles 2, 10-29.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Last week we concluded with David living in the wilderness with his personal army; he did very good things for his people and defended and protected them well. Even when he was living with the Philistines pretending to be an enemy of Israel who had defected, he never undermined his own people.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;When he heard the news that Saul and Jonathan were dead, he mourned for them greatly and never once did David bad-mouth or criticise Saul.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Initially, David became king of Judah (King of his own tribe) and Hebron becomes his capital for 7½ years and then David conquered Jerusalem and was publically anointed king over all Israel.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;There are far too many instances in David’s life to mention in our brief time for Home Group but we can look at a couple of very significant things about David’s life.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;He had too many wives.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;In &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;Deuteronomy 17:14-17&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; Moses prophesied to the people that when they entered the Promised Land they would demand a king to be like the other nations. God stipulated that all future kings were not allowed to accumulate horses for themselves (power) or gold and silver (personal wealth) or wives (immorality and compromise).&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David had 8 named wives in the Scripture: Michal, Ahinoam, Abigail, Maachah, Haggith, Abital, Eglah, Bathsheba. It’s believed that there were more who were not named, but we know for certain he had 8 wives.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David had 5 children by Bathsheba, the first died. He had 16 children born from his other wives and concubines.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;This penchant for women set a seriously dangerous precedent as we’ll see when we look at Solomon, and it was in direct contrast to God’s Word. David loved God...so why did God allow David to have multiple wives?&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;We human beings are always ready to point the finger at God and accuse Him of being a dictator, or a kill-joy, or of wanting to control and manipulate people; that He’s so restrictive and says everything we want to do will lead to sin, but we never think it will happen t us!&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;God said not to accumulate wives or wealth...how would we know what the consequences are if no one ever accumulated wives and wealth. God sets the standard and then allows men to make their decisions and then we can see that God was right all the time. His standards and rules are good and are in place for our benefit. When we ignore God, there are consequences and we can’t say that God is unfair for allowing these things to happen...He has already warned us what is right and wrong. If He doesn’t allow us to choose what we want to do, men call Him a dictator...if He does allow us to choose, men call Him unloving because He didn’t stop disaster from taking place.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David was a man who loved God right down to the very depths of his heart and look at the turmoil that came into his life because of his desire for women...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Too many siblings and too many wives breeds competition...who is the favourite wife and who are the favourite children. (Rachel and Leah are also good examples of this and then of course Joseph was Jacob’s favourite son by Rachel and look what happened to him)&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Then there was incest and rape between his son Amnon against his half-sister Tamar. Then his son Absalom plotted against and murdered his half brother Amnon for raping his sister Tamar and then had to live in exile. After he was allowed back to the city, he then plotted the overthrow of his own father’s throne. When David was close to death, his Adonijah tried to take the throne also despite the fact that David had already declared Solomon would be his successor.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;His adultery with Bathsheba lead to the death of his first child with her, not to mention that he contrived to make her husband Uriah think the child she was carrying was his and when that doesn’t work (because Uriah was more faithful than David), rather than confess his sin David arranged for Uriah’s murder.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David did accumulate wealth but admittedly, he donated humungous amounts toward the building and construction costs of the Temple that Solomon would build. But he had enormous wealth left over for his heirs.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David did many good things and in most ways, he was a very good man and a good king, but he also did many wicked and self-indulgent things. When you compare David to Saul, you see two very different men.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;It appears that Saul had one wife and one concubine. He had 6 children with his wife and 3 children with his concubine. While he gathered the most skilled men around him, it doesn’t appear that he went out of his way to accumulate wealth.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;The real difference between Saul and David however, was that while David appeared to be a bigger sinner than Saul, David’s heart was quick to be contrite, he was always quick to admit and confess his sin, he always felt remorse and sorrow for his sin.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Even when Nathan the prophet told him the story of the poor man and the rich man who took his only sheep from him so he didn’t have to kill any of his own many sheep, David was incensed at the injustice of it and was immediately remorseful when Nathan said to him &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;“You are the man!” (2 Samuel 12:7)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;, he was in fact talking about him and his sin with Bathsheba and the murder of Uriah.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;There is another important incident that happened in David’s life and emphasises the principle of ‘consequences’.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Not only did David’s sin bring shocking and painful consequences into his own family, but there are good consequences from some of David’s choices as well.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;For example, in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Samuel 16&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, when Absalom attempted to overthrow David and take the throne for himself, David and his entire court – with the exception of a few to maintain things in the palace – left Jerusalem to find security and on the way they encountered a man named Shimei and Shimei came out cursing David, calling him names. Shimei was a descendant of Saul.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;When the security men around David heard these insults against their king, they wanted to kill Shimei for his treasonous behaviour but David wouldn’t let them. David noted the sovereignty of God in all situations and extended mercy to Shimei.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;Do you know who was a descendent of Shimei? None other than Mordechai, the cousin of Queen Esther. How important was Mordechai to the unfolding events in Ancient Persia when Esther was made Queen and their people were about to be slaughtered because of evil Haman? We mentioned when we talked about King Saul’s disobedience in not killing king Agag of the Amalekites and the fact that it resulted in the birth of Haman.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;If Saul had been obedient, Haman would never have been born. But if David hadn’t been merciful, Mordechai would never have been born. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;The two most important things I’ve learned from David’s life (and there are vastly more than 2) is that every action has a consequence and those consequences can have far reaching effects on many, many people. David’s sins of immorality impacted his family tragically and they never recovered. Also, in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;2 Samuel 24&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, when David numbered the people, the consequence was a pestilence that killed 70,000 people throughout the land.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;In contrast, David’s abundant and enthusiastic worship and adoration of God publically brought great blessing and favour on David, the people and the land as well as incredible success against his enemies because of God’s Spirit being with him.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David’s mercy and faithfulness to Saul, despite being constantly on the run and living under constant threat of death, brought about the enduring line of David eventuating with Messiah.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David’s mercy toward Shimei resulted in the birth of Mordechai who along with Esther, brought deliverance of the Jewish people in Ancient Persia when they were threatened with annihilation.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;The second really important lesson of King David’s life is that he was ALWAYS quick to confess his sin, admit his guilt and repent. Unlike Saul who constantly tried to squirm out of taking responsibility or blaming others for his sin, David would immediately confess and fall on the mercy of God.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;David was far from perfect, in fact David was a very great sinner, and yet David’s rule is known as the Golden Age of Ancient Israel...this is stunning when you consider the depravity within David’s own household and the anarchy that impacted the throne and the royal court.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;But because David’s heart was always to please God despite his own failings and failures, God promised again and again that David’s line would endure for all time, and that through David’s line, the Messiah of the whole world would come from him.&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;In a nutshell, to be like David – a man with a heart after God’s own heart – we need to pursue the following attributes:-&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Be quick to confess and admit our sin and repent&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Be quick to extend mercy, grace and forgiveness&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Be slow to dish out vengeance and retribution&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Remember that every single action we take has a consequence for both good and bad&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cultivate a heart that desires to please God above all else.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Shalom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Mandy&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;",2012-04-12 00:00:41,mworby
5862,Home Group Notes - David Pt 1,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;David Pt 1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;: In all the Bible, there is only one person who goes by the name David and the meaning of this word is quite long and complex because its Hebrew roots are complex. It can mean ‘beloved’ or ‘uncle’, and a derivative also means infirmity, sick or unclean, although these last meanings are somewhat unfounded and not part of the original meanings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;David was known as Israel’s ‘beloved’ king, which would validate the initial meaning of this name, but his life was consistently marred with grief and drama. He personally was vilified, accused of treason, was hunted like an animal and had his life threatened numerous times. Because of his sin his family was tainted with immorality, murder, incest and rape, treason and betrayal. So beloved and sick or unclean are both very good adjectives that apply to David.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;We’ll look at David’s life next week as well but this week we’ll look at his life prior to becoming king, and look at only a few situations. To get the full picture of David’s life, what he did and who he interacted will you can read his story beginning in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Samuel 16 to the end of 1 Samuel, all of 2 Samuel, the first 2 chapters of 1 Kings&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;and 1 Chronicles 2, 10-29.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In short, David began his life as a humble, faithful and unassuming young man. He was the youngest of 8 sons, he was a good looking young guy but being the youngest he had no social standing or influence. He was not the heir to his father’s estate and therefore, he was not wealthy. He was a young shepherd boy who spent his time out in the fields looking after the flocks of his father Jesse.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Samuel came to town one day and is directed by God to the house of Jesse and promptly tells this man that God has chosen one of his sons to be the next king of Israel. Jesse presents his eldest son to Samuel...and subsequently each of his other sons from eldest to youngest...however, David was of such insignificant position within the family that he wasn’t even mentioned. It’s as if he didn’t exist.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Samuel is puzzled, he knows God has told him to anoint one of Jesse’s sons, they’re strong, powerfully built, having all the&lt;/p&gt;
",2012-03-27 05:48:07,mworby
5814,Home Group Notes - Saul Pt 2,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;King Saul Pt 2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Picking up from last week where we learned that in the very first early years of Saul’s monarchy he wasn’t so bad, he wasn’t great but he wasn’t full of himself...yet. His fall from reality and humility came pretty quickly however...after his first victory over the Amorites his decline was quite quick and steep.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;First battle against the Philistines&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Samuel 13&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; we read about the Philistines gathering for battle against Israel and many of the Israelites were terrified of this formidable foe. The Philistines were particularly barbaric and cruel and Israel had no real weaponry for defence and a host of Jews fled and hid themselves. The Philistines had 30,000 chariots, 6,000 horsemen and soldiers in number like the sand on the seashore...to an unarmed people they were terrifying. Saul and his son Jonathan however managed to gather 3000 men to fight with them and Saul was feeling the pressure of leading this tiny band of men into battle against impossible odds...he needed to hear from God. He had contacted Samuel and received word back to wait for the Prophet’s arrival which would be in 7 days time, at which point Samuel would offer the burnt offering and then receive instruction from God as to how they were to proceed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Verses 8-11 says, ‘Now he waited seven days, according to the appointed time set by Samuel, but Samuel did not come to Gilgal; and the people were scattering from him. So Saul said, “Bring to me the burnt offering and the peace offerings.” And he offered the burnt offering. As soon as he finished offering the burnt offering behold, Samuel came; and Saul went out to meet him and to greet him. But Samuel said, “What have you done?”.....’&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;God’s rules for the monarchy and the priesthood and for prophets were very different and the role of priest and king were not allowed to cross over. Kings were not allowed to perform the rituals of priests and priests were not allowed to assume&lt;/p&gt;
