5757,Home Group Notes - Saul Pt 1,"&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;King Saul Pt 1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #000000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;text-decoration: underline;&quot;&gt;Saul&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/span&gt; The Hebrew pronunciation is Sha'ul and comes from the verb sha’el which means to ask, inquire, borrow or beg. Many godly men throughout the Scriptures ‘inquired’ of the Lord, but Saul showed his weak and shallow character when he tried to contact the Prophet Samuel after the prophets death, through the witch of Endor, begging Samuel to give him guidance because God was against him and gave him no direction at all. Most Bible helps believe the name Saul simply means ‘prayed for’ or ‘asked for’ however there is a little more depth to this name.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;For all intents and purposes, Saul wasn’t such a bad guy in his early years and there’s a lot in the Bible about him that we can learn. This week we're looking at the first half and we'll look at the second half of Saul’s life next week.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The life story of Saul begins in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Samuel 9&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and goes through to &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;chapter 31&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Samuel speaks to the people and in essense says, ok, you want a king over you to be like the rest of the nations....he gives them a rebuking lecture about the fact that they already have a KING...God is their king...and they’re rejecting God in preference to a human king and God was actually very angry about it. In fact, God was so angry, that in &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;13:16-18&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; at Samuel’s word, God sent thunder and rain – totally out of season - to show how angry He was and the people were really frightened. The people responded with repentance and God said they could still have their human king but that they were to remain faithful to Him and God would continue to lead them through a human king so long as they and their king served Him.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;In &lt;span style=&quot;color: #ff0000;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;1 Sam 9&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, we first learn about Saul. He was of the tribe of Benjamin, his father’s name was Kish – who was reasonably wealthy...he had servants and livestock which equated to wealth and substance in those days - and Kish sent Saul and his&lt;/p&gt;
